<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jay Jacobs Prepares for Liquidation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Jay Jacobs Inc., a clothing retailer that tried  
to shift its focus from teen-agers to young professionals after a 
brush with bankruptcy in the mid-1990s, is preparing to go out of 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	The 58-year-old company filed a Chapter 11 petition Friday and  
asked U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Thomas T. Glover to grant authority for 
liquidation of inventory and termination of Rex Loren Steffey as 
president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Following liquidation, ``it currently is contemplated that the  
leases for its 114 stores in 22 states will either be rejected or 
assigned and store employees will be laid off,'' a company 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The release said 54 employees at corporate headquarters and the  
Jay Jacobs distribution center were laid off Aug. 27. As of July 
31, the company had about 1,500 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1941, the company became a leader in teen fashion in  
the 1960s and '70s. At its zenith in the 1980s, the chain included 
nearly 300 stores nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Beset by growing competition and expansion costs, Jay Jacobs  
filed for reorganization in a Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing in May 
1994. Steffey was hired late that year and the company emerged in 
October 1995 with 153 stores and a new focus on clothing for 
professionals 18 to 34 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales failed to rebound and more stores were closed. Founder Jay  
Jacobs resigned as chairman in June 1997 and from the board that 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	In December 1997 a bankruptcy judge approved a recapitalization  
as a modification to the reorganization plan, but the statement 
said the company has been short of cash since last October. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
