<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 18:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thrashers Sign Top Pick Stefan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Thrashers are complete for their  
first training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion team signed center Patrik Stefan to a three-year  
contract Friday, ensuring the NHL's top draft pick would be on hand 
for the start of camp in Orlando, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Stefan, who turns 19 on Sept. 16, will receive a total of $3.075  
million in base salary over the three years -- the maximum allowed 
for a rookie under the league's collective bargaining agreement -- 
but the deal was held up by the value of potential bonuses in the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something I was pretty nervous about,'' said Stefan, who  
arrived in Orlando about 6 p.m. on a flight from the Los Angeles 
area. ``But it's done now. It's great to be here. I'm excited and 
everything is perfect. I can't wait to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither side would disclose the bonus structure, but Stefan's  
agent, Steve Kotlowitz, was looking to exceed the potentially 
most-lucrative rookie package, currently held by Tampa Bay's 
Vincent Lecavalier. 
</P>
<P>
	Lecavalier can earn up to $3 million annually in bonuses or $8  
million over the life of his three-year deal for reaching targets 
in games played, goals, assists, points, points per game and 
plus-minus rating. 
</P>
<P>
	After weeks of negotiations, Kotlowitz and Thrashers general  
manager Don Waddell finally agreed on the bonuses Thursday night 
and finalized the deal Friday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patrik has the potential to be an elite player in the NHL and  
having him in camp is an important part of his development,'' 
Waddell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stefan arrived in time for a team meeting Friday night. The  
Thrashers will take the ice for the first time Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very important for him to be there,'' Kotlowitz said in  
a telephone interview from his office in Edmonton, Alberta. ``He's 
very much looking forward to being part of the Atlanta Thrashers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers traded up to land Stefan with the top pick in the  
draft. The 6-foot-2, 205-pounder played last season with Long Beach 
in the International Hockey League, totaling 11 goals and 24 
assists in 33 games. His playing time was limited by a pair of 
concussions, but Atlanta officials insist that his health is fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Stefan should make the Thrashers' 23-man roster but the team is  
hoping to bring him along slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not too concerned with Patrik Stefan this year or next  
year,'' Waddell said. ``We want to bring him along right. I'm more 
concerned with where he is four or five years from now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, Atlanta agreed to a deal with its only other  
unsigned player, goalie Scott Langkow. The 24-year-old, who spent 
all but one game last season in the minors, is expected to provide 
minor-league insurance behind Damian Rhodes and Norm Maracle. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 65 players at training camp.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
