<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises With Stocks, Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar staged a broad, sharp advance Friday,  
following the course of U.S. stocks and bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	A report of less-than-expected increases in wages and new jobs  
in the United States dampened inflation jitters and bolstered 
American markets. The dollar benefited as investments poured into 
the rising American markets before the three-day Labor Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 110.05 Japanese yen in late New York from  
109.11 yen Thursday, when it was at a seven-month low. The dollar's 
gains also undercut the euro, which fell to $1.0612 from $1.0686, 
and the British pound, which dropped to $1.6026 from $1.6067. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar had been under pressure in recent trading as  
economies overseas begin showing new signs of strength and 
inflation fears rose in the United States. As U.S. stocks and bonds 
slumped earlier this week, there were fears that investors would 
dump dollars as they unloaded American securities. 
</P>
<P>
	But an unemployment report of only a modest rise in wages and a  
smaller-than-expected rise in the number of new jobs calmed fears 
that a 4.2 percent jobless rate -- the lowest in 29 years -- was 
rekindling inflation. In Friday's rally, the Dow Jones industrial 
average shot up 2.2 percent and the Nasdaq composite index surged 
almost 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the gains in U.S. financial markets Friday on the  
brighter inflation outlook did not remove the long-term questions 
about the dollar, however. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also rose to 1.5067 Swiss francs from 1.4936, but  
slipped to 1.4921 Canadian dollars from 1.4952. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8433 German 
marks, up from 1.8301; 6.1819 French francs, up from 6.1379; and 
1,824.80 Italian lire, up from 1,811.80. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
