<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Donates Kidney to Stranger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Several transplant centers turned down a  
50-year-old woman's offer to donate one of her kidneys to a 
stranger in need before a hospital here agreed to the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman endured surgery and a battery of physical and  
psychological tests at the University of Minnesota's hospital 
simply because she knew there was a long waiting list for organs. 
</P>
<P>
	The donor was ``purely motivated by altruism,'' said Cheryl  
Jacobs, a social worker who took part in the psychological 
screening of the woman. Hospital officials said they were 
convinced, after intense psychological and physical screening, that 
she made the offer for the right reasons and knew the risks. 
</P>
<P>
	The donor and the recipient both asked to keep their identities  
secret, even from each other. 
</P>
<P>
	The transplant took place in early August but wasn't disclosed  
until Thursday, after the patients had left the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Transplanted kidneys generally come from a cadaver or a living  
relative. Transplant programs have been reluctant to accept kidney 
donations from living strangers for several reasons, including 
concern about exposing the donor to the risks of surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical risks to the donor are considered quite low, although in  
this case, the donor had to spend three to four days in the 
hospital, and up to six weeks at home recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	``Living, unrelated transplantation is growing in the United  
States,'' said Dr. William Bennett, president of the American 
Society of Nephrology. ``It was always felt before, why use a 
living patient when you could use a cadaver donor? But it turns out 
the fact that the donor is living confers some advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Arthur Matas, who performed the transplant, published a  
study in 1992 in The Lancet, a British medical journal, that found 
that people who live with one kidney after donating the other are 
not at increased risk of suffering from kidney failure or 
hypertension. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42,000 people on the kidney transplant waiting list now have  
to wait between three and five years for a new organ. Two decades 
ago, the wait was only about a year. 
</P>
<P>
	For that reason, doctors have been discussing the ethical issues  
surrounding unrelated transplants for years. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital is approached about a half-dozen times a month by  
people asking if they can donate kidneys, but until recently, there 
was no system to screen the callers, identify their true motives 
and put their kidney into a pool for recipients. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
