<DOCNO> APW19990903.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 11:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dennis Still Menaces N.C. Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- Like the fictional character of the same  
name, Dennis won't leave his neighbors alone and is making a mess 
of the yard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Wilson says: Go Home Dennis the Menace,'' proclaimed a  
sign at one restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents up and down North Carolina's Outer Banks expressed  
similar sentiments. The only people apparently happy with the storm 
were two surfers spotted Thursday afternoon floating on their 
boards off the beach village of Frisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Stiff wind gusting up to 60 mph, showers and 14-foot waves  
assaulted the state's northern coast for a fifth day today. Road 
crews worked to clean up the mess Dennis made. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis first battered the North Carolina shoreline as a  
hurricane on Monday, then headed out to sea and weakened. But 
within a day, it was backtracking toward the Outer Banks, this time 
downgraded to a tropical storm. 
</P>
<P>
	By this afternoon, the storm was about 190 miles south-southeast  
of Cape Hatteras. The storm was drifting erratically, with maximum 
sustained wind around the core of 60 mph. Forecasters believe 
Dennis will begin moving slowly to the west by Saturday. There is a 
chance it could come ashore Sunday or Monday, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Erosion experts compared Dennis to a nor'easter, the winter  
storm that does not pack a hurricane's wallop but stays longer, 
making it worse for beaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is that beaches along the Outer Banks were already  
in bad shape to begin with,'' said Bill Cleary, who studies barrier 
islands at the University of North Carolina, Wilmington. ``Over the 
past 25 years, these beaches have been hit by several hundred 
nor'easters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the Outer Banks -- a thin, 130-mile strand of barrier islands  
-- the storm wreaked havoc on Hatteras Island's lifeline, N.C. 12, 
ripping out some sections of road and heaping chest-deep beach sand 
on others. At a quarter-mile neck of Hatteras Island just north of 
Buxton, Dennis created a trench cutting the island in half, then 
filled it in with sand. 
</P>
<P>
	Battered N.C. 12 was opened to islanders in four-wheel-drive  
vehicles, but it may be days before regular traffic is permitted on 
the island. The stretch near Buxton where the ocean cut through can 
be drive across only at low tide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Highway 12 is now passable,'' state public safety Secretary  
Richard Moore said today. ``The roadbed, or parts of the roadbed, 
are there for people who know what they are doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dare County Sheriff Bert Austin, trapped at his home on Hatteras  
all week, said tourists will be able to leave the island with their 
cars later today when the ferry to Ocracoke and the mainland 
reopens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to some people from Pennsylvania who have been here  
14 days on their summer vacation,'' Austin said today. ``They've 
been very patient, but they're ready to roll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the islanders plan to stay, he said. ``I don't think you  
could tear them out chained to a bulldozer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Department of Transportation called in 181 pieces of  
equipment, 200 employees and 200 prisoners to clean sand and 
debris. 
</P>
<P>
	Trucker Andrew Hoffman, who left his home in Salvo on Sunday to  
make deliveries as far away as Pennsylvania, waited in Manteo for 
word that he could go back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to get home and see what happened,'' Hoffman said.  
``The not knowing is rough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An evacuation order for neighborhoods in Nags Head, Kitty Hawk  
and Kill Devil Hills north of Hatteras Island was lifted this 
morning. Visitors were welcome in the beach towns over the Labor 
Day weekend but they should confirm reservations first. 
</P>
<P>
	While waiting for commercial deliveries to resume, islanders  
have been supplied with emergency food, water and repair materials 
by helicopters and convoys of National Guard vehicles racing to 
avoid high tide. 
</P>
<P>
	Power and water service had been restored to much of the island  
by Thursday, but phones still were down. 
</P>
<P>
	Electric power also was restored on Ocracoke Island, which had  
operated for days on generator power, and a ferry loaded with heavy 
equipment left Cedar Island on Thursday to begin clearing roads 
there, said state Public Safety Secretary Richard Moore. He said 
another ferry bearing a fuel truck and food would head there later. 
</P>
<P>
	On Hatteras Island, steep escarpments were seen along the beach  
in front of houses washed under by waves and along deserted 
stretches of Cape Hatteras National Seashore 
</P>
<P>
	The erosion caved in a swimming pool at a beachfront motel and  
also claimed five houses in the village of Rodanthe and one in 
Kitty Hawk, where others showed signs of being undermined. Scores 
more houses were left with waves washing under them and dangling 
decks and steps. 








  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
