<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of the Unemployment Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The nation's unemployment rate inched down to 4.2 percent in  
August, returning to a 29-year low and helping some workers who 
historically have had a harder time finding jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The rate of unemployed blacks fell to 7.8 percent from July's  
8.8 percent. The August rate still was more than double the 3.7 
percent rate for whites, the Labor Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the unemployment rate for Hispanics crept up to 6.5  
percent in August from 6.2 percent in July, Labor Secretary Alexis 
Herman said unemployment rates for Hispanics as well as blacks are 
near record lows. 
</P>
<P>
	The black unemployment rate hit a record low of 7.3 percent in  
June, and Hispanic unemployment was at a record low rate of 5.8 
percent in March. 
</P>
<P>
	In other details:  
</P>
<P>
	--The unemployment rate for whites remained unchanged at 3.7  
percent, the same rate as in July. 
</P>
<P>
	--The jobless rate for adult women fell to 3.7 percent from 4  
percent, while the rate for adult men rose slightly to 3.6 percent 
from 3.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--The rate of unemployed teen-agers climbed to 13.5 percent from  
12.7 percent, as many left summer jobs to return to school. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
