<HEADLINE> Soybeans Rise on Crop Outlook / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures jumped higher early today on the  
Chicago Board of Trade after private forecasts suggested the crop 
will be smaller than official reports estimate. Grain futures also 
were slightly higher. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the fourth straight day that soybeans headed upward,  
although gains were expected to be limited amid profit-taking ahead 
of the three-day Labor Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharp gains early were in response to an estimate the previous  
day by Farmers Commodities Corp. of Des Moines, Iowa, that pegged 
the 1999-2000 soybean crop at 2.736 billion bushels. That fell well 
shy of the Department of Agriculture's August forecast of 2.87 
billion bushels. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn opened slightly higher before turning mixed amid light  
profit-taking in advance of the holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also opened higher but hit resistance because of U.S.  
spring wheat harvest delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1/4 cent to $2.71 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1/4 cent to $2.22 1/4 a bushel; December oats rose 1/2 
cent to $1.16 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 3/4 cents to $4.97 1/4 
a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were slightly higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .18 cent to 66.85 cents a bushel;  
October feeder cattle rose .03 cent to 79.15 cents a bushel; 
October lean hogs fell .85 cent to 46.20 cents a bushel; February 
pork bellies fell 2.57 cents to 54.75 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
