<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Asks Review of Twins Antitrust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- State Attorney General Mike Hatch this  
morning asked the U.S. Supreme Court to review a state Supreme 
Court decision which held that the Minnesota Twins were exempt from 
antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``Organized baseball, unlike any other sport or industry, claims  
to have a complete and blanket exemption from antitrust laws,'' 
Hatch said in a statement. ``The state of Minnesota believes it has 
the right to look at professional baseball to see if they have 
violated antitrust laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court's ruling in April temporarily ended a  
state investigation into whether baseball officials conspired to 
get public money for a ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said neither the Twins nor major league baseball could  
be forced to comply with an investigation begun by former Attorney 
General Hubert Humphrey III and continued by Hatch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is important to pursue the possibility that the independent  
owners of baseball may be threatening to boycott communities which 
do not increase public subsidies for ballparks,'' Hatch said in the 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Humphrey had asked for papers going back to 1959 to determine  
whether baseball officials illegally conspired by threatening to 
move franchises. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins and the league argued that their conduct was exempt  
from state and federal antitrust laws because the U.S. Supreme 
Court has held that the business of professional baseball was 
exempt. The state Supreme Court followed that decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We conclude that the sale and relocation of a baseball  
franchise ... is an integral part of the business of professional 
baseball and falls within the exemption,'' Justice Paul H. Anderson 
wrote in the Minnesota Supreme Court's unanimous decision in April. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote that the exemption ``may be an aberration'' carved out  
by the U.S. Supreme Court, but the nation's highest court should 
retain the exclusive privilege of overruling its own decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Humphrey began the investigation in December 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	A Ramsey County judge last year ordered the team to comply with  
the investigation, but only as far back as 1992. The judge stayed 
the order while the Twins' appeal was pending. 
</P>
<P>
	The order covered all documents related to revenue sharing,  
potential relocation and sale of major league baseball teams, and 
the construction and methods for obtaining new ballparks in 
Minnesota and elsewhere. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
