<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Wanted U.S. Fugitive Is Nabbed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- After more than a decade of freedom in Central  
America, the No. 1 fugitive on the U.S. Marshal Service's ``15 Most 
Wanted'' list was arrested at an Atlanta airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Paul Zink, a fugitive since 1988, will stand trial in  
Wisconsin on charges of running a large cocaine ring there. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested Thursday as he stepped off a plane at Hartsfield  
International Airport under the guard of State Department 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Zink, 43, was arrested in Guatemala in February, but officials  
there refused to extradite him to the U.S. to face drug charges. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Guatemalan immigration officials expelled Zink as  
an ``undesirable person,'' said Robert McMichael, U.S. Marshal for 
the Northern District of Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Guatemalan officials, working with representatives from the U.S.  
State Department, put Zink on a flight Thursday morning. State 
Department officials then guarded him on the flight, McMichael 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Zink was No. 1 on the U.S. Marshal's list because of the length  
of time he was a fugitive and because he was considered dangerous, 
McMichael said. 
</P>
<P>
	Zink had been arrested before for homicide, attempted murder and  
weapons and drug possession, but the Marshal Service said on 
Thursday it didn't know if he had been convicted or served time in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to federal charges of conspiracy to distribute  
cocaine, Zink also was wanted on murder-solicitation charges in 
Kenosha County, Wis., for allegedly hiring a gunman to kill a 
police informant in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Zink had family in Guatemala and was found working as a  
freelance guide, providing tours of Mayan ruins under the name 
Marcos Potts. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Zink used his brother's vital statistics to  
obtain a passport to leave the United States. His brother, Kevin, 
was convicted in 1990 of assisting his flight. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 22:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cookies Recalled Over Nut Allergy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A labeling error that could result in serious,  
even life-threatening, repercussions to people allergic to nuts is 
prompting a Canadian company to recall certain bags of Sensational 
Gourmet chocolate chip cookies sold in 10 states. 
</P>
<P>
	The cookies may contain pecans, although they are not listed as  
an ingredient. People allergic to nuts should not eat the recalled 
cookies, but return them to the place of purchase for a refund. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled cookies are in 12-ounce bags marked with the codes  
``Best By Feb. 24 OOD'' or ``Best By Feb. 24 OOE.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colonial Cookies of Kitchener, Ontario, said Friday they were  
sold in grocery and convenience stores in Connecticut, Maryland, 
Massachusetts, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Rhode 
Island, Virginia and West Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	A Connecticut child had a mild allergic reaction, prompting  
Colonial Cookies to suspect some of its cookies with pecans may 
have been mixed up in packaging with the chocolate chip variety. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers with questions may call 1-800-265-6508, ext. 311.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
