<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Friday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
 *Coca-Cola Co., down 2 1/8 at 57 3/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta-based soft-drink giant warned that its third-quarter  
earnings will fall short of Wall Street forecasts because of weak 
beverage sales in Asia and South America. Coke predicted earnings 
per share will be 34 cents to 35 cents in the quarter, compared to 
analysts' expectations of 36 cents. The earnings estimate excludes 
the impact of a product recall in Europe, which will reduce 
earnings for the quarter by an additional 2 cents to 3 cents a 
share. 

</P>
<P>
 *National Discount Brokers Group Inc., down 5 1/2 at 25 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The Jersey City, N.J.-based financial services company expects  
first-quarter results from continuing operations to be between a 
loss of 1 cent a share to earnings of 2 cents. Wall Street analysts 
had expected the company to earn 21 to 22 cents a share. 

</P>
<P>
 *Pillowtex Corp., down 13/16 at 9 1/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The manufacturer of home furnishings expects to report earnings  
of between 25 and 30 cents a share in the third quarter, and 
between 50 and 55 cents a share in the fourth quarter. Wall Street 
analysts had expected the company to earn 81 cents in the third 
quarter and 79 cents in the fourth quarter. 

</P>
<P>
 *National Westminster Bank PLC, down 7 at 112    	
</P>
<P>
	Britain's third-largest bank is negotiating to buy life  
insurance and pension provider Legal and General Group PLC. Neither 
company provided any details, but The Financial Times reported 
Natwest would pay 10.75 billion pounds ($17 billion) in a deal that 
mixed cash and stock. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Quintiles Transnational Corp., up 2 3/4 at 37 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The pharmaceutical product development company will replace King  
World Productions Inc. in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Health Care 
Industry Group, effective after the close of trading on Sept. 7. 

</P>
<P>
 *Play-By-Play Toys &AMP; Novelties Inc., up 1 13/16 at 6 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	Shares of the San Antonio-based toy manufacturer rose sharply  
for the second straight day on news that the company said it had 
been awarded licensing rights to the popular Pokemon cartoon 
character. Play-By-Play expects to begin shipping Pokemon 
merchandise to the amusement market in the early spring. 

</P>
<P>
 *AutoCyte Inc., up 2 1/16 at 6 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Aetna Inc., the nation's largest health insurer, agreed to cover  
a new type of Pap smear test, which federal officials in 1996 said 
was more effective in detecting early signs of cervical cancer. One 
of the tests is Prep, made by AutoCyte. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
