<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets ended lower Friday on  
worries over another rise in U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue chip Hang Seng Index fell 189.25 points,  
or 1.4 percent, closing at 13,178.31. On Thursday, the index had 
lost 176.63 points, or 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said investors were cautious ahead of the release later  
Friday in the United States of unemployment data, which could 
provide clues about whether there would be another increase of U.S. 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, U.S. stocks fell because of worries over inflation  
and interest rates. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial 
average lost 94.67 points to close at 10,843.21. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average slipped  
1.26 points, or 0.01 percent, to close the day's trading at 
17,629.99 points. On Thursday, the average closed down 171.23 
points, or 0.96 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading in Tokyo was listless, with investors wary of taking new  
positions ahead of next week's release of several important 
economic indicators. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were anxious to see what direction the U.S. stock market  
would take after Labor Day, in addition to waiting for the 
announcement of Japan's gross domestic product data, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 109.74 yen in  
late trading, up 0.32 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also 
above its late New York level of 109.11 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan shares closed sharply lower for the second straight  
session as investors took profits following recent gains. Reports 
that Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, a U.S. investment advisory 
company, has recommended not overweighting Taiwan shares added to 
the bearishness, said analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 152.18  
points, or 1.8 percent, to 8,073.97. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed lower on growing fears over  
the possibility of worsening violence in East Timor after Monday's 
ballot to decide on the province's future. The Composite Index fell 
1 percent, or 5.919 points, to 565.196. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 15.73 points, or 0.7 percent, to 
2,138.76. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed slightly lower as investors  
brace for higher interest rates, both domestically and in the 
United States. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 
3.86 points, or 0.2 percent, to 2,155.09. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower as some potential  
investors awaited the release of U.S. non-farm payrolls data. The 
All Ordinaries Index closed at 2,962.4, down 31.3 points, or 1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed mixed, with the key index rising 1.3  
percent on a rebound from recent sharp losses. The main Korea 
Composite Stock Price Index rose 11.65 points to 910.62. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower. The benchmark Straits  
Times Index fell 25.03 points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,093.18. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed higher on  
bargain-hunting. The Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip 
stocks, closed at 745.32 points, up 9.80 points, or 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares closed higher in a rebound on banking  
stocks which have suffered sharp losses for the past four days. The 
Stock Exchange of Thailand index rose 4.42 points, or 1.0 percent, 
to 431.12. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
