<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Famed Calif. Beach Declared Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Miles of famed ``Surf City,  
USA'' beach along the Southern California coast are open again now 
that the mysterious bacteria which forced them closed this summer 
have all but disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	Contamination levels of fecal bacteria at Huntington State Beach  
have dropped enough to allow swimmers and surfers back into the 
water. 
</P>
<P>
	Health officials believe urban runoff in storm drains -- rather  
than a sewage leak -- may have caused the beach fouling. A report on 
possible causes will be reviewed today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be monitoring the water twice a day and keeping a close  
eye on the results,'' said Larry Honeybourne of Orange County's 
Health Care Agency. ``For now, the water meets the standards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only about one mile of the 8-mile strip will remain closed, he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes after Thursday's announcement, lifeguards removed the  
tape that had cordoned off the shoreline for most of the summer, 
earning cheers from business owners and city officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're all smiles down here,'' said Jack Clapp, who had already  
recalled laid-off workers for his beachfront store. ``I called them 
all and told them I'm going to have some work for them this 
weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The reopening came just in time for the Labor Day weekend,  
traditionally one of the year's most lucrative along the shore. The 
city has lowered its normal $7-a-day parking fee to $1 for the 
holiday weekend in an attempt to lure beachgoers back. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem first surfaced in late June when health officials  
found high levels of bacteria, including extremely high levels of 
enterococcous -- known to cause gastrointestinal and respiratory 
infections. By July 1, they closed its first section of beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the level of bacteria intensified and spread. Between Aug.  
6 and Aug. 21, officials closed six more sections. 
</P>
<P>
	It's too early to tell how much the pollution problem may have  
damaged the image of Huntington Beach, immortalized as ``Surf City, 
USA'' in the 1950s Jan and Dean rock classic and in Beach Boys 
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the reopening, health and sanitation workers warn the  
problem has not been resolved -- and swimmers and surfers could be 
out of the water again. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
