<DOCNO> APW19990903.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 18:22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Standards Effort Hits Snag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A much-touted industry effort to develop a  
common standard to let technology companies freely exchange data 
with other businesses across the Internet has hit an unexpected 
snag due to conflicting corporate agendas. 
</P>
<P>
	A computer industry group said Friday it had rejected a proposed  
version of the standard over concerns it skewed toward U.S. 
companies and will prevent European companies from participating. 
</P>
<P>
	One worry of the Computing Technology Industry Association is  
the standard would enable businesses to exchange personal data 
about their consumers, such as buying habits. This would violate of 
European government privacy rules, which are stricter than those in 
the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	The rejection is expected to delay the release of the standards  
to computer and software makers and distributors, which had been 
expected next February. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bump in the road,'' said Kathey Hale, an analyst with  
the Dataquest high-tech research firm. ``I'm surprised there was 
such a lack of communication here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The standards-setting group, called RosettaNet, was launched  
with much ballyhoo in June to harness the XML software language to 
speed the transmission of data across electronic networks linking 
computer and software makers, parts suppliers and distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	Other industries, such as auto companies, also are working on  
standards for XML, or extensible markup language. XML is a way to 
tag electronic information with identifying codes so that 
businesses can exchange information without worrying about the need 
to reformat data so that it can be retrieved and viewed by others. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a business can easily send orders to a parts  
supplier across the Web without paying big consulting fees to an 
outside company to set up an electronic network. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology industry is being closely watched by XML  
supporters because it is a driving force behind international 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
	A phone message left with Fadi Chehade, executive director of  
the RosettaNet group, was not returned. A RosettaNet spokeswoman 
said he wasn't available. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the concern over European privacy standards,  
another worry is the standard would require companies using it to 
have an identifying code issued by the Dun &AMP; Bradstreet financial 
information firm. Most U.S. companies have such codes, though 
European companies do not. 
</P>
<P>
	``Companies in Europe wouldn't use the standard at all,'' said  
Nicole Shelley, senior director of electronic commerce standards 
for the CTIA, based outside Chicago and made up of 7,500 U.S. and 
Europe technology companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelley said as a result of its concerns, its members would not  
launch tests of the standards over the next several months. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's rejection of the proposal ``is going to delay'' the  
standards, she said. ``The smaller and larger players are saying 
they can't implement these standards.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 15:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Foyt Returning to Winston Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DARLINGTON, S.C. (AP) -- An old face will make a new start next  
year in NASCAR when A.J. Foyt returns to Winston Cup racing as a 
car owner. 
</P>
<P>
	And Foyt, a four-time Indianapolis 500 champion and winner of  
the 1972 Daytona 500, will run the entire Winston Cup schedule for 
the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 64-year-old Foyt, conditioned to winning championships  
with his Indy Racing League cars, is not abandoning the IRL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just be doing a lot of commuting,'' Foyt said Friday at  
Darlington Raceway. ``It might be a little tough to do the 
Indianapolis 500 and the Coca-Cola 600 in the same day, but I'll 
get there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt, despite infrequent appearances he worked into his Indy-car  
career for more than two decades, is no stranger to NASCAR. And his 
operation out of a 30,000-square-foot shop in Charlotte, N.C., will 
be run by longtime team manager and crew chief Waddell Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not getting into this just to run,'' said Foyt, who also  
announced a sponsorship deal with Conseco Inc., the financial 
services group that has backed his Indy-car effort. ``We want to go 
out there and finish in the top 10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt realizes the difficulty of that with a single-car operation  
in a sport where all 23 races this year have been won by drivers 
from multicar teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's tough, and it was even when I raced here,'' said  
Foyt, who had seven victories in 128 NASCAR career starts. ``But if 
you hire the right people, you can make some things happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much remains to be done before Foyt will be ready to field his  
first entry in the first race of the next century -- the 
season-opening Daytona 500. Most of the details will be left to 
Wilson, who built the engines and has called the shots for several 
Daytona 500 winners. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the unfinished business is selecting a driver and make of  
car. All Foyt knows at this time is that the car will be his 
familiar No. 14, the number Kenny Brack drove to both the IRL title 
last year and the Indianapolis 500 championship in May. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kenny likes those IROC cars,'' Foyt said of the all-star  
series in which Brack has driven stock cars. ``But I don't think 
he's ready for these Winston Cup cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt might consider owner-driver Ricky Rudd, and discussed  
buying his operation. Rudd, a 20-time career winner who lost his 
lucrative sponsorship, is still seeking backing to keep his own 
operation afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	But he wouldn't rule out driving for Foyt.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know A.J. is a fierce competitor, and I am, too,'' Rudd  
said. ``A.J. and I are alike in that if we were playing tiddlywinks 
we'd probably be kicking each other under the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt is the second open-wheel car owner to announce he's  
entering NASCAR next season. Cal Wells III, who owns cars in CART, 
is forming Winston Cup and Busch Series teams in 2000. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
