<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Industry Wins Fla. Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The tobacco industry dodged a potential  
multibillion-dollar judgment after a judge ruled damage claims in a 
class-action lawsuit must be considered one person at a time 
instead of as a group. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling Friday by the 3rd District Court of Appeal in Miami  
came in a case filed on behalf of as many as 500,000 sick Florida 
smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Daynard, a Northeastern University law professor who  
heads an anti-tobacco clearinghouse, said the ruling erased 
prospects for a crippling damage award against cigarette makers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Short term, it's a victory,'' Daynard said. ``The industry has  
ducked the bullet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In July, a jury decided in the smokers' favor, ruling that the  
industry produced a deadly product. The next step is to decide how 
much the smokers will get in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers on both sides were barred by a gag order from talking  
about the case, but industry experts saw Friday's decision as a 
major shift in the case favoring tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has essentially devastated the most threatening aspect of  
the claim to the tobacco industry,'' said Martin Feldman, tobacco 
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	A big verdict would have forced tobacco companies to post a  
large bond to appeal the case and could have forced a bankruptcy 
filing this year, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was the first class-action lawsuit by smokers ever to  
go to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the second round is set to begin. The jury will  
return to determine whether two sick smokers should be compensated. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants are the nation's five biggest cigarette makers --  
Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, 
Lorillard Tobacco and the Liggett Group -- and two industry 
associations, the Council for Tobacco Research-U.S.A and the 
Tobacco Institute Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	With Friday's decision, ``there is no potential for damages to  
be decided on a group basis and, as a result, this case now doesn't 
look very different from the vast majority of cases brought against 
the industry,'' Feldman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The individual claims will produce smaller dollar awards, and  
the industry will have an opportunity to wipe out the whole case by 
appealing once one damage award is set, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll just be ordinary multimillion punitive verdicts,''  
Daynard said. ``But this thing is still probably the most potent 
litigation on the horizon against the tobacco companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Results of recent tobacco cases have been mixed. In March, a  
jury in Portland, Ore., awarded $81 million to the family of a 
smoker who died of lung cancer. The month before, a woman with 
inoperable lung cancer won $51 million in San Francisco. Both 
awards were reduced by judges. 
</P>
<P>
	But the industry won another Oregon case as well as lawsuits on  
behalf of unions in Ohio, three dead smokers in Tennessee and one 
in Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. juries have awarded damages in smoking liability cases only  
five times -- twice in Florida and once in New Jersey, Oregon and 
California. Both Florida verdicts and the New Jersey verdict were 
overturned on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The $206 billion national settlement reached with the tobacco  
industry in November bars states from suing to recoup the costs of 
treating sick smokers, but it does not prohibit lawsuits by 
individuals. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 17:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baines Back As an Indian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Harold Baines returned to Camden Yards on  
Friday, happy to be closer to home and delighted to be playing with 
a contender. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baltimore Orioles traded the 40-year-old designated hitter  
to the Cleveland Indians on Aug. 27, getting two young pitchers 
while giving the longtime St. Michael's resident a chance to play 
for a first-place team. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland arrived Thursday night, and Baines took a drive to the  
Eastern Shore to be with his family. On Friday, he was in the 
starting lineup as the Indians resumed their quest to wrap up 
another AL Central title. 
</P>
<P>
	Beforehand, he took some time to talk to Baltimore beat writers  
who had grown accustomed to talking to him in the home clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	So Harold, who'd have thought you'd end up here?  
</P>
<P>
	``It's part of the game. That's the way I approach it,'' he  
said. ``I'm just happy to be in this situation at this point in the 
season, knowing that I'm going to go farther than playing in the 
regular season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because his contract ends after this year, he could very well  
return to the Orioles next season. That's something he'll think 
about after the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to talk about the future right now,'' he said, as  
always using the minimum amount of words to convey his thoughts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
