<DOCNO> APW19990903.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 18:19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Collins Resigns As Angels' Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- A tearful Terry Collins resigned as the  
Anaheim Angels' manager on Friday, less than three months after the 
last-place team gave him a two-year contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Maddon, the Angels' bench coach, will take over as interim  
manager for the rest of this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Anaheim began Friday with a nine-game losing streak and a 51-82  
record, the worst in the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins and general manager Bill Bavasi said the manager was not  
forced out. The two had a long talk Thursday night, and both 
decided it would be best if he quit now. 
</P>
<P>
	Bavasi said he made his recommendation to Collins ``a little bit  
for the club and mostly for Terry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he's not bitter, but I'm bitter. This club had every  
reason to respond and didn't. This is just bad chemistry in the 
clubhouse,'' Bavasi said. ``The team didn't quit on Terry; I can't 
imagine anybody quitting on Terry. ... They quit on themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels were still in contention at the All-Star break, but  
lost 37 of their next 47 to plummet into last place in the AL West. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is, the team's got to perform,'' Collins said.  
``When you don't perform, the manager's accountable. I had a 
feeling today that this is the time. I tried everything I knew, 
from patting them on the back to try to motivate them to kicking 
them in the butt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, 50, hadn't spoken to any of the players about the  
decision, although he said he planned to talk later with some of 
them individually. 
</P>
<P>
	His decision apparently had lot more to do with the players'  
squabbling among themselves than it did with the team's record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday in Cleveland, I had to address a couple of issues  
again and was unable to talk about the game, and that's when it hit 
me,'' Collins said. ``I won't miss the bickering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Bavasi asked some players for their opinion of the manager  
before Collins' contract was renewed, players seemed to splinter 
into pro- and anti-Collins factions. A few unidentified players 
complained about Collins' managing style, but he was given the 
extension anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Second baseman Randy Velarde, who publicly took issue with  
Collins, was traded to Oakland along with starting pitcher Omar 
Olivares for three minor leaguers on July 29. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest clubhouse flareup came when reliever Troy Percival  
complained that not all of his teammates were on the field during a 
brawl with in Cleveland on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident began began after Percival allowed a three-run  
homer to Richie Sexson, capping a 10-run, eighth-inning rally, and 
then hit David Justice with a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Mo Vaughn was in the clubhouse watching on TV and went to the  
dugout, but said he arrived too late to go on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Percival noted that some players hadn't participated in the  
fight, an apparent reference to Vaughn. The following day, Vaughn 
complained that no Angels' pitcher has retaliated this year after 
he was hit, and criticized Percival for hitting Justice, saying, 
``Take a beating like a man and get the next out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bavasi said the makeup of the team doesn't seem to be working,  
and that he accepted responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than we're going to be looking for a manager the rest of  
this season, we're going to be looking at the players,'' he said. 
``I don't know how they're going to react to this, and I'd be less 
than honest if I said I cared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anaheim could be headed for the poorest season in the Angels'  
39-season history -- worse than the 1980 team's 65-95 mark. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like they're the Harlem Globetrotters out there, and  
we're the Washington Generals,'' Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina 
said after Thursday night's 6-5 loss at Cleveland, which turned out 
to be Collins' final game. 
</P>
<P>
	After managing the Houston Astros to second-place finishes in  
the NL Central from 1994-96, Collins went to Anaheim and had a 
220-237 record with the Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in clubhouses where guys don't like each other,''  
Collins said. ``But when I was in Houston, they still went out and 
played hard every game. The manager has one hammer these days, the 
lineup card, and that's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team had high expectations after signing Vaughn to an $80  
million, six-year contract last November, and began the season with 
baseball's 13th-highest payroll at $51.5 million. But the season 
was filled with injuries and discontent. 
</P>
<P>
	DiSarcina was one of several key players sidelined for an  
extended period, along with Vaughn, outfielders Jim Edmonds and Tim 
Salmon, and pitchers Ken Hill, Tim Belcher, Jason Dickson, Mike 
James, Pep Harris and Jack McDowell. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, criticized in the past for being too intense, signed  
the extension on June 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't believe there's a better place to work,'' he  
said then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 18:19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
