<HEADLINE> Circle of Life Wins Spinaway Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Circle of Life came from just off  
the pace and beat odds-on favorite Surfside by 1 1/4 lengths in the 
$200,000, Grade I Spinaway Stakes for 2-year-old fillies at 
Saratoga on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Surfside, a daughter of Seattle Slew-Flanders, lost for the  
first time after two impressive starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Whineshine was another 1 3/4 lengths back in third in the  
field of six. The order of finish was completed by March Magic, 
Dance for Dixie and Asher. 
</P>
<P>
	The win was the second in three career starts for Circle of Life  
who carried 121 pounds and John Velazquez over seven furlongs in 
1:23:1. She earned $120,000 for Michael B. Tabor. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner returned $10, $3.60 and $2.10. Surfside paid $2.90  
and $2.10, while Miss Whineshine was $2.10 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Pletcher, Circle of Life's trainer, had endured some bitter  
disappointment just two days earlier when he was forced to withdraw 
More Than Ready, his prize colt and the pre-race favorite, from 
Saturday's Hopeful Stakes because the colt developed a slight 
fever. 
</P>
<P>
	Pletcher, who once worked as an assistant to Surfside's trainer  
D. Wayne Lukas, said ``It's nice to win a race like the Spinaway. I 
have a lot of respect for Wayne's filly. When I was working for 
him, Flanders was one of my favorite horses. We have a tough 
decision to make. There are only 16 days to the Matron and, after 
that the Frizette. Obviously, the Breeders' Cup (Nov. 6 at 
Gulfstream) is our major goal. We have to see if those other two 
races fit into the schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas revealed that Surfside ``had a little mucous after her  
last race and that's why we put her on Lasix. I thought 
seven-eighths was well within her range. I don't think she showed 
her best today. We kind of committed to Kentucky, so she may run 
there (at Churchill Downs) next.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
