<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Hikes Bank Bailout Estimate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The Mexican government has sharply increased  
its estimate of the cost of bailing out the country's banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicente Corta, executive secretary of the new Mexican deposit  
insurance agency known as IPAB, told reporters Friday the bailout 
would cost $93.4 billion, or about 19.3 percent of Mexico's gross 
domestic product. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous government estimate was $59 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Even with the sharp increase, though, the government's bailout  
estimate was still lower than the one given earlier this week by 
the ratings agency Standard &AMP; Poor's: $105.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Corta said the government's estimate is lower because it  
includes expected asset recoveries and higher deposit insurance 
fees that banks are required to pay. The government hopes to 
recover $22 billion from the sale of bank assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico's poorly regulated banking industry was on the brink of  
collapse when the value of the peso dropped in 1994-95, sending 
interest rates soaring and leaving debtors unable to pay back their 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	President Ernesto Zedillo's bailout plan was approved by  
Congress last year, despite strong objections from opposition 
politicians who considered it a bailout of rich, politically 
connected bankers by poor taxpayers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
