<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Higher, Tokyo Stocks Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen Friday amid concern  
that Japanese monetary officials were ready to intervene to prop up 
the greenback. Tokyo's key stock index slipped marginally. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 109.60 yen at midafternoon, up 0.18 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
109.11 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 1.26 points,  
or 0.01 percent, to close the day's trading at 17,629.99 points. On 
Thursday, the average closed down 171.23 points, or 0.96 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar steadied amid renewed market  
feeling that Japan's central bank may intervene in an attempt to 
halt the yen's appreciation, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials have repeatedly said a premature  
strengthening of the yen is undesirable amid sporadic signs that 
Japan is recovering from its worst recession in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen is seen as negative for Japan's economy because it  
makes the nation's exports more expensive, and therefore less 
competitive, overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's recovery was prompted by comments from Eisuke  
Sakakibara, Japan's former vice finance minister for international 
affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a U.S. television interview broadcast Friday on CNBC,  
Sakakibara, now an advisor to the Finance Ministry, said currency 
``intervention is always a strategic decision,'' which depends on 
market conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Sakakibara's remarks, there have been no recent signs of  
dollar-buying intervention by the Bank of Japan, the country's 
central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said investors were waiting for the release of U.S.  
employment figures for August, due out in Washington later Friday, 
for a further signal about the direction of the high-flying U.S. 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 117.48 yen, up from  
115.86 late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei slipped marginally on concerns  
that the stronger yen may undermine Japan's fledgling economic 
recovery, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	An overnight fall on Wall Street also pushed down Tokyo share  
prices, they said. The Dow closed 94.67 points lower at 10,843.23 
on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up a marginal 0.01 points, insignificant in 
percentage terms, to 1,497.00. The TOPIX closed up 0.75 points, or 
0.05 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 215 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.8400 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8850 
percent, driving its price up to 100.50 yen from 100.12 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
