<HEADLINE> N.J. Cops Thwart Casino Suicide Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- After a string of three suicide leaps  
off casino buildings last month, police convinced another would-be 
jumper to abandon his attempt Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people gathered at the foot of a Trump Plaza hotel  
tower after Jaramillo Rogeles, 19, climbed onto a ledge at about 
10:30 p.m. Thursday, police Sgt. Michael Tullio said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ledge was nearly 20 stories up, near the top of the  
building. Police negotiators climbed to the top of the tower and 
after nearly 2 1/2 hours of talk, convinced Rogeles to put on a rescue 
harness and climb a ladder to safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Tullio said the man was suffering from personal problems that  
had nothing to do with gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	During an eight-day period last month, three people killed  
themselves by leaping from casino buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	A gambler who had lost $87,000 at the tables jumped off a Trump  
Plaza roof. A dealer at Caesars Atlantic City Hotel Casino leaped 
to his death from the casino's parking garage. A German tourist 
made a fatal jump from a Resorts Atlantic City parking garage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
