<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United Shuttle Turbulence Hurts 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- It was just another flight up the  
California coast. The seat belt light was out, and some of the 107 
passengers on the United Shuttle flight were roaming around the 
cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, without warning, turbulence. The plane plunged  
dramatically, sending passengers flying. Fifteen people were 
injured with sprains, cuts and back pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody went straight to the ceiling,'' passenger Ronald  
Kalio said. ``There was two stewardesses that spent the rest of the 
trip in the aisles. They were knocked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines flight 2036 encountered the turbulence at about  
2:20 p.m. Thursday, about halfway through the flight from Los 
Angeles to San Francisco, said United spokesman Joe Hopkins. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how far the plane, flying at 24,000 feet,  
dropped. An airport spokesman noted that people can hit their heads 
if a plane drops just a few feet and they are not wearing seat 
belts. 
</P>
<P>
	Five of those injured were members of a Quincy, Mass., high  
school girls soccer team. Eight-year-old Benjamin Francisco, who 
was traveling with the group of 57 people, suffered a gash on his 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I looked out the window, my first thought was, `It's  
going down,''' said Maureen Cheesman, mother of one of the team 
members. ``When I looked down the aisle, I saw the little boy whose 
head was bleeding profusely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Boeing 737 continued to San Francisco International Airport  
and landed safely less than an hour later, a Federal Aviation 
Administration spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen passengers and a flight attendant were treated at  
hospitals and released. Another flight attendant was kept overnight 
at a hospital with a head injury and was in stable condition 
</P>
<P>
	Airport spokesman Ron Wilson said the plane most likely  
encountered clear-air turbulence, which is rarer than the more 
common wake turbulence. Hopkins, however, said that after talking 
with the pilot, United is ``90 percent sure'' the culprit was wake 
turbulence. 
</P>
<P>
	Wake turbulence is caused by air stirred up by another plane.  
Wilson said a larger MD-11 passenger jet was in front of the United 
Shuttle flight, but was ahead by at least 10 miles, the minimum 
legally required separation. 
</P>
<P>
	Clear-air turbulence -- a weather phenomenon -- can't be seen or  
spotted by instruments and results in a more violent jolt for 
passengers, Wilson said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 17:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Donates Kidney to Stranger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- A woman donated a kidney to a complete  
stranger, undergoing surgery and a battery of physical and 
psychological tests simply because she knew there was a long 
waiting list for organs. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts said that transplants in which neither donor nor  
recipient knows the other person were almost unheard of until a few 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, the 50-year-old donor was ``purely motivated by  
altruism,'' said Cheryl Jacobs, a social worker who took part in 
the psychological screening of the woman. 
</P>
<P>
	The donor and the recipient both asked to keep their identities  
secret, even from each other. 
</P>
<P>
	The transplant took place in early August but wasn't disclosed  
until Thursday, after the patients had left the hospital at the 
University of Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Transplanted kidneys generally come from a cadaver or a living  
relative. Transplant programs have been reluctant to accept kidney 
donations from living strangers for several reasons, including 
concern about exposing the donor to the risks of surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the donor in this case was turned down by several  
transplant centers before the university accepted her offer. 
Hospital officials said they were convinced, after intense 
psychological and physical screening, that she made the offer for 
the right reasons and knew the risks. 
</P>
<P>
	She could have gotten some reassurance from Dr. Arthur Matas,  
who performed the transplant. In 1992, he published a study in The 
Lancet, a British medical journal, that found that people who live 
with one kidney after donating the other are not at increased risk 
of suffering from kidney failure or hypertension. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42,000 people on the nation's kidney transplant waiting list  
generally will have to wait three to five years for a new organ. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, there were 11,990 kidney transplants in the United  
States, and just over 4,000 came from living donors. Of those, 163 
were unrelated to the recipients, according to the United Network 
on Organ Sharing. UNOS doesn't keep data on how many came from 
strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Matas said he has heard of only one other such procedure.  
</P>
<P>
	However, Dr. William Bennett, president of the American Society  
of Nephrology, said: ``Living, unrelated transplantation is growing 
in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was always felt before, why use a living patient when you  
could use a cadaver donor?'' Bennett said. ``But it turns out the 
fact that the donor is living confers some advantage.'' That's 
because organs from cadavers have to be preserved. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Kahn, director of the university's Center for Bioethics,  
said he expects the hospital to perform more transplants with 
organs from unrelated donors. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital is approached about six times a month by people  
asking if they can donate kidneys, so officials have set up a 
system to screen the callers, identify their true motives and put 
their kidneys into a pool for recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if one kidney we get this way, it's one less person on  
the list,'' Kahn said. ``Even if it's one a year, it's a success.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
