<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Die When Small Plane Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- An ambulance plane flying from  
Michigan to Boca Raton crashed into a strip mall early today while 
trying to make an emergency landing, killing all seven aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't immediately known if any were patients.  
</P>
<P>
	The plane, a twin-engine Beechcraft King Air BE-90, hit the roof  
of a mall building at about 3:30 a.m., according to Federal 
Aviation Administration spokeswoman Tanya Wagner in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	All seven dead were aboard the plane, according to Jorge  
Prellezo, regional director of the National Transportation Safety 
Board in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	It was an ambulance flight, ``like airplanes they actually  
charter to move a patient,'' he said, but he didn't know whether 
any of the seven were patients. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a small fire after the crash, Prellezo said.  
</P>
<P>
	``The landing gear from the aircraft is inside one of the  
buildings,'' Capt. Nigel Baker of Palm Beach Fire Rescue told 
WFOR-TV in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane, which took off from a small airport near Pontiac,  
Mich., was diverted after the pilot reported problems, the station 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot asked permission to land at West Palm Beach, Prellezo  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roads in the area were closed early today and crews were working  
on downed power lines, said Doug Hawkins of the Palm Beach County 
sheriff's office. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
