<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Photos Peek Into D.C.'s Top Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People who don't expect ever to get into the  
private drawing room of Sir Christopher Meyer, Queen Elizabeth's 
ambassador to Washington, can get a peek inside the residence 
through a book of photos that penetrates some of the capital's top 
homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The kind of peeping Toms who are fascinated by interior decor  
can have a look at Sir Christopher's state dining room. They will 
see the massive red drapes, the four glasses at each place setting 
and the queen's monogram on the chairs. 
</P>
<P>
	But they have to imagine the white ties, deep-cleavage dinner  
gowns, tall footmen in royal livery and the kilted Scots bagpiper 
who used to appear at formal dinners. 
</P>
<P>
	``Private Washington'' is a coffee-table book that appeals to  
people curious about how the other half lives. 
</P>
<P>
	Architectural photographer Walter Smalling Jr. also looked into  
Halcyon House, built in 1787 five years before the White House was 
begun. On Prospect Hill just below the tower of Georgetown 
University, it looks out over the Potomac, the landmarks of the 
capital and the high-rises of Rosslyn on the Virginia side of the 
river. 
</P>
<P>
	George Washington and other founding fathers knew Halcyon House  
as the home of Benjamin Stoddert, the first secretary of the Navy. 
It was near the landing of the ferry from Virginia, where 
Washington and Jefferson lived. Author Jan Cigliano writes that the 
William Jefferson Clintons have also been there to ``dance the 
night away.'' The first lady's office confirmed that they have been 
guests at least once. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once people accepted to let us go into their homes, it wasn't  
difficult,'' the author said in an interview. ``But about twice as 
many refused. They were people who are in public office, or just 
want to keep their lives private.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cigliano and Smalling cover 26 homes in the book.  
</P>
<P>
	Real estate developer John Dreyfuss, 49, has spent more than 20  
years redoing Halcyon House. His biggest job was to get rid of odd 
additions by a former owner who kept building for 38 years until 
his death. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Clemons, known in his Georgetown neighborhood as an  
eccentric, had put in doors that led into walls, closets that led 
into other closets, rooms too low to stand in, and 10 rental 
apartments masked by a four-story facade facing the street. The 
original spare but elegant two-story structure faces the river, 
across a garden said to have been laid out originally by Pierre 
L'Enfant, who planned the city of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Dreyfuss now has a sculpture studio in the basement and rents  
out space for business events every few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Private Washington'' provides views of the dining room and its  
Japanese screens in the Georgetown mansion of Katharine Graham, 
which also dates back to Revolutionary times. She's the 82-year-old 
president of the Washington Post Co. who won a Pulitzer Prize last 
year for her autobiography ``Personal History.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other media celebrity lairs include the home of the Post's  
retired executive editor, Ben Bradlee. His wife, author Sally 
Quinn, writes in the introduction to the book of being scared by an 
apparition in her back doorway of a woman in the lace cap and 
full-skirted gown of the 1700s. The ghost disappeared as suddenly 
as she came. 
</P>
<P>
	It turned out it was a costumed guide from the Old Stone House,  
the oldest house in Georgetown, built long before the White House. 
She had seen the Bradlees' garden gate open and couldn't restrain 
her professional curiosity. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 07:38:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charges Dropped in Princess Di Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A French judge has dismissed all charges against  
nine photographers and a press motorcyclist implicated in the car 
crash that killed Princess Diana, ending the two-year investigation 
into the accident, judicial sources said today. 
</P>
<P>
	In his decision, Judge Herve Stephan said the accident was ``due  
to the fact that the driver of the car was inebriated and under the 
effects of drugs incompatible with alcohol, which did not allow him 
to maintain control of his vehicle,'' the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephan also concluded that the decision by Dodi Fayed, Diana's  
boyfriend, to order an off-duty security official, who was drunk, 
to drive the Mercedes, also contributed to the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Diana died in the Aug. 31, 1997 crash in a Paris traffic tunnel.  
Fayed and the driver, Henri Paul, were also killed. Only bodyguard 
Trevor Rees-Jones survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohamed Al Fayed, Dodi's father and the owner of the Ritz Hotel  
that leased the vehicle, will appeal the decision, said his lawyer 
in Paris, George Kiejman. 
</P>
<P>
	``The photographers have a shared responsibility with the  
drivers,'' Kiejman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Fayed will continue to pursue ``the truth,'' said a spokesman  
in London. Al Fayed has said he believes there was a murder 
conspiracy plotted by people who did not approve of Diana's 
relationship with Dodi, an Egyptian. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Al Fayed has the resources and the will and has vowed to  
find out exactly why his son and the others died,'' said spokesman 
Laurie Mayer. 
</P>
<P>
	Earl Spencer, Diana's brother, who had also lashed out against  
the photographers, thanked the French authorities for ``the time 
and effort they have put into the investigation, and I respect the 
legal conclusions that have been reached.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buckingham Palace had no comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The judge followed recommendations issued Aug. 16 by the state  
prosecutor to drop charges of manslaughter and failing to assist 
persons in danger against the photographers and the press 
motorcyclist, the sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Speed and alcohol long have been identified as the major causes  
of the crash, but initial suspicion fell on the photographers who 
were involved in a high-speed chase of Diana in hopes of getting a 
valuable shot of the princess and her beau. 
</P>
<P>
	The photographers, who acknowledge tailing Diana, claim they  
were made scapegoats and maintained throughout the investigation 
that they bore no responsibility for the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	They had been placed under formal investigation, which in France  
is one step short of being formally charged. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision to dismiss the charges is a tremendous relief  
and puts an end to two nerve-wracking years,'' said Romuald Rat, a 
photographer who had tried to take Diana's pulse as she lay dying. 
</P>
<P>
	Diana was the world's hottest photographic prey in the summer of  
1997, and photos of her and Dodi in the midst of a budding romance 
could fetch hundreds of thousands of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-awaited report by Stephan, the chief investigating  
judge, can be appealed by any of the parties to the case. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for Rees-Jones, who has filed a suit against the Ritz  
hotel and its car service, Etoile Limousine, ``for endangering the 
lives of others,'' praised the decision. Christian Curtil said he 
was pleased the judge had ``emphasized the responsibility of the 
Ritz hotel and the Etoile-Limousine company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Rees-Jones had not decided whether to appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	The bodyguard's suit cites the Ritz and the car service for  
``failing to provide a licensed driver'' for the Mercedes that 
crashed. The driver, Henri Paul, did not have the type of license 
required to drive the Mercedes 280S sedan, provided to the Ritz by 
Etoile-Limousine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
