<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns Tear Up Home Turf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Browns decided to plow under  
their ``cow pasture'' before playing the Pittsburgh Steelers on it. 
</P>
<P>
	After players complained about loose turf and former linebacker  
Chris Spielman called it a ``cow pasture'' after two exhibition 
games, the Browns tore up and replaced the entire playing field in 
their new $283 million stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	With their first regular-season home game at the new Cleveland  
Browns Stadium set for Sept. 12 and on national TV, the Browns had 
the field, planted by the city in late June, re-sodded from goal 
line to goal line. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did this because we felt the level of play that one could  
expect on the preexisting field was not what the mayor of the city, 
the Cleveland Browns or the National Football League were expecting 
from this new facility,'' Browns president Carmen Policy said. 
``This was not the way we wanted to highlight our game especially 
on prime-time TV with the nation watching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the Browns' first two exhibition games, players were  
losing their footing as they tried to cut and large chunks of the 
sod came up. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, according to Policy, was that a clay base should  
have been used instead of sand and the sod should have been laid 
earlier. The grass needed at least 3 inches of root depth and had 
only reached 2, partly because of the late installation and a hot, 
dry summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Spielman, who retired earlier this week because of a neck  
injury, was the most outspoken player about the condition of the 
playing surface. But Policy said the team was aware of the problem, 
and decided to replace the field and its sand base, partly because 
of safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns are reportedly paying the $75,000 to $100,000 bill to  
redo the job, but Policy said the team, which has made other 
alterations to the stadium, would work with the city before 
deciding on how to pay for the latest change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't make the decision because we thought it was on  
somebody else's dime,'' said Policy, who was handed the keys to the 
new stadium by the city on Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Policy said he has been very pleased with the new stadium, and  
that the majority of the complaints the Browns have received from 
fans could be easily solved. 
</P>
<P>
	The day after the Browns played their first exhibition game,  
Policy heard about one of the problems while jogging. 
</P>
<P>
	``This guy ran buy, and said, `Great game, great stadium. Put  
some timeouts on the scoreboard,''' Policy said. ``We took care of 
that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
