<DOCNO> APW19990903.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins QB Craig Erickson Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Craig Erickson, once the heir apparent to Dan  
Marino, was released Friday by the Miami Dolphins. 
</P>
<P>
	Erickson underwent elbow surgery last year and failed to  
overtake Damon Huard this summer in the battle for the job backing 
up Marino. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't disappointed in Craig's play,'' coach Jimmy Johnson  
said. ``We were extremely happy with the play of Damon Huard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erickson, an eight-year veteran, said he wasn't surprised to be  
released. 
</P>
<P>
	``Going into training camp, I knew I had to have a very good  
camp,'' Erickson said. ``I could have done some things differently. 
There might be a few philosophy things, the way I approached the 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to elaborate, but it's no secret he fell out of  
favor with Johnson last year. Johnson was skeptical about the 
severity of Erickson's elbow injury before the quarterback finally 
had surgery Nov. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Erickson, 30, said his elbow feels fine now, but he declined to  
say whether he wants to join another team. He grew up in nearby 
West Palm Beach, played for the Miami Hurricanes and plans to keep 
his home in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Erickson was released partly because the Dolphins have numerous  
injuries and need roster space for other positions. They may sign 
another third-string quarterback in a few weeks, and Johnson said 
he might try to re-sign Erickson later at a reduced salary if he's 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	Erickson, who had a base salary of $650,000 this season, didn't  
rule out rejoining Miami, his third NFL team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a dream come true to be able to play for the  
Dolphins,'' he said. ``I've had a great time here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erickson was Miami's No. 2 quarterback in 1996-97, starting  
three games when Marino was hurt. Marino, 37, has started 41 
consecutive regular-season games. 
</P>
<P>
	Huard, a third-year pro, was an undrafted free agent and joined  
Miami in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good friend,'' Erickson said. ``He's progressed really  
well.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
