<DOCNO> APW19990903.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 15:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Finds Pirates' '79 Series Trophy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The missing 1979 World Series trophy turned up  
behind a Pittsburgh-area church, and the boy who found it got to 
visit with the Pirates on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, it remained unclear exactly how the trophy disappeared  
from the lobby of the Allegheny Club at Three Rivers Stadium and 
authorities continued their investigation, now armed with 
fingerprints taken from the well-traveled trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe somebody's conscience was bothering them and they  
decided to turn it in,'' said Det. Donald Pasquarelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Offerman, 12, was doing cleanup work Friday morning at a  
church when he found a black plastic bag outside the back door. He 
saw the trophy gleaming from the top of the bag and hailed firemen 
who were conducting a fundraiser in the neighborhood, after which 
they contacted police. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I saw it at first I knew what it was, but I didn't want  
to believe it,'' said Offerman, who had seen television reports 
about it being taken. 
</P>
<P>
	Pasquarelli said the freckle-faced youngster mentioned to police  
that he was a big fan of the Pirates, and told him he knew the team 
was back in town Friday for a game against the San Francisco 
Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was so cute,'' Pasquarelli said. ``He said, `Hey officer,  
I'm free tonight. I don't have anything to do.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Pasquarelli said he knew someone at the Allegheny Club, and a  
few phone calls later, the Pirates had arranged for Offerman to 
meet his favorite player, second baseman Warren Morris. He was also 
given tickets to attend the game with family and friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the game, Offerman walked awestruck across the field and  
visited in the dugout with Pirates manager Gene Lamont. He tried on 
a few hats before finding one that fit just right; Lamont told him 
to make sure and roll the bill just right. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's eyes opened wide as Morris walked up to him. When  
asked what position he would play, Offerman said second base. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'd better watch out, Mo,'' Lamont teased.  
</P>
<P>
	Offerman doesn't really remember much about the 1979 World  
Series when the Pirates won the trophy, but he wanted to make sure 
the trophy got back to its proper place, so officials made sure he 
was the one to put it back into the trophy case. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a real good kid, just like out of a movie or something,''  
Sgt. Mark Ninehouser said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was minor damage to the award; two pennants -- the Boston  
Red Sox and the Oakland Athletics -- were missing. 
</P>
<P>
	The trophy has rarely left the stadium since it was donated by  
the Galbreath family, former owners of the team. But sometime 
between 5:15 p.m. and 6 p.m. Wednesday, during a private corporate 
party at the club, the trophy disappeared from an unlocked glass 
display case. Authorities and a memorabilia expert estimate the 
value of the trophy at $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Allegheny Club president Kevin Vaughn said they don't think it  
was a guest who took it. A guard is posted at the stadium entrance 
to check the guest list for anyone coming in and likely would have 
noticed someone leaving with something that stands 3 feet tall and 
weighs about 50 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that the trophy is returned, they're in there reviewing  
all the security measures,'' Vaughn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh burglary detectives were questioning employees and  
some 100 guests who attended the private evening party, which was 
hosted by a club member. 
</P>
<P>
	``It must have gone out into the stadium area,'' Vaughn said.  
``We have no idea how they got it, actually.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 13:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Irvan To Retire From Winston Racing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DARLINGTON, S.C. (AP) -- Ernie Irvan, recovering from a second  
head injury in five years, retired today after 13 seasons on the 
NASCAR Winston Cup circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a tough decision to make, but I was able to make it  
on my own terms, and now I can focus on my immediate future,'' said 
Irvan, who nearly died from a head injury five years ago and still 
is recovering from a less-serious one two weeks ago. ``Physically, 
I feel good, but I believe this is the right decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 40-year-old Californian said doctors who have been treating  
him since his latest crash, Aug. 20, at Michigan Speedway, did not 
tell him he had to retire. He said he made the decision Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said another accident like the one I had earlier probably  
would be detrimental to me living a wholesome life,'' Irvan said, 
his voice cracking with emotion as he sat with his wife and two 
children. ``It's something that brings tears to my eyes to know I'm 
never going to drive a Winston Cup car again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He crashed during a practice session for a Busch Series race,  
sustaining head and lung injuries. He spent several days in a 
Michigan hospital, then returned to his farm in Mooresville, N.C., 
to continue his recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened five years to the day after a near-fatal  
wreck on the same 2-mile superspeedway. Irvan lingered near death 
after the 1994 crash, at first given only a 10 percent chance of 
survival. 
</P>
<P>
	But he recovered, and 14 months later resumed a once-promising  
career that included a victory in the 1991 Daytona 500, the world's 
premier stock car race. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan has driven in the Winston Cup series since 1987, getting  
his first victory for Morgan-McClure Racing in 1990. He had seven 
of his 15 career victories for that team, then moved to Robert 
Yates Racing late in 1993 after its driver, Davey Allison, was 
killed in a helicopter crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan became a fan favorite in part because the No. Ford 28 had  
been driven by several Hall of Famers. Yates did not renew Irvan's 
contract at the end of the 1997 season, and the driver moved to 
MBII Motorsports, with whom he recently agreed to a contract 
extension through the end of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Irvan didn't win in two seasons with MBII, his  
popularity grew with fans as a result of slick marketing by his 
sponsor. Children were excited by the paint schemes on his cars, 
especially that of M&AMP;M's, which includes comic-strip-like candy 
pieces all over the No. 36 Pontiac. 
</P>
<P>
	After the first Michigan accident, Irvan never regained his  
form. He had three more victories for Yates, the most recent his 
only career win at Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was big moment for me, because I almost died at that  
track,'' Irvan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvan had five top-10 finishes this season, his best sixth in  
the Las Vegas 400. He made 313 starts, had 22 poles and 68 top-five 
finishes. 
</P>
<P>
	He also is co-owner of Irvan-Simo Motorsports, which has fielded  
entries in NASCAR's Truck, Grand National and Winston Cup series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think some people are surprised that I'm still able to  
comprehend all this,'' Irvan said. ``So, I think retiring now is 
the smartest thing I can do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 13:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
