<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Deal in Detroit Teacher's Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Officials in the state's largest school district  
and the teachers striking against it dug in their heels over merit 
pay and class sizes as negotiators tried to end the walkout. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked a lot but we agreed on nothing,'' said John Elliott,  
president of the Detroit Federation of Teachers, the union 
representing 9,200 teachers. ``There's no movement, no momentum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Classes in the 172,000-student district were canceled for a  
fourth day Thursday as negotiations went on throughout the day 
before breaking off shortly before midnight. Talks were scheduled 
to resume today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have issues that haven't been resolved,'' said Jim  
Amar, a state mediator appointed Aug. 24 to sit in on the talks 
between the board and union. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers won at least one concession from the reform-minded  
school administration -- a district proposal to extend the school 
day by 2 hours, to 8 1/2 hours, was withdrawn. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, teachers would not oppose having aides and other  
non-teaching personnel work longer days so the district could offer 
after-school programs. 
</P>
<P>
	David Adamany, the district's chief executive, remained  
committed to his proposal to reward schools meeting test score and 
attendance targets by granting ``merit bonuses'' to every employee 
in that school -- including custodians and secretaries. 
</P>
<P>
	But Paul Danic, an English teacher at Osborn High School, said  
the plan would reward teachers at what he called ``showcase 
schools'' without recognizing competent teachers at other schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``The inequity of the worst teacher in a good school receiving a  
bonus, but not a good teacher in a bad school, is totally unfair,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other contentious issues included salary, class size and sick  
days. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous contract between the teachers and the school system  
expired June 30, and an extension ran out Monday. Teachers then 
voted to reject negotiators' recommendation for another extension. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike has put at least a temporary halt to reform efforts  
led by Adamany since he took the job in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. John Engler, who signed legislation shifting control of the  
district from the elected board to an appointed board that hired 
Adamany, said the change was necessary to shore up lagging test 
scores, chronically low attendance and graduation rates in the 
nation's 10th-largest city. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Surge Upward; Crude Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Soybean futures zoomed Friday to their highest price since March  
as investors braced for a smaller crop than expected due to a run 
of dry weather in the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, crude oil and its products rose and pork  
bellies fell. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans advanced for a fourth consecutive day on the Chicago  
Board of Trade in response to three forecasts that predicted the 
crop would come in significantly smaller than the most recent 
government estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	The three private forecasts averaged about 90 million bushels  
less than the 2.87 billion bushels anticipated by the U.S. 
Department of Agriculture in its August estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers Commodities Corp. of Des Moines, Iowa, predicted the  
1999-2000 soybean crop would be 2.736 billion bushels, while Sparks 
Co. put it at 2.789 billion bushels. Allendale Inc. of McHenry, 
Ill., forecast it only slightly higher -- 2.816 billion bushels. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices had risen 5 percent in electronic trading overnight, and  
the trend continued into the regular trading day. But enthusiasm 
was dimmed somewhat by forecasts for rain in the Midwest that could 
increase crop size. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans for November delivery rose 2 3/4 cents to $4.98 1/4 a bushel,  
the highest closing price since March 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains also advanced slightly along with soybeans over similar  
crop uncertainties. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had some bullish forecasts out, but we're also getting  
closer and closer to harvest time,'' prompting caution, said Jack 
Scoville, vice president of the Price Futures Group in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	December wheat rose 2 3/4 cents to $2.89 a bushel; December corn  
rose 1/2 cent to $2.22 1/2 a bushel; December oats were unchanged at 
$1.16 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil prices leapt back up to the $22-a-barrel mark on the  
New York Mercantile Exchange, recovering from two days of losses, 
and natural gas followed suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said that with the U.S. hurricane season still not over,  
the market was wary about the possibility of a sudden storm that 
could cause damage in the Gulf of Mexico during the three-day Labor 
Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``People just didn't want to go home short over the long weekend  
in case something tropical came up,'' said Bill O'Grady, an energy 
analyst for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices also got support from a private survey of oil companies  
which found that OPEC countries are thought to be largely 
fulfilling their promise to stick to oil production cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil for October delivery rose 51 cents to $22 a barrel;  
October unleaded gasoline rose 1.25 cents to 64.76 cents a gallon; 
October heating oil rose 1 cent to 57.47 cents a gallon; October 
natural gas rose 9 cents to $2.561 for each million British thermal 
units. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude for October delivery rose  
23 cents to $21.03 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures plummeted for a second straight day on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange over concerns of an overabundance of product on 
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4.8 percent fall meant the pork bellies market was just shy  
of recording the maximum 5 percent decline for the second day in a 
row. 
</P>
<P>
	February pork bellies fell 2.75 cents to 54.57 cents a pound;  
October lean hogs fell 1.20 cents to 45.85 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 13:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Homeless Samaritan Finds a Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A woman who gave a kidney to save a boy's  
life, then wound up in a homeless shelter, got a new place to live 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first key that I've had in years to my own  
house,'' Marian Neal said as she entered the Washington, D.C., 
townhouse with Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo. 
</P>
<P>
	Neal will pay $56 per month in rent -- utilities included -- for a  
one-bedroom apartment in a complex built in 1942. 
</P>
<P>
	The small brick rowhouse has bars on the ground floor windows  
and public housing police make routine patrols. But for Neal, it is 
a small slice of heaven. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to worry about someone saying, 'You can't be  
here, you can't stay,''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Neal befriended a 7-year-old neighbor while living  
with a friend in a public housing complex in nearby Alexandria, Va. 
She began taking the boy to kidney dialysis treatments and 
eventually donated a kidney. A successful transplant was done in 
December. 
</P>
<P>
	But earlier this week, housing officials said she was breaking  
the rules by living with her friend and ordered her to leave. Neal 
is unable to work because of a degenerative spinal condition and 
she was denied Social Security benefits, so she moved to an 
Alexandria homeless shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	Her plight was featured on radio and television stations,  
leading to more than $5,000 in cash donations and a used car from a 
local dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuomo said he told his staff on Thursday to find Neal a place to  
live and they did it in a day, using exemptions to federal housing 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone who has been that good and that kind to the community  
deserves a place to live that they can call their own,'' he said, 
calling Neal ``a genuine American heroine.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:30:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inkster May Head for Hall of Fame  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- When Juli Inkster last appeared at the  
State Farm Rail Classic in 1983, she was a rookie starting what 
would become a remarkable career. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, she could leave the three-day tournament as a member  
of the LPGA Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	After being a dominant player on the tour in the latter half of  
the 1980s, Inkster had only four victories between 1991 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, however, the mother of two has rejuvenated her career  
by winning four tournaments -- two of them majors -- and is No. 2 on 
the tour money list behind Karrie Webb. Inkster has been in the top 
10 in 14 of 18 events this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Golfers need 27 points to get into the Hall of Fame under the  
LPGA's new point system. Inkster has 26 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Most tournament wins are worth a point, with majors worth two.  
</P>
<P>
	Inkster is among several big names competing in the tournament  
that begins Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Famer Nancy Lopez also is seeking a milestone this  
weekend. Despite a sore knee -- she underwent surgery in June -- 
Lopez is looking for career win No. 50, her third in this 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Others entered are Dottie Pepper, winner of last week's  
Oldsmobile Classic, No. 4 money winner Lorie Kane, British Women's 
Open champion Sherri Steinhauer and defending champion Pearl Sinn. 
</P>
<P>
	The course is known for its low scores. In the past two years,  
it took a 3-under 141 to make the 36-hole cut -- an LPGA record. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't have to hit spectacular shots,'' Sinn said of the  
6,403-yard, par 72 course. ``Your whole work begins on the 
greens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sinn earned her first career victory last year by shooting a  
final round 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Other former Rail Classic champions in the field are Hollis  
Stacy (1977), Betsy King (1985, '86 and '88), Helen Dobson (1993), 
Barb Mucha (1994), Mary Beth Zimmerman (1995), Michelle McGann 
(1996) and Cindy Figg-Currier (1997). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 00:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada To Test-Burn U.S. Nuke Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers will use a shipment of reactor  
fuel from New Mexico's Los Alamos lab to test whether Canada's 
nuclear reactors are suitable to dispose of weapons-grade 
plutonium. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada has committed only to the tests, although the Canadian  
government has offered to burn as much as 100 tons of the plutonium 
fuel blend over a 25-year period. The test burns are expected to 
take several years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The test is a step forward in getting rid of nuclear weapons,  
and the government of Canada is committed to decreasing the number 
of nuclear weapons in the world,'' said Canadian Foreign Affairs 
Minister Lloyd Axworthy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department and Canadian officials announced an  
agreement Thursday on the shipment, which will be made later this 
year. The experiment at the CANDU reactor in Chalk River, Ontario, 
100 miles west of Ottawa also will involve a separate shipment of 
similar fuel from Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The fuel is a mixture of plutonium oxide and uranium oxide. The  
Energy Department previously announced that about 36 tons of 
plutonium from the U.S. weapons program will be burned as a 
mixed-oxide fuel at three U.S. civilian reactors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian experiments are designed to determine whether the  
Canadian reactors -- a different design than the U.S. light-water 
reactors -- also can use the mixed-oxide fuel as part of a plutonium 
disposal plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, nine mixed-oxide fuel rods containing 120  
grams of plutonium will be shipped sometime this fall by truck from 
the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico to Sault St. 
Marie, Mich., where it will cross into Canada, U.S. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shipments have caused concern in states along the routes,  
especially in Michigan. Antinuclear groups and some members of the 
Canadian Parliament also have voiced opposition to the program, 
fearing Canada will become a dumping ground for Cold War-era 
plutonium from both Russia and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nuclear Control Institute, a Washington-based  
nonproliferation advocacy groups, also has voiced concerns about 
using the CANDU reactors for plutonium disposal. Other countries, 
including South Korea, have the same design reactors and may pursue 
similar programs, said Steven Dolley, the institute's research 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Canadian and U.S. officials characterized the Canadian  
program as another step to ensure that the plutonium is disposed of 
safely and kept out of the hands of rogue states and terrorists 
seeking to use if in weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The disposal plan calls for pure plutonium from weapons pits, or  
triggers, to be converted into plutonium oxide and then mixed with 
uranium oxide to create the mixed-oxide, or MOX, fuel that can be 
burned in a civilian reactor much like the conventional uranium 
fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	The fuel rods at Los Alamos already have been processed into MOX  
fuel, officials said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 13:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UNLV Hopes To Start New Streak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- It didn't take John Robinson long to stop one  
UNLV football streak. Now he wants to work on another. 
</P>
<P>
	``This football team is 1-0. It's a winning streak we're on  
now,'' Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-longest losing streak in college football -- 16 games  
over two seasons -- came to an end Thursday night in Denton, Texas, 
where UNLV opened the Robinson era with a 26-3 win over North 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	It was cause for celebration not only for the new coach, but for  
the players who have endured tough times. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did it, baby,'' fifth-year senior wide receiver Len Ware  
said. ``We finally did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not only did UNLV break its 16-game losing streak, it also broke  
a 26-game road losing streak that began in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Just because it came against a mistake-prone North Texas team  
that looks to be the easiest opponent on UNLV's schedule did not 
temper the celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	``The streaks are dead,'' UNLV safety Randy Black screamed at  
his teammates as the game ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson gave UNLV president Carol Harter the game ball after  
the win, which was the first for the 64-year-old coach since he was 
fired at USC two seasons ago. Harter hired Robinson after last 
season's team went 0-11 under former coach Jeff Horton. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Robinson's recruits could easily have gotten the ball,  
though, after making solid debuts that give the team hope for the 
rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Tailback Jeremi Rudolph showed why he was considered the top  
running back prospect in Florida five years ago by carrying 20 
times for 97 yards and two touchdowns, while junior quarterback 
Jason Vaughan's first Division I start was efficient with 16 of 19 
passes completed for 127 yards and a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``We said before the game that regardless of what happened we  
were going to come home and start getting ready to be a better 
football team,'' Robinson said. ``and that's what we're going to 
do. There's not an unbelievable hue and cry in our locker room. We 
expected to win the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the most impressive part of the win was UNLV's defense,  
which has been much maligned over recent seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	North Texas was limited to just four first downs in the second  
half, and the three points allowed were the fewest by a Rebels' 
defense since Sept. 3, 1994, when UNLV defeated Eastern Michigan 
17-3 in Horton's debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``No way,'' defensive coordinator Jeff McInerney said when asked  
if he thought before the game his unit could hold North Texas to 
just a field goal. 
</P>
<P>
	UNLV led only 6-3 going into the fourth quarter, then turned a  
crucial penalty on a field-goal attempt into a touchdown that 
sparked a 20-point fourth-quarter rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Things get tougher next week as the Rebels travel to Baylor  
before returning home to face Iowa State on Sept. 18 in the home 
opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think our kids played like winners,'' Robinson said. ``How  
talented are we? Hell, I don't begin to know. But I felt like we 
did not look like a team that had lost 100 million in a row. I'm 
really proud of them for that. I think this is just one more step 
forward.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
