<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 18:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Wings Sign Steve Duchesne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Free agent Steve Duchesne, a playmaking  
defenseman who finished last season with Philadelphia, signed a 
one-year contract with the Detroit Red Wings on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steve brings a great deal of NHL experience and depth to our  
blue line,'' Red Wings general manager Ken Holland said. ``He's a 
strong skater, moves the puck very well and will fit in nicely with 
our defensive group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duchesne, 34, is a three-time all star who was once part of the  
trade that sent Eric Lindros from Quebec to Philadelphia. He was 
fourth among NHL defensemen in scoring two seasons ago with St. 
Louis with 14 goals and 42 assists. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was a disappointment last year for Los Angeles, which  
signed him as a free agent. He had just had just four goals and 19 
assists in 60 games before being traded to Philadelphia. He had two 
goals and five assists with the Flyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Duchesne is not a physical player and is not known as a strong  
defensive player. 
</P>
<P>
	During his 14-year NHL career, Duchesne has played for  
Philadelphia, Los Angeles and St. Louis twice each and Quebec and 
Ottawa once. He has 208 goals and 460 assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Contract terms were not disclosed.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 09:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia PM Skips Pacific Rim Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad  
will not attend next week's annual summit of Pacific Rim leaders in 
New Zealand, fueling speculation Friday about imminent general 
elections in Malaysia. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar said Deputy Prime Minister  
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi would stand in for Mahathir at the Sept. 
12-13 summit of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should not be interpreted as a snub,'' Syed Hamid told  
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The move, however, whipped up widespread speculation that  
Mahathir, Asia's longest-serving leader, is preparing to dissolve 
Parliament and call a quick poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's reaction is that it's election related,'' said Lim  
Kit Siang, the opposition leader of Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	But Syed Hamid denied it.  
</P>
<P>
	``Dr. Mahathir has many things to attend to,'' he said, but  
refused to give a cause for the cancellation. ``It is nothing 
unusual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said Mahathir would travel to New York later this month  
to attend the U.N. General Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Elections are not due until June 2000, when Parliament expires.  
But observers widely expect Mahathir to hold them before the end of 
the year, as the ruling National Front coalition has been 
feverishly campaigning nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the 73-year-old leader may try to capitalize on the  
rebounding economy and lack of cohesion within the opposition, 
which holds only 25 of the 192 seats in Parliament and would need a 
two-thirds majority to unseat Mahathir. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahathir's absence from the APEC forum in Auckland will remove  
its loudest advocate of restrictions on global financial markets 
and one of the harshest critics of the 21-member body. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahathir boycotted APEC's inaugural 1993 summit, saying APEC was  
dominated by Western members. A year after APEC was launched, 
Mahathir proposed his own East Asian Economic Group, which would 
have excluded the United States, Canada, Australia and New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, when Malaysia hosted the APEC summit, Mahathir  
criticized the body for not doing enough to put an end to the Asian 
financial crisis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 18:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Witness: Jim Brown Wasn't Violent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A psychiatrist testified Friday that Jim  
Brown's wife was molested as a child and has a ``borderline 
personality disorder'' that may have caused her to lie to police 
when she claimed her husband threatened to kill her. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Helene McDonald said she interviewed Monique Brown for 12  
hours and learned of her lifelong problems with men, dating to 
abandonment by her father, conflicts with her stepfather and her 
molestation by a stranger when she was 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The doctor suggested that Monique Brown called 911 on June 15  
after arguing with her husband because she wanted to elicit a 
reaction from him, and that she later claimed to police that he 
threatened her because she was afraid their marriage was ending. 
</P>
<P>
	She quoted Monique Brown as saying: ``If I'm going to get a  
divorce, I'd better look like the victim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who set NFL rushing and scoring records for the Cleveland  
Browns in the 1960s, faces misdemeanor charges of making a 
terrorist threat and vandalism for bashing his wife's car with a 
shovel. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, the prosecution has portrayed Brown as an  
abuser and his wife as a classic battered woman who cried for help 
then rescinded all claims of abuse in order to keep her marriage 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown testified Wednesday that she had lied about her  
husband's behavior and saying, among other things, she had given 
him permission to smash the car. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald said Monique Brown told her she believed her husband  
was having an affair and was going to leave her and move to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt he was going to leave me, so I left him,'' Monique  
Brown told her, the psychiatrist said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mrs. Brown has a borderline personality disorder,'' and such  
personalities have ``a long history of instability, fear of being 
alone and fear of being abandoned,'' she testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown tends to idealize men she is involved with, then  
fears they will reject her and so rejects them first. 
</P>
<P>
	She quoted Monique Brown as saying: ``I freaked out. I felt  
totally out of control. I felt I was being abandoned. ... I felt he 
was trying to break me like my step dad did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the doctor took the stand, the defense called Brown's  
personal consultant, Duane Moody, who related a long list of his 
felony arrests and convictions before he came under Brown's 
influence a year ago and reformed himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Moody said he went to the police station with Monique Brown the  
night of June 15 and heard her trying to rescind her allegations 
against her husband, who was arrested that night. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald was still on the stand when the case recessed for the  
holiday weekend. Outside court, Brown told reporters that this was 
the first time he had heard a report of his wife's alleged mental 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think my wife has been very brave and courageous to open  
herself up to a doctor,'' he said. ``I have so much respect for 
her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, the widow of Brown's closest friend told  
jurors that the Hall of Famer was always nonviolent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never seen him angry at a human being,'' said Shirley  
Hughley, who sobbed through much of her testimony as she recalled 
the 40-year friendship between Brown and George Hughley, a law 
enforcement officer. 
</P>
<P>
	She acknowledged that Monique Brown once sought refuge at the  
Hughley home after an argument with Brown but she said it was 
merely a dispute over business and the fact that ``he wouldn't pay 
attention to her in their argument so she took action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said Monique Brown spent the night at their home and the  
next day she drove her back to the Brown home. 
</P>
<P>
	After her husband died in February, Hughley said Brown retreated  
and she didn't see him for two or three months. But since then, 
they have spent a lot of time together, ``holding each other and 
talking about George and crying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a break in the proceedings while the judge was conferring  
with lawyers, Brown sat at the counsel table with his hands over 
his face and shook with sobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughley was preceded to the witness stand by Brown's  
housekeeper, Magdalena Monteroso, who said she never saw any 
violence between the Browns, saw no signs of injury on Monique 
Brown and said, ``I see them always hugging and together and 
loving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On cross-examination, the housekeeper acknowledged she wasn't  
always with them and encountered them only occasionally during her 
chores. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside court, Brown told reporters he has made his life's work  
to teach gang members not to show their anger and feels he is a 
model of peaceful behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the charge that he smashed the windows on a car, he said  
``I was frustrated and I broke the windows. ... It's a question of 
is it legal to break your own property.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He denied that he ever threatened his wife and, as the trial  
neared its conclusion, he said, ``regardless of what happens, you 
will never see this black man on his knees. I'm not a slave. I am a 
free, strong black man and that may be an issue with a lot of 
people.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Mull Romanowski Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Scientists are divided over whether a diet drug  
allegedly used by Denver Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski could 
be abused. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities in suburban Douglas County, where Romanowski lives,  
said Thursday they were investigating whether the player obtained 
the drug phentermine through fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski's lawyers have denounced investigators for releasing  
information before any charges have been filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists disagree on whether the drug, used alone, could be  
abused. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it has great abuse potential,'' said Jim Hill,  
obesity researcher at the University of Colorado Health Sciences 
Center in Denver. ``A lot of physicians are comfortable prescribing 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, president of the North American Association for the Study  
of Obesity, added, ``I can't believe it is being used to enhance 
performance. It's nothing like amphetamines, though it is a 
stimulant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It may not be as addictive as cocaine, but it has abuse  
potential,'' said Paul Wellman, head of the psychology department 
at Texas A&AMP;M. 
</P>
<P>
	One study in Los Angeles found that many users of methadone, a  
drug used to treat heroin addiction, also took phentermine, Wellman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Brinton of Orem, Utah, who has prescribed phentermine  
hundreds of times, said it can make patients feel they have more 
energy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes you feel good,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Brinton said he has taken it himself, at a maximum dose of 60  
milligrams a day, and doubts it affects performance, although ``it 
does raise the metabolism a little.'' He said he didn't know what 
the impact of taking a larger dose might be. 
</P>
<P>
	The use of phentermine with fenfluramine, in a combination  
called ``fen-phen,'' has been linked to potentially fatal heart 
valve damage. Wellman has testified for plaintiffs in lawsuits 
filed against the manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski's lawyers, meanwhile, denied he did anything illegal.  
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Springer, one of Romanowski's lawyers, said at a news  
conference Thursday that authorities have been harassing his 
client. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is truly disappointing when a decent, good family man gives  
of himself to the community and charitable organizations and has 
his good name and character assassinated under the circumstances 
simply because he finds himself to be a Denver Bronco,'' Springer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The allegations are scandalous.''  
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski and his wife, Julie, attended the news conference,  
but declined to answer questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Attila Denes, spokesman for the sheriff's department, said  
investigators have recommended felony criminal charges be filed 
against Romanowski, his wife, Dr. Randall Snook of Littleton and 
Loretta Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the four has been arrested.  
</P>
<P>
	Denes said Snook wrote eight prescriptions for phentermine for  
Mrs. Romanowski and Johnson between September 1998 and August. He 
alleged the drugs were obtained primarily for Romanowski. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer said the drug is legal and is not banned by the NFL.  
</P>
<P>
	``What Bill Romanowski did here was approved and encouraged by a  
doctor, and has been ratified by at least one other doctor,'' 
Springer said. ``In order to avoid publicity, the doctor wrote the 
prescription in the name of somebody else. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is our opinion ... Bill has not violated any laws.''  
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's Capt. Bill Walker said his deputies and Drug  
Enforcement Administration agents took the case to prosecutors 
Thursday following a two-month investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision on whether Romanowski will be charged probably won't  
be made until next week, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski could be charged with felony counts of fraud and  
deceit and conspiracy, and a misdemeanor charge of unlawful use of 
a controlled substance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
