<DOCNO> APW19990903.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 07:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NatWest Seeks L&AMP;G Acquisition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- National Westminster Bank PLC, Britain's  
third-largest bank, is negotiating to buy life insurance and 
pension provider Legal &AMP; General Group PLC, the companies announced 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither company provided any details, but The Financial Times  
reported Natwest would pay $17 billion in a deal that mixed cash 
and stock. 
</P>
<P>
	A joint statement by the companies and the London Stock Exchange  
said the takeover talks ``may or may not lead to a recommended 
offer being made by Natwest for Legal &AMP; General.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The simple truth is that we are in discussions. There is no  
deal,'' Natwest spokesman Steve Coulton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in Natwest dropped sharply on the news, trading at  
$18.52, a 4 percent decrease from Thursday's close. Shares in Legal 
&AMP; General -- which would become part of a powerful new force in 
British financial services -- rose 16 cents to $3.23, a 5 percent 
increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The move marks a turnabout for Natwest, which in recent years  
has been retrenching. It sold most of its global equities business 
to Bankers Trust Corp. of New York and Deutsche Morgan Grenfell for 
$300 million in December 1997, saying it did a poor job running the 
equities business. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Times said a definitive statement was expected  
next week and that NatWest's offer will be worth $3.36 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal &AMP; General chief executive David Prosser would join the  
NatWest board to run the retail banking and life assurance 
businesses, and both the chairman and the chief executive of 
NatWest would retain their roles in the newly enlarged group, the 
newspaper added. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
