<DOCNO> APW19990903.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 12:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baptist Foundation Losses Feared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- To Robert and Linda Hunt, the Baptist Foundation  
of America seemed like the perfect way to ensure their teen-age son 
Brian would get a college education without going into debt or 
having to juggle a job and studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert's mother had left the family ``five figures'' in  
investments with the foundation when she died in 1996, and the 
Hunts promptly earmarked some of it for their son, now 19. 
</P>
<P>
	But now Brian's plans -- and those of 13,000 other investors --  
are in doubt. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the foundation froze all new and existing accounts,  
and state regulators ordered a halt in securities sales. State 
investigators say the foundation misrepresented the securities and 
their returns and doesn't have enough money to cover all the 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	State regulators estimate that investors had poured $483 million  
into the foundation by the end of 1998. When, or if, the Hunts and 
others will see their money is unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Sendrow, director of the securities division at the Arizona  
Corporation Commission, said the investigation could take months. 
</P>
<P>
	For Brian Hunt, who is from Prescott, Ariz., the uncertainty  
means working full time while attending college. For others, it 
could mean the loss of life savings or scaling back retirement 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The First Southern Baptist Church of Glendale invested more than  
$1.5 million with the BFA and planned to use the money for a new 
church in suburban Phoenix, said its pastor, Mark Mucklow. Mucklow 
said while the church awaits results of the investigation, it is 
looking at other ways of financing the $3 million building. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are trying to find God's will,'' he said. ``We don't hold  
any animosity. We want to know what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The BFA was created in 1948 by the Arizona Southern Baptist  
Convention and manages money for Southern Baptist charities. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors -- particularly church members -- were lured by high  
interest rates and assurances that the investment money would 
benefit churches and ministries, according to investigators. 
Literature from late 1997 promised returns ranging from 6 percent 
for a six-month note to 11 percent for a 15-year note. 
</P>
<P>
	Sendrow said it looks like the foundation ran into problems in  
the 1980s with the decline of the real estate market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rather than writing them down, they apparently engaged in a  
series of manipulative operations to hide their losses,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	BFA officials say they are cooperating with the investigation  
and reviewing their assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Management changes have already taken place. On Aug. 26, the BFA  
board fired William Crotts, the foundation's president since 1982, 
its legal counsel and its controller. Still, 136 staff members 
remain on the payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Feigin, executive director of Washington-based North  
American Securities Administrators Association, which represents 
state securities regulators, said investors tend to trust 
investments with religious or other common bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The trust ``can be intoxicating,'' he said. ``Unfortunately with  
investing that always means a higher risk. You have to treat them 
like strangers or you face a greater risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even the letter dated Aug. 7 telling investors that their  
accounts had been frozen used religion: ``God has not promised that 
every day would be easy. And God has promised that he would be with 
us every step of the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hunt said of the whole affair, ``I'm not willing to give it  
our soul. She and her family, unlike her late mother-in-law, are 
not Southern Baptist. But her family is Christian, she said, and 
will not ``write off an entire denomination or entire agency of a 
denomination.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
