<DOCNO> APW19990903.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 08:09:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More FBI-Waco Evidence Is Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Roundly criticized for not disclosing evidence  
related to its 1993 assault on the Branch Davidian cult, the FBI 
released a videotape on which an FBI commander is heard authorizing 
the use of incendiary tear gas hours before a deadly fire ended the 
Davidians' 51-day standoff with federal agents. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI made the tape public Thursday as Attorney General Janet  
Reno asked an outsider to head an independent inquiry into the 
FBI's long-denied use of flammable weapons during the April 19, 
1993, assault near Waco, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin confirmed Reno's  
decision to seek someone outside the FBI and the Justice Department 
to head the inquiry, but declined to identify the candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those said to be on the informal candidate list were two  
former Republican senators, John Danforth of Missouri and Warren 
Rudman of New Hampshire, as well as former Iran-Contra prosecutor 
Dan Webb. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House, FBI Director Louis Freeh and congressional  
Democrats and Republicans alike have suggested that Reno sidestep 
her department and the FBI's investigative resources in favor of an 
independent review. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton ``is deeply concerned that the attorney  
general appears to have been misled and may have been lied to'' 
about what went on at Waco, White House spokesman Jake Siewert said 
Thursday as the president vacationed in upstate New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI's admission last week that combustible tear gas was  
used, recanting six years of claims to the contrary, provoked a 
furor on and off Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Reno-ordered probe, congressional hearings  
will be convened this fall and House Judiciary Committee Chairman 
Henry Hyde, R-Ill, is pushing for a congressional commission that 
he believes could conduct a review free from the bitter 
partisanship exhibited during earlier Waco hearings on Capitol 
Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	The infrared videotape made public Thursday, recorded from an  
FBI plane, runs from just before 6 a.m. to 8 a.m. on the final 
morning of the 51-day siege -- covering the period during which the 
FBI assault began. 
</P>
<P>
	That footage, which FBI officials said was recently discovered  
at the FBI Hostage Rescue Team's offices in Quantico, Va., was 
taken into custody Wednesday by federal marshals at Justice's 
instruction. The Hostage Rescue Team was in charge of operations 
during the siege. 
</P>
<P>
	A second videotape, which runs from 8 a.m. to 10:42 a.m.,  
surfaced Thursday; and FBI officials were taking steps to release 
it publicly as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Bureau officials had previously insisted in sworn affidavits  
that they didn't have any infrared video footage before 10:42 a.m. 
-- hours after the tear-gas assault began at 5:55 a.m. FBI spokesman 
Tron Brekke said the apparent discrepancy is ``a legitimate point 
for inquiry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The early morning tape captured a radio transmission in which an  
FBI field commander granted permission for an agent to lob military 
incendiary tear-gas rounds at a concrete bunker 40 yards from the 
Davidians' compound. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can try it?'' asked the rescue team's supervisory special  
agent, Stephen P. McGavin, after saying that an agent could ``with 
relative safety'' use a vehicle as cover and fire military tear gas 
canisters into the bunker. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, that's affirmative,'' answered Richard M. Rogers, the  
rescue team's assistant special agent in charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Brekke said bureau officials decided to release the video and a  
transcript because the action ``clearly demonstrates that we are 
interested in the facts concerning Waco to come out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's in our interest,'' he added. ``Our credibility's been  
hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said the conversation took place at 7:49 a.m. -- nearly  
two hours after the tear-gas assault began but hours before flames 
began racing through the Davidians' wooden home at 12:07 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI and Reno, who have been harshly criticized over the Waco  
assault and its deadly ending, have said there was no evidence to 
suggest the blaze was set by the pyrotechnic devices. 
</P>
<P>
	Cult leader David Koresh and some 80 followers died during the  
inferno, some from gunshot wounds, others from the fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 07:50:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israel Says Peace Deal Imminent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Momentum built today in the quest for a new  
Israel-Palestinian land-for-security deal, with Israeli Foreign 
Minister David Levy saying the two sides were near an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli officials speaking on condition of anonymity said  
negotiators had resolved a dispute over the release of Palestinian 
prisoners that had delayed the accord. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement by Prime Minister Ehud Barak's office said ``there  
is a possibility'' the agreement would be signed Saturday. The 
Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh has been proposed has a 
venue. 
</P>
<P>
	However, speaking to reporters in the Gaza Strip, Palestinian  
leader Yasser Arafat said there were still difficulties. Asked what 
were the main obstacles blocking an agreement, Arafat pointed to an 
``attempt to escape from the obligations which had been signed and 
agreed upon.'' He did not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at a joint news conference after meeting with U.S.  
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Levy expressed optimism a 
deal would be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very close to reaching a final agreement between the  
two sides for the betterment of the peace process,'' Levy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright played down her involvement. ``I was there basically in  
the role of facilitator. Perhaps I shouldn't introduce a new term 
into all of this, but maybe I was just the handmaiden,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had excellent meetings here ... with the prime  
minister and his team,'' she said. ``We are hopeful that this 
agreement will be concluded and we will be able to move forward in 
the comprehensive peace process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One Israeli official said the dispute over the prisoners had  
been resolved after the Palestinians accepted an Israeli offer to 
release 350 Palestinians held for anti-Israeli activities. The 
Palestinians initially had insisted on the release of 400 
prisoners. Earlier reports said the Israeli offer stood at 356 
prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the agreement on prisoner releases, the Israeli  
officials said there was still disagreement one a clause barring 
both sides from taking unilateral actions in the West Bank and Gaza 
Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute over the prisoners had drawn Albright into a shuttle  
diplomacy she never sought. She held talks Thursday in Alexandria, 
Egypt, with Arafat, and in Jerusalem early today with Barak to try 
to resolve the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak had issued a veiled ultimatum after his meeting with  
Albright, saying the Palestinians had until today to come up with a 
satisfactory answer. If such a response was not received, Israel 
would implement the original Wye River land-for-security agreement 
of last October to the letter. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Palestinians had initially sought exactly that, it  
appears that both sides would benefit from carrying out the revised 
agreement instead. The Palestinians would get more West Bank land 
sooner and win the release of more prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israelis would gain because the projected new agreement  
carries a tentative target date -- September 2000 -- for a permanent 
agreement and would thus defuse the threat of a unilateral 
Palestinian declaration of statehood. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to justify their brinksmanship, both sides have said the  
release of prisoners was a fundamental and emotional issue. Israel 
has said that as a matter of principle, it cannot release 
Palestinians who killed Israelis in terror attacks. The 
Palestinians have said that as part of peacemaking, the bloody 
slate of the past has to be wiped clean and that former guerrillas 
must win their freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	The last-minute deadlock had changed Albright's role from  
honored guest to mediator. Until now, she had held back, operating 
on the assumption the most successful agreements are the product of 
direct negotiations between the parties with minimal outside 
intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	But as prospects waned for a signing ceremony Thursday in  
Alexandria, a resigned Albright stepped in. ``It is natural that 
while I am here I try to be of assistance,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other thorny issues have been settled in recent days. The  
parties settled on a five-month timetable for a withdrawal from 
part of the West Bank -- starting at the beginning of this month and 
ending Jan. 20. They have also agreed that talks on a permanent 
peace agreement should begin immediately after the first pullback, 
and that the negotiations should be concluded within a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft of the new accord also contains a clause saying both  
sides should refrain from unilateral actions. For the Palestinians, 
this would mean that Israel will not massively expand or build new 
Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, or change the 
status quo of Jerusalem. For Israel, this would be an assurance 
that the Palestinians will not declare statehood before a peace 
accord is reached. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli officials said there were last-minute disagreements  
over this clause. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 09:54:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Says IMF May Delay Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund's next loan  
installment to Russia may be delayed, the country's finance 
minister said Friday as he insisted that no previous IMF money was 
misspent. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said the IMF board in  
Washington, which had planned to meet later this month, may not 
convene until October to discuss releasing the second installment 
of a $4.5 billion loan to help Russia pay its debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian officials have said that a visiting IMF delegation was  
satisfied with the government's adherence to loan conditions. The 
IMF team flew out on Friday, but did not comment on its findings. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF loan is being used to pay back existing Russian debts to  
the fund. The amount of the next installment has been set at $640 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's efforts to obtain the next installment have been  
complicated by U.S. newspaper reports questioning whether the 
Russian government may have diverted IMF money. The IMF says it has 
no evidence of any wrongdoing by Russian authorities, but is taking 
the allegations seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no basis for anyone to say that there are problems  
with the use of funds from international sources,'' Kasyanov said. 
</P>
<P>
	The finance minister also said that increased government  
controls were helping control capital flight from Russia, a major 
problem that is estimated to drain $1 billion out of the country 
each month. 
</P>
<P>
	In other economic developments Friday, Russia's exports have  
fallen 5 percent and imports have crashed 45 percent in the first 
eight months of this year compared to last year, Kasyanov said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Russia consumer prices rose 1.2 percent in August, down  
from 2.8 percent a month earlier, the Russian Statistics Agency 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation was 29.5 percent for the first eight months of the  
year, the government statistics agency said. However, the monthly 
inflation rate has been coming down since a financial crisis a year 
ago sent prices surging. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation for all of 1998 was 84 percent.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 16:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Pastor Gets Va. Prison Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANASSAS, Va. (AP) -- Former pastor James Ogle was sentenced  
Friday to eight years in prison for asking a parishioner to join 
him in a plot to kill each other's wives. 
</P>
<P>
	In a rambling, tearful statement, Ogle apologized to his wife,  
children, friends and the congregation of the Bull Run Bible 
Fellowship in Manassas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was never my intention to put my wife's life in danger,''  
Ogle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ogle, 46, was convicted in June of attempted murder and  
solicitation of a felony. 
</P>
<P>
	Ogle, who blamed his wife for his career failures and had had an  
affair with a parishioner, had suggested to Scott Jinks that they 
swap murders, police testified. Ogle was counseling Jinks and his 
wife about their marriage at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I take care of your wife, will you take care of mine?''  
Ogle asked Jinks, according to police. Jinks went to police and 
taped several conversations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 07:50:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Israel Says Peace Deal Imminent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
