<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	U.S.-China Trade Talks Planned  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and China have scheduled  
their first trade talks in four months, signaling a thaw in the 
countries' recent chilly relations. The technical-level discussions 
will be held next week, probably in Beijing, in advance of a 
meeting between President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin 
in New Zealand. Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Richard Fisher 
said yesterday the technical-level meeting will be a 
``stock-taking'' of where the two countries stand on negotiations 
to bring China into the World Trade Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Says Protect U.S. Coastlines  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore cruised Boston Harbor and  
then went ashore to announce new federal initiatives aimed at 
protecting America's coastlines and ocean waters. ``They're not 
just part of the environment, but they're an engine of our 
economy,'' Gore said of oceans in a speech at the New England 
Aquarium. ``We need to take bold steps to protect the oceans.'' 
Gore announced that President Clinton had signed a proclamation 
yesterday giving U.S. authorities the right to enforce 
environmental, customs and immigration laws at sea within 24 
nautical miles from shore, up from 12 miles. 

</P>
<P>
	Movement in Mideast Peace  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Drawn into a shuttle diplomacy she never  
sought, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright pressed Israelis and 
Palestinians to resolve their disagreement over the release of a 
few dozen prisoners and sign an agreement. Officials in Egypt -- 
another broker in last-minute efforts to revive the Wye memorandum 
-- indicated that a signing ceremony is set for today at Sharm 
el-Sheik, an isolated Red Sea resort. The Information Ministry even 
chartered a plane for journalists. The Egyptians had hoped to host 
the signing ceremony in Alexandria -- Albright's first stop -- 
yesterday, but the disagreement over 44 Palestinian prisoners 
stymied an otherwise completed agreement. 

</P>
<P>
	More FBI-Waco Evidence Is Found  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Roundly criticized for not disclosing evidence  
related to its 1993 assault on the Branch Davidian cult, the FBI 
released a videotape on which an FBI commander is heard authorizing 
the use of incendiary tear gas hours before a deadly fire ended the 
Davidians' 51-day standoff with federal agents. The FBI made the 
tape public yesterday as Attorney General Janet Reno asked an 
outsider to head an independent inquiry into the FBI's long-denied 
use of flammable weapons during the April 19, 1993, assault near 
Waco, Texas. 

</P>
<P>
	Wildfire Burning Calif. Economy  
</P>
<P>
	BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters battled back flames  
from huge wildfires that roared around mountain resort towns 
yesterday as hotel owners and shopkeepers feared the pall of smoke 
would kill their usually prosperous Labor Day business. Closed 
campgrounds and a canceled carnival had merchants worrying about 
the impact on tourism on the last holiday weekend of summer. ``It 
will affect business big time,'' said Barb Aker, owner of Gold Pan 
Dining. ``It's very, very slow. There's no traffic at all. Normally 
cars are piling in by now.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dennis Keeps Battering Coast  
</P>
<P>
	NAGS HEAD, N.C. (AP) -- Tropical Storm Dennis hung off North  
Carolina's Outer Banks for a third day yesterday and kept pounding 
away at the coast with 14-foot waves and 45 mph gusts, doing more 
damage to the beach than a single blow from a big hurricane. ``It 
is immensely worse as far as damage to the shoreline and beachfront 
retreat,'' said Orrin Pilkey, a Duke University coastal geologist. 
Although a hurricane can be deadly because it can blow down 
buildings, it typically ``goes across the islands very quickly.'' 
The assault on the North Carolina coast has been going on since 
early Monday. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks End Down  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks closed down 1.26 points Friday as  
the Nikkei Stock Average fell to 17,629.99. In New York on 
Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down 94.67 at 
10,843.21, having worked its way back from a loss of 205 points 
earlier in the session. 

</P>
<P>
	Castro: Athletes Victims of Plot  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- President Fidel Castro charged last night that  
Cuba's own urine tests and other evidence proves that the two 
weightlifters stripped of gold medals for drug use during the Pan 
American Games were actually drug free. ``It was all a colossal 
lie, an infamous and shameful lie, a criminal plundering of merits 
won through denial, tenacity, consecration and sacrifice,'' the 
Cuban leader said on national television. Castro called for the 
unusual television program, which included 14 foreign journalists 
and five Cuban journalists. No questions were allowed until the 
completion of the second half of the program, scheduled to resume 
at 8:30 p.m. today. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
