<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep: Let Feds Watch Amusement Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a spate of fatal roller coaster  
accidents, a member of Congress wants to restore the Consumer 
Product Safety Commission's oversight of amusement park rides. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., said Friday he will introduce  
legislation giving the commission power to set standards for rides, 
perform inspections and investigations, recall unsafe equipment and 
impose civil penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	``As these rides get higher, faster and more technologically  
sophisticated, the potential for unforeseen catastrophe rises as 
well,'' said Markey, the top Democrat on the House Commerce 
subcommittee on telecommunications, trade and consumer protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission regulated rides at amusement parks and temporary  
sites, such as carnivals and fairs, prior to 1981. That year, after 
court challenges, Congress exempted rides at permanent sites from 
the commission's oversight. 
</P>
<P>
	``That left nobody watching the store,'' said Ann Brown, the  
CPSC chairwoman. ``If Congress were to vote to return safety 
authority to the CPSC, we would certainly welcome it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission still regulates rides at carnivals and fairs. It  
collects death and injury data from all rides. 
</P>
<P>
	Although 38 states regulate amusement park rides, the rules vary  
widely. Florida, for example, has exemptions for parks with over 
1,000 employees, said Russ Rader, the commission's spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve states and the District of Columbia do not regulate  
rides: Alabama, Arizona, California, Kansas, Mississippi, Missouri, 
Montana, North Dakota, Rhode Island, South Dakota, Utah and 
Vermont. 
</P>
<P>
	Four deaths last month called the safety of rides into question.  
</P>
<P>
	In Ocean City, N.J., a mother and daughter died when they were  
ejected from a roller-coaster car at Gillian's Wonderland Pier 
after it suddenly slid backward from a 30-foot ascent and crashed 
into another car. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Great America park in Santa Clara, Calif., a disabled  
12-year-old boy died on the Drop Zone ride when he slipped out of a 
harness. At Paramount's Kings Dominion in Doswell, Va., a man who 
had partially wiggled out of a shoulder harness died when he fell 
from the Shockwave, a stand-up roller coaster. 
</P>
<P>
	``The unusual events of the past couple of weeks have us all a  
bit mystified,'' said John Graff, president of the International 
Association of Amusement Parks and Attractions. ``But we are 
absolutely certain it's not because of any change in the safety 
practices of the industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graff said the industry still has an extraordinary safety  
record, with serious injuries occurring in one out of every 25 
million rides. At least 95 percent of parks fall under some sort of 
state or local regulation, and more than half the states without 
regulations have no or very few parks, he said. Additional federal 
oversight ``would be unwise,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
