<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wildfires Hinder Tourism in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. (AP) -- Spirits lifted today as only a thin  
stain of brown smoke marred a blue sky over San Bernardino 
Mountains resorts a few miles from a huge fire that jeopardized 
vital Labor Day weekend tourist business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Turning the corner,'' declared the headline of the fire  
command's daily situation report for the West's biggest wildfire, a 
61,770-acre blaze that was 50 percent contained. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the progress would embolden tourists to head to the  
popular region east of Los Angeles was uncertain, however. 
Merchants have already seen profits blow away with the towering 
billows of smoke that poured off the range most of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Vacancy signs eagerly blinked along the road circling the lake  
6,750 feet high in the mountains, while business owners Thursday 
fielded hundreds of phone calls from tourists worried about reports 
of the big wildfire just six miles to the northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our last hurrah of the season and bad press could ruin  
the tourism industry up here,'' said Barb Aker, co-owner of Gold 
Pan Dining and Nugget Room Cocktails in Fawnskin, a tiny hamlet on 
the north side of the lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabins at Big Bear Lodge are normally packed at this time, said  
manager Chuck Smith. But they were only at 50 percent occupancy 
Thursday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although no smoke or soot reached the resorts that line the  
lake, the drone of a steady stream of helicopters could be heard as 
they dipped buckets into the water and hustled back to the fire's 
hottest spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Roads, by contrast, were quiet.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to make for a very slow weekend,'' said Damon  
Dennis, manager of Alpine Sports Center, which sells camping 
supplies. ``Usually we're very busy by now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called Willow fire closed 13 campgrounds and halted all  
travel on San Bernardino National Forest land north of the lake. By 
today, the cost of fighting the blaze reached $6.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The blaze was blamed on an illegal campfire but now classified  
as ``under investigation,'' meaning the cause is unclear. It is one 
of seven large California fires that have burned about 125,000 
acres of forest and desert land. Elsewhere across the West, 
firefighters made progress against six other significant wildfires 
in Montana, Utah and Idaho, where a 35,118-acre grass blaze near 
the Snake River community of Glenns Ferry was contained Wednesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	The worries of Big Bear-area merchants were mirrored in  
communities near other California fires. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3,300-acre Mixing fire in Riverside County was fully  
contained, but it still put a dent in business at nearby Idyllwild. 
Gary Busher said his family's Oak Crest Lodge had only one of five 
rooms booked, and just for tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``And we have nothing else for the weekend,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles County, some campgrounds in Angeles National  
Forest were closed because of a 7,100-acre blaze north of Azusa. It 
was 68 percent contained today. 
</P>
<P>
	In Northern California, firefighters struggled with clusters of  
wildfires started by lightning storms on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27,100-acre High Complex fire in the Shasta-Trinity area --  
actually 19 lightning-ignited blazes burning in a cluster 22 miles 
north of Redding -- was 87 percent surrounded. Containment was 
expected Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
