<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Mom's Blues Can Hinder Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Children do worse on developmental tests if  
their mothers are depressed, but a mother's depression does less 
damage if the family is well off financially, says a study released 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers studied 1,200 families to see if mother's depression  
hindered her children's learning ability in the crucial first three 
years of life. 
</P>
<P>
	They questioned mothers beginning at their children's births and  
visited their homes to watch mother-child interaction. When the 
children were 3, their school readiness -- things such as counting 
and knowing colors and shapes -- was tested. 
</P>
<P>
	Mothers who were chronically depressed were more likely to have  
children who scored lower on the tests, concluded the eight-year 
study financed by the National Institutes of Health. The study will 
appear in the September issue of the journal Developmental 
Psychology. 
</P>
<P>
	But depressed women who had higher incomes, and other advantages  
such as higher education, were more sensitive to their children's 
needs, and their depression had lesser effect on their children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money seems to be a key issue,'' said one of the researchers,  
University of North Carolina child development specialist Martha 
Cox. ``It could be a case of women in positions of seeking better 
outside child care, or giving themselves more breaks, or buying 
more services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These women have more options or more things to turn to, to  
keep their depression from affecting their relationship with the 
child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reseachers recruited families from Arkansas, California, Kansas,  
Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, Virginia, North Carolina, Washington 
and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	A mother's depression is problematical because of the theory  
that depressed moms wouldn't interact with their children. And 
researchers said maternal blues may have the worst affect on the 
youngest babies, who depend more on their mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	The study showed that if mothers were particularly sensitive to  
their babies, regardless of depression, the children developed 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``Exploration and play are such an important way that children  
learn in the early years,'' Cox explained. ``Having a mother that 
can facilitate that exploration and play is important to the 
children's development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For example, if a mother and child were playing with a book or  
puzzle, the sensitive mother would pay attention to what the child 
was trying to do, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study children are now in third grade and will be followed  
at least through sixth grade. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen percent of the families were headed by single mothers,  
but interactions with fathers and other adults were not measured. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the study may have underestimated depression's impact  
because teen mothers, disabled children or substance abusers also 
were not studied. The poorest families wound up dropping out of the 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	School readiness has long worried educators, given that poor and  
other disadvantaged children often get to kindergarten without 
skills necessary for school success. 
</P>
<P>
	The research shows families in which the mother suffers  
depression need to seek help, said Sarah Friedman, who coordinated 
the study for the NIH's National Institute for Child Health and 
Human Development. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women need to know if they feel depressed, it's not only about  
them,'' she said. ``It's also going to affect their children.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0119 </DOCNO>
