<HEADLINE> Park Ride Inspections Bill Advances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A bill requiring annual inspections of  
amusement park rides moved one step closer to law with final 
approval Friday from the state Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure was introduced after an accident in December on a  
sailing ship ride at Disneyland killed one man and injured his wife 
and a park worker. It gained renewed attention last month after 
accidents at two Northern California amusement parks. 
</P>
<P>
	A 12-year-old disabled boy was killed Aug. 22 after falling out  
of the Drop Zone Stunt Tower at Paramount's Great America in Santa 
Clara. Three days later, 28 passengers were trapped for nearly four 
hours on a roller coaster at Six Flags Marine World in Vallejo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate passed the bill 30-6. The measure faces a final vote  
next week in the Assembly, which approved an earlier draft by a 
60-15 margin, before going to Gov. Gray Davis. Davis had not yet 
taken a position on the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	California requires inspections of rides at traveling carnivals,  
but not at the state's 72 permanent amusement parks. There have 
been 16 fatal accidents in the past 28 years on amusement rides in 
California, including 12 at permanent amusement parks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
