<DOCNO> APW19990903.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 07:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *Almeric L. Christian    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- Almeric L.  
Christian, the first native of the U.S. Virgin Islands to be named 
a judge in the territory's District Court, died Wednesday at age 79 
of an undisclosed illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian was appointed by President Nixon in 1969 and retired  
in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's most controversial decisions were in two 1970s cases  
in which he ruled that immigrants' children had a right to public 
education. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Mary Hudson    	
</P>
<P>
	PRAIRIE VILLAGE, Kan. (AP) -- Mary Hudson, a self-made  
businesswoman who built an oil empire worth $325 million that 
landed her as one of the few women on the Forbes 400 list, died 
Thursday of cancer. She was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in 1933, when her husband was killed in a truck  
accident, Ms. Hudson borrowed $200 from her father to open her 
first Hudson Oil Co. station in Kansas City. It was the first of 
more than 300 gas stations and convenience stores that would make 
her one of America's richest entrepreneurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hudson said that when Forbes listed her on its list of 400  
richest Americans, in the mid-1970s, she was worth about $325 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	She would also live to see much of her business fall apart in  
the 1980s following a string of court judgments for overcharging 
customers at the pumps and for underpaying some employees. She 
pleaded no contest to conspiracy and was ordered to perform 200 
hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hudson rebounded in the final years of her career to oversee  
a smaller, rejuvenated operation. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Milton Jack Mirman    	
</P>
<P>
	DREXEL HILL, Pa. (AP) -- Milton Jack Mirman, an authority on U.S.  
stamps and a major stamp dealer for years, died Aug. 27 of cancer. 
He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirman started attending stamp auctions as an amateur dealer  
when he was 14. In 1950, he decided to make his hobby his business 
and bought the dealership Stanley Gibbons Inc., one of the leading 
traders for stamp collectors in the U.S. For years, the Gibbons 
catalogue served as a pricing guide for American stamps. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirman headed the company until he sold it to the  
Intergovernmental Philatelic Corp. in 1979. He stayed in its 
management until he retired in 1997. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Bishop P. Francis Murphy    	
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Auxiliary Bishop P. Francis Murphy, who worked  
for social justice and better interfaith relations during his over 
40 years with the Catholic Church, died Thursday of cancer. He was 
66. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy was named auxiliary bishop by Pope Paul VI and appointed  
vicar general and western vicar in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy co-chaired the program committee for the 9th  
Jewish/Christian Workshop in 1986, which led to many initiatives, 
including the Baltimore Institute for Christian/Jewish Studies. He 
also was a board member of The Interfaith Alliance, an organization 
of Christian and Jewish leaders from across the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, Murphy co-founded Interfaith Housing of Wester,  
Maryland, Inc., an organization dedicated to developing safe and 
adequate housing for the poor. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Eugene Ostroff    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eugene Ostroff, longtime curator of  
photography at the National Museum of American History, died last 
month of cancer. He was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Ostroff retired in 1994 after 34 years with the Smithsonian  
Institution. He was credited with opening the museum's Hall of 
Photography in 1972 and organizing a number of special exhibitions. 
</P>
<P>
	After joining the Smithsonian in 1960, he pursued research into  
the history of photography and published his findings, mostly in 
technical and scientific periodicals. 
</P>
<P>
	He later consulted with museums around the world on standards  
for storing and displaying old photographs. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Stanley Weigel    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Retired U.S. District Judge Stanley Weigel,  
a gruff liberal who defended professors in loyalty oath cases, died 
Wednesday at age 93. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge since 1962, Weigel took semi-retired senior status in  
1982 but continued handling cases until he stepped down about two 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	His most prominent case started in the early 1970s, when inmates  
of Northern California prisons challenged their conditions of 
confinement. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, Weigel ordered improvements in conditions for 2,500  
inmates of the maximum-security lockup units at century-old San 
Quentin and Folsom prisons. 
</P>
<P>
	As a lawyer, starting in 1928, he specialized in antitrust  
cases, but he took on a civil liberties case in 1949 that other 
local lawyers shunned: the defense of 39 University of California 
professors who refused to take loyalty oaths. He won their 
reinstatement with back pay. 
</P>
<P>
	A Republican, Weigel was appointed to the bench by Democratic  
President Kennedy. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Henry R. Singleton    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Henry E. Singleton, an innovative engineer  
and co-founder of Teledyne Inc. who designed an aircraft guidance 
system used worldwide, has died. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	He died Tuesday of brain cancer at his home.  
</P>
<P>
	Singleton led one of the nation's largest conglomerates for  
three decades. He was known for his prowess on Wall Street and was 
a merger guru from the 1960s to the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	He launched Teledyne in 1960 as a semiconductor maker with his  
partner George Kozmetsky. Their first venture was building digital 
computers for aircraft and space exploration projects. Singleton 
developed the inertial guidance system now used in commercial and 
military aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	By the mid-1980s, conglomerates were not in favor with Wall  
Street and Teledyne began divesting itself. It also became involved 
in military procurement scandals and paid more than $100 million in 
fines to settle claims that it inflated bills to the Pentagon and 
falsified tests on electronic components. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes magazine listed Singleton as one of the nation's 400  
richest people last year with an estimated fortune of $750 million. 
Singleton retired as Teledyne's chief executive officer in 1986, 
but remained as chairman until 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
