<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kipketer, Szabo Near $1M Jackpot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- World champions Wilson Kipketer and  
Gabriela Szabo maintained their perfect records in the Golden 
League competition at the Van Damme meet Friday, putting them only 
one victory away from sharing the $1 million jackpot. 
</P>
<P>
	Kipketer, of Denmark, ran the season's best time in the 800  
meters, clocking 1 minute, 42.27 seconds, beating Hezekiel Sepeng 
by five meters. Kipketer was within world record pace after 400 
meters, but had too much to do on his own from then on and fell 
1.16 seconds short. Sepeng set a South African record of 1:42.69. 
</P>
<P>
	``The jackpot is out there,'' Kipketer said. ``It is like a  
lottery. I just have to run fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Szabo did just that to maintain her chance.  
</P>
<P>
	Morocco's Zahra Ouaziz tried to shake off Szabo for much of the  
women's 3,000-meter race, but the Romanian just bided her time and 
waited to outkick her. The result was similar to the World 
Championships at Seville last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Szabo finished in 8:25.82, her second-fastest time this year.  
</P>
<P>
	The two champions have won all six Golden League meets, and if  
they continue their streak through Tuesday's ISTAF Berlin meet, 
they will end up with $500,000 each as the overall jackpot would be 
sliced in half. 
</P>
<P>
	In a great performance which had no impact on the Golden League,  
Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj ran the second-fastest men's 3,000 in 
history, 7:23.09, only 2.42 seconds off Kenyan Daniel Komen's 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Steeplechase world record-holder Bernard Barmasai also won his  
sixth race out of six Friday, but the IAAF has eliminated him from 
the jackpot competition. If he wins the last of the seven races and 
is denied the Golden League purse, he said he might sue the IAAF. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot be employed somewhere and get no salary,'' he said.  
``I want to run good in Berlin and then afterwards do something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF punished Barmasai for saying he colluded with Kenyan  
teammate Christopher Koskei to determine the outcome of the Golden 
League race at Zurich. Barmasai denied he tried to fix the race. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Van Damme, he proved he was the best in his discipline,  
taking the lead at the halfway stage and building a 40-meter lead 
before finishing in 8:03.08, the second-best time of the season. 
Koskei, the world champion, finished four seconds back. 
</P>
<P>
	Barmasai finished fifth at the World Championships, but said the  
Zurich scandal had cost him too much sleep and concentration. 
</P>
<P>
	Marion Jones, the women's 100-meter world champion, was the only  
other athlete with a 5-for-5 record, but she has not recovered from 
the back injury sustained during the semifinals of the 200 at 
Seville and was a no-show here. 
</P>
<P>
	The meet had 53 medalists from the World Championships,  
including 18 world champions. The main absentee was triple gold 
medalist Maurice Greene, who is running in Britain over the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Bruny Surin, the silver medalist at Seville, won the  
100 in 10.04, edging Jon Drummond. 
</P>
<P>
	Surin could not make it a 100-200 double though. Michael  
Johnson, the 400 world champion and 200 and 400 record-holder, won 
the 200 at 19.93, .09 seconds off the season's best of Nigerian 
Francis Obikwelu. 
</P>
<P>
	Inger Miller continued to dominate the 200 in the absence of  
Jones, beating Beverly McDonald of Jamaica, matching their 1-2 
finish at Seville. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgium's Mohammed Mourhit set a European record for 10,000  
meters, breaking the mark of Portugal's Antonio Pinto by more than 
20 seconds in finishing second to Charles Kamathi of Kenya. Kamathi 
ran the year's fastest time, 26:51.49. The Moroccan-born Mourhit, 
now competing for Belgium, was timed at 26:52.30. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinto had set the previous mark of 27:12.47 at Oslo in July.  
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Hartwig, the American record-holder in the pole vault, made  
up for a disappointing showing at Seville, beating world champion 
Maksim Tarasov of Russia with a leap of 19 feet, 6 1/4 inches. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
