<HEADLINE> Top Marlins Pick Beckett Visits Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Florida Marlins first-round draft choice Josh  
Beckett got a good look Friday at Pro Player Stadium and wondered 
whether he'll ever pitch there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Aren't y'all going to have a new stadium?'' Beckett asked.  
</P>
<P>
	Team owner John Henry applauded that remark at a news conference  
introducing the 19-year-old Beckett to South Florida. Henry is 
leading the push for a new ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter how that campaign comes out, the brash Beckett expects  
to join the Marlins rotation soon. But after talking with general 
manager Dave Dombrowski, Beckett backed off an earlier prediction 
that he'll pitch in the 2001 All-Star Game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Dombrowski doesn't want me to rush,'' said Beckett, just  
out of high school. ``It's going to be wherever the development 
takes me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Marlins need pitching, and Beckett was encouraged to see  
22-year-old rookie A.J. Burnett starting Friday night against San 
Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes me happy that they're giving a young pitcher a  
chance,'' Beckett said. ``It brings a smile to your face thinking 
you can be a starting pitcher in the major leagues at his age.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett, the second overall selection in June's amateur draft,  
signed a $7 million big league contract that includes a $3.625 
million signing bonus, the second-highest ever. 
</P>
<P>
	What does a teen-ager do with so much money? The right-hander  
from Spring, Texas, said he just bought the ``Urban Cowboy'' CD, 
and he's shopping for a truck. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett played little baseball this summer. He'll pitch in the  
Fall Instructional League beginning Sept. 17. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty excited,'' he said. ``I'm still a fan right now.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
