<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jesuits Focus of Harassment Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- All John Bollard wanted to do was live his  
life by the laws of the Jesuits -- poverty, obedience and chastity. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he wants the Jesuits to live by the laws that apply to  
everyone else -- particularly the law that makes employers 
responsible when supervisors sexually harass employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Bollard is suing the California Province of the Jesuits for  
sexual harassment, claiming he was sent pornographic cards, invited 
to cruise gay bars, and subjected to unwanted advances by a dozen 
priests at a Jesuit seminary in Berkeley. 
</P>
<P>
	His suit brings the workings of a religious organization under  
the scrutiny of the courts -- a responsibility that federal courts 
have been unwilling to accept. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we lose this lawsuit, it means that the church can hide  
behind its history and its Roman collar and its pulpit and not have 
to face issues that every corporation and every other employer in 
this country has to face,'' Bollard said in an interview Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal courts, in a long series of rulings, have refused to  
allow clergy to sue churches for discrimination, saying judicial 
interference in religious decisions was either unauthorized by 
Congress or forbidden by the First Amendment's guarantee of 
religious freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	Bollard's lawsuit was dismissed last year by U.S. District Judge  
Susan Illston. The application of civil rights laws would amount to 
an ``interference of federal government in church autonomy,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals must decide whether  
Bollard can sue at all. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first time an ex-seminarian has sued the Jesuits for  
sexual harassment. It is also the first time a federal appeals 
court has been asked to decide if a religious organization is 
covered by the same sexual harassment laws that govern employers 
and schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's response may determine whether numerous churches are  
legally vulnerable in a time of increasing complaints of sexual 
misconduct by clergy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bollard's lawyers argue that a harassment case involves a  
secular question -- whether sexually offensive conduct occurred and 
was permitted -- that does not require delving into religious 
doctrine. 
</P>
<P>
	The question before the court, which heard arguments in June, is  
not whether Bollard was harassed but whether the government has any 
power to regulate a religious organization's treatment of its 
clergy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bollard, who left the Jesuits after eight years in 1996 and now  
teaches at a college in Southern California, is seeking an apology 
and $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't put in jeopardy the separation of church and  
state,'' he said of the suit. ``It calls them to an honesty and 
integrity that everybody is being called to in this day and age.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jesuits have not addressed his factual claims in their court  
papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bollard's lawyer, James Wagstaffe, argued in court papers that  
the Jesuits ``cannot be allowed to use the First Amendment as a 
shield for illegal activities that have nothing to do with 
religious beliefs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Jesuits and their supporters say that if Bollard can sue  
them over their response to his alleged harassment -- failing to 
fire or discipline the priests or otherwise protect him -- nothing 
is sacred. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, if allowed to proceed, would interfere with ``the core  
religious act -- the selection, assessment, retention and discipline 
of those who are designated to engage in a religion's mission,'' 
Paul Gaspari, lawyer for the Jesuit organizations in California and 
Oregon, said in court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Discrimination suits against religious organizations that have  
been dismissed by the courts include a female Buddhist minister 
whose funding was cut off, a female Salvation Army minister who was 
fired, a female chaplain dismissed by a Presbyterian hospital and a 
nun denied tenure by the Catholic University of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Bollard, who entered the seminary in 1988, said the harassment  
started a few years later with a birthday card with a picture of a 
naked man and suggestive language. A pornographic card from his 
supervisor read, ``Thought this might inspire some theological 
thoughts,'' the suit said. 
</P>
<P>
	He brought his complaints to his supervisors, and eventually to  
Father John Privett, the Provincial or head of the West Coast 
Jesuits, who he said advised him to avoid lawyers and asked him to 
release the Jesuits from liability. 
</P>
<P>
	Privett also gave him a gift, Bollard said: a coffee cup  
inscribed ``No Whining.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
