<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 15:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Funeral Held for Fritz Shurmur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Scott Shurmur said his father could never  
resist a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Family and friends gathered on a summery Friday morning at St.  
Francis Xavier Cathedral for the funeral for Fritz Shurmur, the 
Seattle Seahawks defensive coordinator whose peripatetic coaching 
career was capped with a Super Bowl title during his memorable 
years with the Green Bay Packers. 
</P>
<P>
	In delivering his father's eulogy, Scott Shurmur said that when  
Mike Holmgren offered Fritz Shurmur a new challenge last winter, he 
accepted it, even though it meant leaving Green Bay, the city he 
had come to call home and where he planned to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was to be a year or two of challenge, followed by a  
lifetime of fishing,'' Scott Shurmur said. 
</P>
<P>
	During his first weeks in Seattle, family members sensed a  
particular homesickness in the 67-year-old defensive coordinator's 
voice. The Seahawks embraced the teachings of their new coach 
during spring minicamps, but during a routine checkup in May, 
doctors discovered the cancer that eventually killed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur died Monday at his home in nearby Suamico. Shurmur and  
his wife, Peggy Jane, are members of St. Benedict Catholic Church 
in Suamico, but the funeral Mass was scheduled for the cathedral 
because of the large crowd of mourners. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 90-minute funeral Mass, the Rev. Gary Dantinne called  
Shurmur ``a person of faith. ... Maybe he's formulating God's new 
defense against evil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren cried during the service, which was attended by several  
Seahawks assistants as well as current Green Bay coaches Ray 
Rhodes, Sherman Lewis and Emmitt Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 25 current and former players attended the funeral.  
LeRoy Butler, Santana Dotson, Gilbert Brown and Bernardo Harris, 
all Packers defensive players under Shurmur, were pallbearers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad to lose a friend, because Fritz was a friend to all  
of us,'' said former Packers defensive end Reggie White, who 
attended with his wife, Sarah. ``It gets me inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur's career began at Albion College, his alma mater in  
Michigan. He was the coach at Wyoming and an assistant in the NFL 
for Detroit, New England, the Los Angeles Rams and Arizona 
Cardinals before coming to Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Shurmur said his father took particular joy in working in  
a small city like Green Bay, where ``he could be ice fishing 10 
minutes after practice.'' The Shurmurs built their retirement home 
next to a lake in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	As Shurmur's condition deteriorated during the summer, his  
favorite activity was watching exhibition games on television. 
Scott Shurmur said his father took pleasure in the Seahawks' 
defensive performance in an exhibition against San Francisco three 
weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the type of guy that really cared about his players,''  
White said. ``He had an intensity, and he really cared about the 
team. That's what made him the great coach he was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers observed a moment of silence for Shurmur before  
their 25-17 exhibition victory over Miami on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Before building the defenses that helped carry the Packers to  
consecutive Super Bowl victories, Shurmur was known for his 
unorthodox defensive schemes with the Rams that helped an otherwise 
undermanned team compete with the 49ers and the other powers of the 
1980s. He authored four books and an instructional video on 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Lining the walls of the funeral home during the visitation  
period earlier this week were more than three dozen flower 
arrangements, from private well-wishers as well as such former foes 
as the San Francisco 49ers, Indianapolis Colts, Chicago Bears, 
Atlanta Falcons and New Orleans Saints. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
