<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 19:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Volleyball Barred From Alero Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- American beach volleyball players just can't  
avoid controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years ago, they sparred with international officials over  
qualifying for the inaugural Olympic beach tournament at Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Karch Kiraly, the sport's biggest name, and three other top  
American players have been told by Association of Volleyball 
Professionals officials that they can't play in next weekend's 
Oldsmobile Alero Series, which is part of the inaugural U.S. 
Olympic Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	AVP officials, coming off last year's bankruptcy, feel the Alero  
Series is a competing tour. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Olympic Cup is a five-sport international competition  
scheduled next Thursday through Sunday in San Diego. Of the five 
sports, only beach volleyball has any qualification ramifications 
for the Olympics, and even that is up for debate between the AVP 
and the national governing body, USA Volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Volleyball set a Friday deadline for Kiraly and his partner,  
Adam Johnson, and the team of Dain Blanton and Eric Fonoimoana, to 
accept invitations to the Alero Series. The AVP refused to let them 
play. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have a great event and we're sorry they can't  
be here to help grow the sport,'' USA Volleyball official John 
Kessel said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Volleyball says the Alero Series is not a tour, but rather,  
a set of nine tournaments this year and next designed to help get 
U.S. teams into the international tournaments that are part of the 
Olympic qualification process. And the purses are big enough that 
younger teams can afford to compete abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiraly is the only volleyball player to win three Olympic gold  
medals, including the '96 beach title with Kent Steffes. His 
longtime rival, Sinjin Smith, will compete here. Earlier this 
summer Kiraly broke Smith's longstanding record of 139 career beach 
victories. Kiraly has 141 wins. 
</P>
<P>
	The top four U.S. pro players aren't the only ones skipping the  
Alero Series. There was room in the eight-team men's field for one 
of three Brazilian teams -- which are ranked 1-2-3 in the world -- 
but their federation said no men's team would come. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe they felt it would be a good tactical move not to play  
on our soil,'' Kessel said. Brazil is sending the top-ranked 
women's team of Adriana Behar-Shelda Bede. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Olympic Cup also will include women's basketball and  
softball, men's and women's swimming, and boxing. The women's 
Olympic softball team will be announced Monday, and the women's 
hoops team will include several WNBA stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Not surprisingly, politics and dueling sponsors are in the  
middle of the volleyball dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that the AVP is back on its feet after going through  
bankruptcy, it wants to protect its sponsors and other business 
interests. AVP players competed in the first Alero Series 
tournament in May, with Kiraly and Johnson winning it, but AVP head 
Bill Berger said Alero organizers haven't lived up to certain 
agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that we don't want to play, but the group that  
produces the event, despite the stars and stripes backdrop, is 
running a for-profit venture,'' Berger said. ``At the end of the 
day, it's a professional beach volleyball endeavor. It's not like 
it's a philanthropic event with Hillary Clinton at the finish 
line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kessel said athletes need to play in a minimum number of Alero  
tournaments as part of the Olympic qualification process. 
</P>
<P>
	But Johnson said he and other AVP members discussed that with  
international officials, ``and they kind of laughed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When push comes to shove, I don't know what will happen,''  
said Johnson, who added that he'll remain loyal to the AVP even if 
it means missing a shot at going to the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``The AVP is where most of us have made a great living for many  
years, and we feel we need to stick behind it to make it strong for 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kiraly wasn't available for comment Friday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
