<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Hails Mideast Peace Deal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today that lasting  
peace in the Middle East ``is now a step closer'' after the 
conclusion of an Israeli-Palestinian deal for a further Israeli 
pullback from the West Bank. ``This is truly a new beginning,'' the 
president said in a written statement. His remarks came as 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright helped orchestrate the 
long-sought accord between Israel and the Palestinians. The 
agreement will be signed tomorrow. Clinton congratulated Israeli 
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat 
``for their vision in seizing this opportunity.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Federal Judge Demands Waco Evidence  
</P>
<P>
	WACO, Texas (AP) -- A federal judge ordered the Justice  
Department to turn over all evidence from the FBI raid on the 
Branch Davidian compound at Waco, saying it is needed in a wrongful 
death suit filed here. Judge Walter Smith threatened to cite the 
Justice Department with contempt if it does not comply with his 
order of yesterday, which comes after a belated FBI admission that 
incendiary tear gas canisters were used in the waning hours of the 
Texas siege. Smith rebuffed the Justice Department's complaint that 
gathering, copying and transferring the evidence would be ``an 
unwarranted and substantial burden.'' 

</P>
<P>
	West's Biggest Blaze Rages in Calif  
</P>
<P>
	BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. (AP) -- More than 2,700 firefighters aided  
by planes, helicopters and bulldozers were battling the 61,770-acre 
Willow fire in the San Bernardino Mountains today. The blaze, which 
started Aug. 28, was one of seven large fires in California. Most 
other fires in the West were contained. Big Bear Lake and the other 
popular resorts 90 miles east of Los Angeles were depending on the 
firefighters to keep flames away through the lucrative Labor Day 
Weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	Energy Dept. Admits Laser Flaws  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department admitted to serious  
problems today in a program to build the world's largest laser, 
including mismanagement that will add hundreds of millions of 
dollars to its original $1.2 billion price tag. Energy Secretary 
Bill Richardson, who said he was assured the project was on target 
as recently as June, ordered an overhaul of the program at the 
Lawrence Livermore weapons laboratory and an investigation into why 
the cost overruns were not revealed earlier. The massive laser, 
which was supposed to have been completed by 2003, is being built 
at the California research lab in a project to monitor and maintain 
America's nuclear warheads without testing nuclear bombs. 

</P>
<P>
	Princess Di Crash Charges Dismissed  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A French judge today closed the painful two-year  
inquiry into the car crash that killed Princess Diana, dismissing 
all charges against nine photographers and a press motorcyclist 
implicated in the accident. The judge's terse conclusion came in a 
one-page statement: Alcohol, drugs and excessive speed caused the 
crash that ended the life of the ``people's princess.'' Diana, her 
boyfriend Dodi Fayed and their driver, Henri Paul, died in the Aug. 
31, 1997, crash in a Paris traffic tunnel. 

</P>
<P>
	CBS-TV To Team Clayson and Gumbel  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After a summer-long search, CBS will announce  
Tuesday that it has hired ABC News correspondent Jane Clayson to be 
Bryant Gumbel's on-air partner on the ``Early Show,'' two sources 
close to the talks said today. The revamped morning news show 
begins broadcasting in November. Ms. Clayson, based in Los Angeles, 
is a reporter for ``World News Tonight'' and has worked at ABC 
since 1996. She was a reporter and anchor at a local station in 
Salt Lake City before then. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 235.24  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks raced higher today after the government's  
employment report calmed fears about rising inflation and prompted 
a broad rally that included the biggest point gain in the history 
of the Nasdaq composite index. At the close of trading on Wall 
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 235.24 at 
11,078.45. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led 
decliners 2,290-677. The Nasdaq rose 108.34 to 2,842.58, according 
to preliminary calculations, surpassing the previous high for a 
one-day point gain, 103.16, set on June 16. 

</P>
<P>
	Rusedski Advances at U.S. Open  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Britain's Greg Rusedski, who reached the U.S.  
Open final two years ago, moved into the third round today by 
pounding out a 6-4, 6-3, 6-1 victory over Germany's David Prinosil. 
In women's singles, Germany's Anke Huber upset eighth-seeded Jana 
Novotna 6-3, 6-2; Mary Joe Fernandez of Miami ousted No. 13 
Dominique Van Roost of Belgium 7-5, 6-0; and No. 10 Arantxa 
Sanchez-Vicario defeated Switzerland's Patty Schnyder 6-2, 6-2. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
