<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co-Founder of Teledyne Dies at 82 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Henry E. Singleton, co-founder of Teledyne  
Inc. and an innovative engineer who designed an aircraft guidance 
system used worldwide, has died. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	He died Tuesday of brain cancer at his home.  
</P>
<P>
	Singleton led one of the nation's largest conglomerates for  
three decades. He was known for his prowess on Wall Street and was 
a merger guru from the 1960s to the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	He launched Teledyne in 1960 as a semiconductor maker with his  
partner George Kozmetsky. Their first venture was building digital 
computers for aircraft and space exploration projects. Singleton 
developed the inertial guidance system now used in commercial and 
military aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	The soft-spoken Singleton helped turn the company into a  
business empire. The company's annual revenues peaked at nearly $5 
billion in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the mid-1980s, conglomerates were not in favor with Wall  
Street. Teledyne began divesting itself. It also became involved in 
military procurement scandals in the '80s and early '90s, paying 
more than $100 million in fines to settle claims that it inflated 
bills to the Pentagon and falsified tests on electronic components. 
</P>
<P>
	Singleton himself was not charged with anything, but some  
analysts said at the time that the legal troubles of Teledyne 
subsidiaries were a sign that its central management wasn't keeping 
tight enough control. 
</P>
<P>
	He had retired as Teledyne's chief executive officer in 1986,  
but remained as chairman until 1991. He was director of Teledyne 
until it combined forces with Allegheny Ludlum Corp. in 1996. 
Singleton then became a director for the new company, Allegheny 
Teledyne, until his retirement from the board in May 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes magazine listed Singleton as one of the nation's 400  
richest people last year with an estimated fortune of $750 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Henry was truly a business icon,'' said Richard Simmons,  
Allegheny Teledyne Inc.'s chairman. ``His accomplishments are 
legendary, including to his commitment to creating shareholder 
value. More importantly, he was a man of integrity and fairness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Singleton was born in Texas on a ranch. He attended the Naval  
Academy in Annapolis, Md. but transferred to the Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology where he earned his bachelor's, master's 
and doctoral degrees in electrical engineering. 
</P>
<P>
	After his retirement, Singleton returned to his roots, raising  
cattle and enjoying some of his passions, including chess, poetry 
and studying Western folklore. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Caroline, five children and four  
grandchildren. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
