<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motor Oil Marketer Settles Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A major marketer of motor oil additives has  
agreed to settle charges by federal regulators that it made 
unsubstantiated claims about its product. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposed settlement announced Thursday by the Federal  
Trade Commission, Prolong Super Lubricants, Inc., would require 
scientific substantiation for a broad range of claims made about 
its automobile motor oil additive, Prolong Engine Treatment 
Concentrate. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC had alleged that Prolong made unsupported claims that  
compared to motor oil alone, the additive reduces engine wear at 
start-up and extends the duration of engine life. The FTC complaint 
also charged Prolong with making unsubstantiated claims that the 
engine treatment reduces corrosion in engines and protects against 
engine breakdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement requires Prolong to back up claims about the  
additive's ability. The order also bars the company from 
misrepresenting tests, studies or research. Testimonials or 
endorsements would also require substantiation or disclosure of 
what results an ordinary consumer could expect. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it constantly conducts scientific tests on its  
products and will continue to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will go about the process of testing with an increased  
knowledge of the guidelines that are consistent with the 
expectations of the commission,'' said Robert Abdellah, vice 
president of corporate communications for Prolong, based in Irvine, 
Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission voted 4-0 to accept the proposed settlement, with  
Commissioner Orson Swindle dissenting in part. The consent 
agreement is subject to a 60-day public comment period, after which 
the commission will decide whether to make it final. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
