<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Letter Says Hatch Lobbied for Kim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Sen. Orrin Hatch promised to ``do  
everything required'' to get the now-indicted son of an 
International Olympic Committee member a permanent resident visa, 
according to a letter revealed Friday by defense attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have the assurances of Senator Hatch that he will do  
everything required to make the Green Card an appropriate success 
or he will acquire the same results by introducing a special 
bill,'' former Salt Lake bid president Tom Welch wrote in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Welch faxed the letter to John Kim, who was indicted Wednesday  
for fraudulently obtaining the residency card and lying to the FBI 
about it. Federal officials say they will try to extradite Kim, who 
left for South Korea before his indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Immigration and Naturalization Service says it would not be  
unusual for Hatch to lobby the agency on Kim's behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are tens of thousands of cases a year of congressmen  
helping people get green cards. Typically, a staffer will fire off 
a letter to INS. We have case workers here at INS who do nothing 
but handle'' congressional inquiries, INS spokesman Russ Bergeron 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether or not that occurred (in Kim's case), we wouldn't be  
able to say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch spokesman Heather Barney said staffers are scouring the  
senator's archives trying to determine what help Hatch offered or 
provided Kim. But Barney says it wouldn't have been anything 
unusual, and that Hatch gets thousands of requests a year for 
immigration help. Typically, his office forwards an application to 
the INS. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim's indictment was the second criminal case arising from Salt  
Lake's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 3, Salt Lake City businessman David E. Simmons pleaded  
guilty to a federal misdemeanor tax charge. Simmons said he created 
a phony job in New York City for Kim and was reimbursed by Kim and 
the Salt Lake Bid Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say the arrangement was designed to get Kim a green  
card and influence his father, IOC executive board member Un-yong 
Kim, to vote in favor of Salt Lake's bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons was charged with illegally deducting Kim's salary from  
his taxes as a business expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim is out of the reach of U.S. law -- for now.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll try to extradite him,'' Justice Department spokesman  
John Russell said Friday. ``We won't be satisfied until he's 
brought to justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Associates for Kim family attorney Howard Graff allowed The  
Associated Press on Friday to inspect Welch's letter in New York 
City, without making a copy. The contents of the letter were not 
disputed by Welch's attorney, Tom Schaffer, who said it ``speaks 
for itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schaffer defended Welch, who is considered a target of the  
continuing Olympic investigation, in the Kim affair. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the deal was set up, it was a legitimate deal. Kim was  
going to provide some consulting, and Tom thought it was going to 
work -- that it would be mutually beneficial,'' Schaffer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Simmons said it didn't work, but Kim says it did. Who's  
telling the truth? Tom says he put the parties together and they 
cut their own deal.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
