<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 15:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Devil Rays' McGriff Signs Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Fred McGriff didn't want to move  
again, and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays were more than willing to allow 
him to stay put. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old slugger, the subject of trade rumors in June,  
signed a two-year contract extension Friday that is worth about $6 
million per season. 
</P>
<P>
	McGriff, a Tampa native, also got a no-trade clause that will  
enable him to live year-round at home and enjoy his children 
growing up. The Devil Rays hold an option for a third season that 
would become guaranteed if he has 550 plate appearances in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's extremely important, because Fred is one of the  
cornerstones of this organization,'' general manager Chuck LaMar 
said, promising that keeping McGriff in the lineup is just one of 
several moves the team will make in an effort to be more 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not only has he had a great 1999, in the next couple of years  
he's truly going to separate himself as one of the great power 
hitters that ever played this game,'' Lamar said. ``Sometimes, 
because he's not as vocal as other players and maybe doesn't grab 
the limelight, his numbers go unnoticed. But they speak for 
themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGriff, who would have been eligible for free agency after the  
World Series, us in the final season of a $20 million, four-year 
contract he signed with the Atlanta Braves. The Devil Rays acquired 
him in November 1997 for $20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	A career .287 hitter with 387 homers in 13 seasons, McGriff  
struggled in 1998, batting .284 with 19 homers and 81 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	He's rebounded this year, hitting .314 with 29 homers and 90  
RBIs going into Friday night's game against the Minnesota Twins. 
</P>
<P>
	When trade rumors swirled in June, McGriff made it clear that he  
preferred to remain in Tampa Bay to try to help the two-year-old 
franchise build a winner. 
</P>
<P>
	With McGriff's return assured, LaMar now will turn his attention  
to the future of three other veterans. Catcher John Flaherty can 
become a free agent after this season, while the Devil Rays hold 
options on the contracts of Jose Canseco and Wade Boggs, who will 
miss the rest of this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a serious challenge ahead of us,'' McGriff said.  
``We're coming along and I believe we have a chance to have 
something really good here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
