<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Meares Back After Rehab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Shortstop Pat Meares returned to the  
Pittsburgh Pirates on Friday after his injury rehab stint in the 
minor leagues was cut short because of problems with his left hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Meares went on the disabled list May 12 with pain in the hand, a  
problem that began late in spring training. He had surgery to 
repair tendons two days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Meares went to Triple-A Nashville on a rehab assignment Aug. 26  
but was only able to play five games before his hand began 
bothering him. 
</P>
<P>
	``His hand is all right; it's just that he still doesn't have  
enough strength to play in the games,'' Pirates trainer Kent 
Biggerstaff said. ``By the time he does his extra work and strength 
work, it kind of fatigues it. When he gets into the game, he just 
doesn't have the strength to have the at-bats you want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates have said that getting Meares completely healthy is  
more important than having him come back and play some games this 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, that work is more important than five swings a  
game,'' Biggerstaff said. ``The options are to not let him do any 
extra work and get five swings in the game or to let him get all of 
his extra work and build his strength back up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Gene Lamont said he wasn't sure if Meares would be able  
to play for the Pirates again this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Meares appeared in 17 games for the Pirates this year, hitting  
.297 with no home runs and five RBIs. He signed with Pittsburgh as 
a free agent in March for $1.5 million, then was given a $15 
million, four-year extension in April. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
