<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Will Name Investigator for Waco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno today said she  
will soon name an independent investigator outside the Justice 
Department to answer lingering questions surrounding the FBI's 1993 
assault against a Branch Davidian sect near Waco, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said she hoped to identify the lead investigator as soon as  
possible, but didn't say when that would be. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has taken some time because I want to do it the right  
way,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno also told reporters at her regular media briefing that she  
was proceeding carefully because she wants to assure that the 
investigation ``has the confidence and faith of the American 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She added that the person selected for the job should ``have no  
conflicts of interest and be well-received'' by the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno dodged questions about whether the furor surrounding the  
recent revelations had caused a strain between her and FBI Director 
Louis Freeh. 
</P>
<P>
	The attorney general said the two often confer on difficult  
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, sometimes I call him and say, `Why did you do this?' or  
he will call and say, `Why did you do that?' That's the type of 
relationship we have,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said that as authorities try to get to the bottom of what  
happened on that fateful day -- April 19, 1993 -- ``it's very 
important that people don't play one off against the other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reno declined to go into detail about the scope of the  
investigation, saying, ``I think we've got to let the independent 
investigator determine what he or she needs to pursue. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I hope will happen is that we will be able to agree on a  
mandate that gives them full authority to pursue any unanswered 
question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The attorney general spoke publicly a day after the FBI released  
a videotape on which an FBI commander is heard authorizing the use 
of incendiary tear gas hours before a deadly fire ended the 
Davidians' 51-day standoff with federal agents. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI had long denied that incendiary gas was used.  
</P>
<P>
	Two former Republican senators -- John C. Danforth of Missouri  
and Warren Rudman of New Hampshire -- and former Iran-Contra 
prosecutor Dan Webb are among those said to be on the list of 
candidates to conduct Reno's investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House, Freeh and members of Congress have suggested an  
independent review of the case. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
