<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lab Heads Admit Doctoring Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Supervisors at a central New Jersey testing  
lab admitted Friday that they doctored data for a Japanese fuel 
blender so millions of gallons of gasoline designed to reduce air 
pollution would appear to meet federal standards. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, substandard reformulated gasoline was sold for 2 1/2  
years to motorists in Connecticut, New Jersey and New York, 
according to the three men, who each pleaded guilty in U.S. 
District Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The three men, supervisors at Caleb Brett's lab in Linden, said  
they falsified the data on behalf of Itochu Corp., The Japanese 
company shipped gasoline to Linden for distribution to retailers, 
but could not unload unless it met specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was understood that if we didn't do it, Itochu would take  
their business elsewhere,'' said former supervisor Ronald J. 
Domnik, who pleaded guilty to conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency had no assessment yet  
of how much extra pollution the gasoline caused, spokesman Rich 
Cahill said. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for Itochu, Lanny Breuer, refused to discuss Itochu's  
alleged role, but said officials will cooperate with the Justice 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Domnik and Julius Balogh, who also pleaded guilty to conspiracy,  
each face five years in prison and $250,000 in fines. Nicholas 
Lehman pleaded guilty to not telling authorities about the 
conspiracy and faces three years in prison and a $250,000 fine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
