<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Track Evens CART Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Dario Franchitti has  
temporary road courses down pat. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, who won last year's Vancouver Molson Indy from the  
pole and has won the last two CART FedEx Series events on temporary 
circuits, took the provisional pole here Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Team Kool Green teammate Paul Tracy, who finished second to  
Franchitti earlier this year on the temporary circuits in Toronto 
and Detroit, had the second fastest speed on Friday. But his lap 
was disqualified after his Reynard-Honda failed a technical 
inspection because it was lower than the allowable 2-inch 
clearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, a 26-year-old Scotsman, turned a fast lap of 104.520  
mph on the reconfigured 1.781-mile, 12-turn course at the edge of 
downtown Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy was closest at 104.102 before his speed was disallowed.  
Fortunately for the Canadian driver, he is eligible to try again 
Saturday in the final round of time trials for Sunday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, who trails series leader Juan Montoya by four points  
in the standings, got the job done Friday in only eight laps. He 
turned his fast time on his final trip around the circuit, which 
now features an uninterrupted back straightaway and wider, more 
open turns at the tightest part of the course. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the new track configuration is already considerably  
faster than last year's 1.802-mile version on which Franchitti won 
after qualifying at a then-record 101.147. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, I was just trying to get used to the track and the  
changes they made,'' said Franchitti, who was conserving tires for 
the race. ``We're definitely looking for improvements tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for those track changes, he said, ``The wall being farther  
away, from a safety standpoint, is very good. It's faster and I 
think it's better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tracy shrugged when asked why he and Franchitti are so good on  
the temporary circuits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really know why we're particularly strong on the  
street courses. They're not places we can test and we really 
haven't tested that much on road courses, either,'' Tracy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I think last year we just got a good baseline and, right  
now, Dario and I are real close to each other on car set-up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti said, ``Yeah, I think it gets down to teamwork again.  
Our engineers have come up with a good set-up and we're taking 
advantage of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Moreno, continuing to sub for injured Christian  
Fittipaldi, moved up to the second qualifying spot at 103.997, 
followed by local favorite Greg Moore, from suburban Maple Ridge, 
at 103.889, Gil de Ferran at 103.867 and rookie Montoya at 103.801. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still working on it, but I'm confident,'' said Montoya,  
who comes into this week with a series-high six victories overall 
and two in a row. ``I really like the track. It was a bit tough the 
first couple of times around, but it's getting better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three-time Vancouver winner Michael Andretti, who is a distant  
third in the season points -- just ahead of Tracy -- was a 
disappointing 11th at 103.079. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's track layout -- which was completely new because of  
continuing construction at Concord Pacific Place, where the race is 
held -- was criticized by nearly every driver for being too bumpy, 
too slow, too narrow in critical places and lacking enough safe 
runoff areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was just no margin for error,'' said Scott Pruett, head  
of the CART drivers' safety committee. ``If you put one wrong 
wheel, you were finished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's problem have all been addressed in the latest  
version of the course, which got passing marks from the drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's improvement at both ends,'' Tracy said. ``I think  
they've done everything they can do with the land available to 
them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
