<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Rise on Economic News / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Good news on the inflation front sent bond  
prices surging Friday, breaking a six-session losing streak and 
nearly pushing the yield on the long bond back below 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 17/32  
point, or $15.31 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 6.01 percent from 6.13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally was touched off by a report showing a  
smaller-than-expected increase in hourly wages in August, which 
helped quell fears that a tight labor market would force wages 
higher and lead the Fed to raise interest rates when it meets on 
Oct. 5. Higher rates tend to hurt the value of bonds, which pay a 
fixed rate of return. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasury securities were up between 3/16  
point and 9/32 point, and intermediate maturities were up 15/32 
point to 7/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.90 percent as the  
discount was unchanged at 4.77 percent. Six-month yields were 5.13 
percent, as the discount fell 0.03 percentage point to 4.93 
percent. One-year yields were 5.19 percent as the discount fell by 
0.07 percentage point from late Thursday to 4.93 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5.13 percent from 5.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 19/32 to 114 7/32. The average yield to 
maturity fell to 5.79 percent from 5.82 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
