<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 12:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Charged in MIT Laughing Gas Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- A student and a recent graduate were  
charged today in connection with the death of a Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology student who inhaled laughing gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Susan Mosher, a Massachusetts Institute of Technology senior,  
and 1999 graduate Rene Ruiz face charges stemming from the 
distribution of illegal drugs from the dorm room where Richard A. 
Guy was found dead Tuesday, MIT Police Chief Anne Glavin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The medical examiner said the 22-year-old junior physics major  
from Mission Viejo, Calif., was asphyxiated as a result of nitrous 
oxide inhalation. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint lists charges that include possession of nitrous  
oxide, hallucinogenic mushrooms, amphetamines and marijuana, all 
with intent to distribute. The pair also face charges of 
conspiracy, possession of a hypodermic needle and cruelty to 
animals, cats. Police did not further explain the cruelty charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The two are scheduled to appear in Cambridge District Court a  
week from today. 
</P>
<P>
	Mosher, a major in brain and cognitive science, lived in the  
same East Campus dormitory as Guy. 
</P>
<P>
	MIT officials believe he was alone at the time of his death, but  
authorities were investigating whether he had been inhaling from a 
``community canister'' of gas shared by other students. 
</P>
<P>
	Guy had taken some time off from the prestigious university and  
was seeking readmission to the degree program as a junior this 
fall, MIT spokesman Ken Campbell said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the second MIT student to die from on-campus substance  
abuse in two years. In September 1997, 18-year-old freshman Scott 
Krueger died three days after he was found in an alcohol-induced 
coma on a fraternity floor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
