<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dennis Still Threatens N.C. Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALVO, N.C. (AP) -- Tropical Storm Dennis, which spoiled last  
weekend for vacationers on the North Carolina coast, threatened to 
wash out the last big beach weekend of summer, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters said they expect the onetime hurricane to finally  
wade ashore on the state's curving southeastern coast on Sunday 
night, in the middle of the Labor Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vacationers and residents alike were sick and tired of the  
11-day-old storm, whether it disrupted their summer break or 
wrecked their hopes for a money-making tourist-filled weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just want to go home,'' said Pete Wilcox, as he sat at a  
roadblock in Nags Head on Friday, trying to reach his home in 
Rodanthe, on Hatteras Island. ``I've been out of work a week and 
don't need that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A mandatory evacuation order was lifted on Friday for beachfront  
neighborhoods in Nags Head, Kitty Hawk and Kill Devil Hills. 
Farther south, on Hatteras Island, where the raging surf chewed up 
the main north-south highway and choked it with chest-high beach 
sand, only four-wheel-drive traffic was permitted. 
</P>
<P>
	But by then, many of the hundreds of thousands of vacationers  
who each summer pack the Outer Banks, a 130-mile stretch of barrier 
islands, were long gone. About 130,000 people live on the coast, 
but during the summer that grows fivefold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally we would be full for all three days,'' said Nancy  
Newins, manager of Lucille's Motel in Carolina Beach, surveying 
bookings for fewer than half her rooms Friday. ``We're hoping the 
storm goes away and everybody sees it on the news and hurries 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, then-Hurricane Dennis sideswiped the coast without  
ever coming ashore, though it dumped up to 8 inches of rain and 
dished out 20-foot waves and 100 mph winds. Then it headed out to 
sea. But soon it began backtracking. 
</P>
<P>
	By Friday night, the storm was about 175 miles south-southeast  
of Cape Hatteras and drifting with sustained winds around 60 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis could strengthen before coming ashore after midnight  
Sunday, Jack Beven, a hurricane specialist at the National 
Hurricane Center in Miami. But he warned that Dennis has confounded 
predictions before. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it has done since it got east of Hatteras is on the  
strange side,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, state Public Safety Secretary Richard Moore warned  
beachgoers: ``We have the prospect of having a lot of rain and wind 
in the state this weekend, or we may not have any at all. We just 
don't know.'' 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
