<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Concerns that Japan's central bank might step in to  
boost the dollar sent the currency higher against the yen today. 
Tokyo's key stock index closed slightly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 109.74 yen in late trading, up 0.32 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
109.11 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 1.26 points,  
or 0.01 percent, to close the day's trading at 17,629.99 points. On 
Thursday, the average closed down 171.23 points, or 0.96 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, market players were concerned the Bank of  
Japan may intervene in markets next Thursday following the release 
of Japanese gross domestic product data for the April-June quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ stepped in on June 10 to stop the yen's rise after  
better-than-expected GDP figures for the January-March quarter 
unleashed frenzied yen-buying. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a possibility of so-called 'event intervention,'''  
said Shuji Takano from ABN AMRO Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials have repeatedly said a premature  
strengthening of the yen is undesirable amid sporadic signs that 
Japan is recovering from its worst recession in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen is seen as negative for Japan's economy because it  
makes the nation's exports more expensive, and therefore less 
competitive, overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Comments from Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's former vice finance  
minister for international affairs, also spurred the dollar's 
gains, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a U.S. television interview broadcast today on CNBC,  
Sakakibara, now an advisor to the Finance Ministry, said currency 
``intervention is always a strategic decision,'' which depends on 
market conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts added that investors were waiting for the release of  
U.S. employment figures for August, due out in Washington later 
today, for a further signal about the direction of the high-flying 
U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded between 109.14 yen and 110.24 yen during  
Tokyo's trading today. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 117.65 yen, up from  
115.86 late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei slipped in listless trading,  
with investors wary of taking new positions ahead of next week's 
release of several important economic indicators. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were anxious to see what direction the U.S. stock market  
would take after Labor Day, in addition to waiting for the 
announcement of Japan's gross domestic product data, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next Monday is a holiday in the U.S., so I don't expect any  
significant movement that day, but often when investors come back 
from the end of their summer holiday, the mood of the market 
changes sharply,'' said Garry Evans, a strategist at HSBC 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow closed 94.67 points lower at 10,843.23  
on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 659 to 513, while 163 issues  
were unchanged. An estimated 464.63 million shares changed hands on 
the first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 603.03 
million shares the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up a marginal 0.01 points, insignificant in 
percentage terms, to 1,497.00. The TOPIX closed up 0.75 points, or 
0.05 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.8350 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8850 percent, driving 
its price up to 100.54 yen from 100.12 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
