<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	East Timor Braces for Violence  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- East Timor voted overwhelmingly for  
independence from Indonesia, U.N. officials announced Saturday, and 
its people braced for a possible violent backlash from pro-Jakarta 
militias. The East Timorese capital was shut and quiet after the 
announcement of the results from Monday's historic vote, with 
scared residents hunkering down inside their homes. In the Mahkota 
Hotel, where many East Timorese were packed into the lobby, tears 
of joy and relief broke out when U.N. elections team chief Ian 
Martin read out the results in Portuguese and Indonesian. 

</P>
<P>
	Mideast Peace Pact To Be Signed  
</P>
<P>
	GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- With a nudge from Secretary of  
State Madeleine Albright, Israel and the Palestinians concluded a 
long-sought agreement today for a further Israeli pullback from the 
West Bank. The deal clears the way for a possible overall peace 
accord within a year. The agreement, which will be signed tomorrow 
in the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh, plants the first 
seeds of a permanent peace by setting a Feb. 15 deadline to put 
together a framework for a final settlement. 

</P>
<P>
	Key Nations Seek New Policy on Iraq  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States has invited the other  
permanent members of the Security Council to meet next week to try 
to narrow differences on a new policy toward Iraq. But China said 
today it had to confer with its leadership in Beijing. More than 
eight months after U.N. weapons inspectors pulled out of Iraq, the 
five permanent council members -- the United States, Britain, 
France, Russia and China -- remain split in two camps on future arms 
monitoring and on whether to suspend sanctions imposed after Iraq's 
1990 invasion of Kuwait. 

</P>
<P>
	Ecuador Teen-Ager Burned Alive  
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) - A 15-year-old boy, accused of robbing  
houses and beating his mother, was burned alive by a mob in the 
public square of a remote village after a six-hour vigilante trial, 
authorities said Friday. The mob execution occurred Wednesday night 
in the village of La Chimba, a half-hour drive from the city of 
Cayambe, 31 miles northeast of the capital, Quito. Police said the 
boy, William Iguamba, was grabbed in Cayambe's central plaza by a 
crowd of about 50 people and brought to La Chimba, where he was 
chained to a post in the central square. There, about 600 Indians 
from four surrounding communities spent six hours deciding the 
boy's guilt, and ultimately burned him alive, police said. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO: Time Not Right for Withdrawal  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO Secretary General Javier Solana  
said today the time was not right for reducing the 29,000-strong 
international peacekeeping force in Bosnia, despite progress made 
toward stabilizing society and establishing peace. Solana said NATO 
defense ministers would likely discuss the future of the Bosnia 
force when they meet Sept. 21-22 in Toronto. ``We do not expect any 
serious drawdown because we do not think the situation is right,'' 
he told reporters after a meeting with Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. 
ambassador to the United Nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 235.24  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks raced higher today after the government's  
employment report calmed fears about rising inflation and prompted 
a broad rally that included the biggest point gain in the history 
of the Nasdaq composite index. At the close of trading on Wall 
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 235.24 at 
11,078.45. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led 
decliners 2,290-677. The Nasdaq rose 108.34 to 2,842.58, according 
to preliminary calculations, surpassing the previous high for a 
one-day point gain, 103.16, set on June 16. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros Defeat Expos 8-1  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Ken Caminiti homered twice and drove in six runs  
and Mike Hampton pitched seven strong innings for his 18th victory 
tonight to lead the Houston Astros to a 8-1 win over the Montreal 
Expos. Caminiti hit his seventh homer off Dan Smith (4-7) leading 
off the second and hit a two-run shot in the ninth. He added a 
sacrifice fly in the third and a two-run single in the seventh. It 
was Caminiti's 18th career multihomer game and second this season. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
