<HEADLINE> Stocks Surge Higher; Dow Up 212.76 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks surged higher today after the  
government's employment report showed the U.S. economy added jobs 
at a slower-than-expected pace and that wage growth moderated in 
August, helping to ease fears about rising inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	In late afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones  
industrial average was up 212.76 at 11,055.97. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also sharply higher. The Standard  
&AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 34.91 at 1,354.02, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was up 90.46 at 2,824.70. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose after the Labor Department reported that employers  
added 124,000 jobs to their payrolls in August and that average 
hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures, rose just 0.2 
percent in August, a 3.5 percent increase compared with a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Both figures helped ease concerns that the economy is  
overheating and that inflation is rising, and they provided good 
news for investors who believe that any inflationary signs could 
prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates for a third time 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed has raised interest rates twice this summer and hinted  
it won't raise them again if the economy is moderating and 
inflation remains tame. Higher interest rates cut into corporate 
profits by raising the cost of borrowing. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices also rose on the employment report, pushing yields  
on 30-year Treasuries down to 6.01 percent from 6.13 percent late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has slipped recently as interest rate fears have  
been preying on investors,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior vice 
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. ``But the payroll data eased those 
rate fears and buyers stepped up to the plate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, the most sensitive to interest rate changes,  
surged today. J.P. Morgan was up 7 1/16 at 133 and American Express 
was up 6 3/16 at 142 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks also rallied. America Online rose 4 5/8 to 95 7/8,  
Intel rose 3 1/2 to 88 13/16 and Yahoo! rose 10 3/16 to 151 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple rose 3 3/16 to 73 3/4 as the company continued to benefit  
from the unveiling of a new desktop computer. 
</P>
<P>
	National Discount Brokers fell 5 1/2 to 25 3/4 after the company said  
earnings in its fiscal first quarter will be well below Wall Street 
estimates. The online brokerage cited higher-than-expected costs 
for advertising and write-offs for old technology. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest loser in the Dow was Coca-Cola, which fell 2 5/8 to 56 7/8  
after it warned third-quarter earnings will fall short of Wall 
Street forecasts because of weak beverage sales in Asia and South 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 548.94 million 
shares, up from 546.93 million shares on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The good economic news prompted many investors to stay in the  
market on what was expected to be a quiet session ahead of the 
three-day holiday weekend. U.S. financial markets will be closed 
Monday in observance of Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.12 to 433.54.  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
