<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno: Court Can OK Starr Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno said Friday that a  
special court has authority to appoint a successor to Independent 
Counsel Kenneth Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr was appointed to investigate President Clinton, the first  
lady and their business associates under a law that expired June 
30. Reno said she believes the three-judge appeals court panel that 
selected independent counsels can nonetheless choose a prosecutor 
to continue his work. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr plans to leave before his office's work is finished,  
according to legal sources familiar with his plans. 
</P>
<P>
	A Justice Department official said that ``based on the reading  
of the statute it is believed that the rules that would apply for 
an (independent counsel) departing before the act expires are the 
same that would apply now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, Reno declined to comment on whether the court  
could choose a successor, saying ``I think it better for the 
Department of Justice to address the issues as they arise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, however, the issue has been examined ``all the way  
to the top'' of the department, said the official, speaking on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's successor could decide to revisit important questions --  
such as whether criminal charges are warranted against either of 
the Clintons. A successor also could decide to act as a mere 
caretaker in charge of closing down the office. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's successor also could stir up political trouble for the  
first lady, who is considering a run for the U.S. Senate from New 
York. One focus of Starr's investigation has been Mrs. Clinton's 
legal work on a 1,000-acre real estate project south of Little 
Rock, Ark., which federal regulators concluded was riddled with 
insider transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Other people remain under investigation by Starr's office.  
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have been looking into whether a Maryland developer  
tried to obstruct the testimony of presidential accuser Kathleen 
Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr also has been looking into whether presidential aides lied  
about a role by Hillary Rodham Clinton in firings at the White 
House travel office. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
