<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Wary on Impact of Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful  
Steve Forbes cautioned Friday that gambling ``does not create a 
backbone for a powerful economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina residents will vote this fall on whether they  
want to keep the video gambling industry in the state. Next year 
they will decide on a state lottery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I oppose video gambling and I think that gets to the whole  
issue of gambling, which has become a national issue,'' Forbes said 
while campaigning in South Carolina, which holds the South's first 
primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``While people think the lottery is much less harmful than video  
gambling -- and they are right on that -- the thing to remember about 
gambling is it does not create a backbone for a powerful economy,'' 
Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some video gambling supporters want to use taxes and fees from  
the industry to cut car taxes. The plan for lottery revenues is to 
help fund education. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there is no guarantee any state will carry through on  
its promises, Forbes said. ``At the end of the day, what do you 
have? You have the government taking more,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential hopeful declined to wade into  
another state controversy -- whether the Confederate flag should be 
taken down from the South Carolina Statehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People  
has proposed an economic boycott of the state until the Confederate 
flag, which was raised above the Statehouse dome in 1962, is taken 
down. So far, the Legislature has refused. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a state issue to be determined by the people of South  
Carolina,'' Forbes said before attending a luncheon attended by 
about 150 people. Other candidates have also kept their distance 
from the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Flag supporters say it commemorates their Southern heritage and  
those who fought on the side of the South in the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I shouldn't say this, but New Jersey was on the other  
side,'' said Forbes, who lives in that state. As for the boycott, 
he said, ``It's a free country and people can call for whatever 
they wish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charleston businessman Claudius Watts, a former president of The  
Citadel military college, said he did not generally attend such 
political events, but attended a Forbes luncheon to see what the 
candidate had to say. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Mr. Forbes has proven himself in the world of business  
and he certainly has a forward-looking perspective,'' Watts said. 
``Who knows what's going to happen as far as the nomination is 
concerned? It's early.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
