<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Predicts Defeat for Mrs. Gandhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Opinion polls published today predict  
Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv 
Gandhi, will lose her first bid for public office when elections 
start Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	If Mrs. Gandhi loses from the Bellary parliamentary constituency  
in the southern state of Karnataka, it would be the election's 
biggest upset, as her Congress party has won every election in the 
district since India's independence five decades ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi is the president of the Congress party and its most  
likely choice for prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	To help ensure her election, Mrs. Gandhi is also running from a  
second district, Amethi, in Uttar Pradesh state. Her husband, who 
was assassinated, had run from Amethi. That race had been seen as 
less secure than Bellary because the Congress party candidate 
selected by Mrs. Gandhi to run last year lost. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls published today in the Times of India and The Pioneer  
newspapers indicated that Mrs. Gandhi would lose in Bellary to 
Sushma Swaraj of the ruling Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Times of India poll, Mrs. Swaraj was projected to win 61  
percent of the Bellary vote and Mrs. Gandhi 37 percent. It said 11 
percent of the voters were undecided. The poll was conducted from a 
sample of 642 voters in several districts of Bellary from Aug. 
27-29. The margin of error was 4 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pioneer poll showed Mrs. Swaraj winning by a slimmer margin,  
45 percent to Mrs. Gandhi's 40 percent, with 15 percent undecided. 
No margin of error was given for that poll, conducted Aug. 30-Sept. 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	That survey, however, showed Mrs. Gandhi handily winning the  
Amethi seat with 59 percent of the vote against 21 percent her 
rival, Sanjay Singh, of Vajpayee's party. The poll of 14,850 people 
in 81 voting constituencies across 16 states had a margin of error 
of 2.5 percentage points, said the Research and Development 
Initiative, which conducted the survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting was to be held in Amethi a few days after it began in  
Bellary on Sunday, the first day of balloting in the monthlong, 
staggered elections for a new parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Swaraj's tactic of aggressively highlighting Mrs. Gandhi's  
foreign birth appears to be paying off. According to the Times of 
India poll, Mrs. Swaraj would win because 75 percent of the 
respondents felt Mrs. Gandhi was a foreigner despite her becoming 
an Indian citizen 16 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty-nine percent of those polled felt Prime Minister Atal  
Bihari Vajpayee was better suited than Mrs. Gandhi for the top job. 
Of those who said they would vote for Mrs. Swaraj, 62 percent said 
they were inclined to do so because she speaks the local Kannada 
language. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
