<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Assets Ordered Frozen in Fraud Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A judge Friday ordered that the assets of  
businesses suspected of defrauding up to $125 million from 
investors remain frozen while investigators try to track down the 
missing money. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials estimate that up to 12,000 investors, mostly retirees  
and wealthy Latin American families, lost part or all of the 
investments made when they were sold unregistered mutual funds, 
federal investigators say. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Edward B. Davis in Miami originally froze  
the assets of Cyprus Funds and three related companies on Aug. 27. 
Davis had also appointed Fort Lauderdale attorney Michael I. 
Goldberg as receiver in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis took that action when the U.S. Securities and Exchange  
Commission filed its lawsuit alleging that the Cyprus Funds 
advisers operated a scheme in which some investors were paid 
interest from money gathered from later investors, a scam normally 
called a Ponzi scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's extremely troubling,'' Christian Bartholomew, lead  
attorney for the SEC, said Friday. ``It's a classic example of 
people taking advantage of the elderly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goldberg said he's already spoken with as many as 40 people who  
invested from $7,500 to $7 million each with Cyprus. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC officials are still looking for Cyrprus Funds chief Eric  
Bartoli. 
</P>
<P>
	Bartoli has homes in Ohio and Florida, and allegedly sold shares  
of the mutual funds from the office of Cyprus Funds in Doylestown, 
Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged scheme came to light in July when Cyprus Funds  
dividend checks were rejected or returned for insufficient funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis last month froze the assets of four Ohio residents:  
Bartoli, 45, of Marshallville, Ohio, and Miami, Fla.; James L. 
Binge, 52, of Massillon; Peter J. Esposito, 45, of Canfield; and 
Douglas R. Shisler, 52, of Doylestown. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyprus Funds have been sold in the United States since 1994. Of  
those in the SEC complaint, only Binge is licensed to sell 
securities in Ohio, said Dennis Ginty, spokesman for the Ohio 
Division of Securities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
