<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Freinds Honor Fritz Shurmur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Family, friends and football fans have  
spent the past few days saying goodbye to former Green Bay Packers 
defensive coordinator Fritz Shurmur, who died this week after 
building a reputation for clever defenses and a kind heart. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a uniqueness to him,'' general manager Ron Wolf said of  
Shurmur, who was on the Packers' coaching staff from 1994 to 1998. 
``For Fritz, it was the love of the game and the respect for the 
people, not only those who played with him, but those that he 
played against. The game misses people like him. You don't replace 
people like that, but you do go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur, 67, died Monday at his home in Suamico, three months  
after he was diagnosed with esophageal and liver cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Gary Dantinne called Shurmur ``a person of faith'' at  
today's funeral. ``Maybe he's formulating God's new defense against 
evil,'' Dantinne said. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Packers coach Mike Holmgren attended today's service, as  
well as Ray Rhodes, who took over coaching duties in Green Bay 
after Holmgren left for the Seattle Seahawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad to lose a friend, because Fritz was a friend to all  
of us,'' said former Packers defensive end Reggie White, who 
attended the service with his wife, Sarah. 
</P>
<P>
	LeRoy Butler, Santana Dotson and Gilbert Brown, all defensive  
players under Shurmur, helped carry his casket into the church 
</P>
<P>
	Shurmur built tough defenses that led the Packers to two  
consecutive Super Bowls. He left the Packers for the Seattle 
Seahawks with Holmgren. However, the Shurmurs had built a home in 
Suamico and intended to retire there. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was to be a year or two of challenge, followed by a  
lifetime of fishing,'' said Scott Shurmur, of his father's position 
with the Seahawks. 
</P>
<P>
	Lining the walls of the funeral home Wednesday were more than  
three dozen flower arrangements, from private well-wishers and 
former foes such as the San Francisco 49ers, Indianapolis Colts, 
Chicago Bears, Atlanta Falcons and New Orleans Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Seahawks, the team that pulled Shurmur from Green  
Bay, sent flowers, too. From a cross-shaped arrangement hung a card 
from Mike and Kathy Holmgren, the former Packers coach and now the 
Seahawks coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Packers President Bob Harlan, offensive coordinator Sherman  
Lewis, quarterback Brett Favre and his wife, Deanna, and tight end 
Mark Chmura also attended. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
