<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Israel, Palestinians Close to Deal  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians resolved a dispute  
over the release of Palestinian prisoners, moving closer to signing 
a revised West Bank land-for-security deal, two senior Israeli 
officials said today. However, there is still disagreement on one 
clause in the emerging accord dealing with a prohibition on either 
side to take unilateral actions in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, 
said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
Palestinian negotiators could not immediately be reached for 
comment. U.S. officials would only say it was possible to reach 
agreement. 

</P>
<P>
	Charges Dropped in Princess Diana Probe  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A French judge today cleared nine photographers and  
a press motorcylist implicated in the car crash that killed 
Princess Diana, ending the two-year investigation into the 
accident, judicial sources said. Judge Herve Stephan followed 
recommendations issued Aug. 16 by the state prosecutor to drop the 
charges of manslaughter and failing to assist persons in danger 
against the photographers and press motorcyclist, the sources said, 
speaking on customary anonymity. Diana; her boyfriend, Dodi Fayed; 
and driver, Henri Paul, died in the Aug. 31, 1997 crash in a Paris 
traffic tunnel. Only bodyguard Trevor Rees-Jones survived. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Seeks All Waco Evidence  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A federal judge has ordered government lawyers to  
submit all evidence from the Branch Davidian compound siege to his 
court by Oct. 1 or face contempt charges. The order issued 
yesterday by Judge Walter Smith of Waco comes in response to a U.S. 
Justice Department motion this week challenging his authority to 
take control of evidence. Smith next month is scheduled to begin 
hearing a wrongful death lawsuit filed against the government by 
Branch Davidians who survived the April 1993 federal raid on their 
compound. 

</P>
<P>
	Canada To Test-Burn U.S. Nuke Waste  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers will use a shipment of reactor  
fuel from New Mexico's Los Alamos lab to test whether Canada's 
nuclear reactors are suitable to dispose of weapons-grade 
plutonium. Canada has committed only to the tests, although the 
Canadian government has offered to burn as much as 100 tons of the 
plutonium fuel blend over a 25-year period. The test burns are 
expected to take several years. The Energy Department and Canadian 
officials announced an agreement Thursday on the shipment, which 
will be made later this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspect in Atlanta Killings Caught  
</P>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- A man arrested after being wounded in a  
shootout with police turned out to be the same man suspected in a 
triple shooting outside Atlanta that left two women dead, police 
said. Jason Pierce, 21, is accused in the Aug. 26 shooting of his 
former girlfriend and her two friends who were in the Atlanta area 
attending college. The two friends died. The ex-girlfriend, shot in 
the mouth, survived and identified Pierce as the shooter. Pierce 
had attended high school with the women in Boston. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll Predicts Defeat for Gandhi  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- An opinion poll published today predicts  
Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv 
Gandhi, will lose her first bid for public office when elections 
start Sunday. If Mrs. Gandhi loses from the Bellary parliamentary 
constituency in the southern state of Karnataka, it would be the 
election's biggest upset, as her Congress party has won every 
election in the district since India's independence five decades 
ago. Mrs. Gandhi is the president of the Congress party and its 
most likely choice for prime minister. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., China To Talk Trade  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In what could be the beginning of a thaw in  
chilly relations between the United States and China, the two 
countries have planned their first trade talks in four months. The 
technical-level discussions will be held next week, probably in 
Beijing, in advance of a meeting between President Clinton and 
Chinese President Jiang Zemin in New Zealand. Deputy U.S. Trade 
Representative Richard Fisher said yesterday the technical-level 
meeting will be a ``stock-taking'' of where the two countries stand 
on negotiations to bring China into the World Trade Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo's key stock index closed slightly lower  
today. The Nikkei shed fell 1.26 points to close at 17,629.99. 

</P>
<P>
	Indians 6, Angels 5  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Richie Sexson's three-run homer capped another  
big inning for Cleveland against the Anaheim Angels, sending 
Charles Nagy and the Indians to a 6-5 victory last night and a 
four-game sweep. Sexson's third homer in three games against the 
Angels gave him 27 this season, and was his second three-run shot 
of the series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
