<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Webster Pleads in Prescription Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEAVER, Pa. (AP) -- NFL Hall of Fame center Mike Webster was  
sentenced to five years' probation Friday after pleading no contest 
to illegally obtaining the prescription drug Ritalin. 
</P>
<P>
	The 46-year-old Webster, who won four Super Bowls with the  
Pittsburgh Steelers, must pay court costs and remain in a treatment 
program under the decision handled down by Judge Joseph Walko in 
Beaver County Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster was accused in February of forging prescriptions to buy  
Ritalin. He could have faced a maximum 15-year prison sentence and 
$250,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster has said he suffers from severe brain damage, and his  
doctors have reported he has a cognitive dysfunction that affects 
the mental process and impairs judgment. Ritalin, a stimulant, can 
help control the condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors have said the blows Webster took on the football field  
might have contributed to the condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
