<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Names Distribution Exec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com on Friday named a new executive to  
oversee its ambitious plan to expand its shipping and distribution 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle-based Internet merchant named Jeffrey Wilke as its  
head of logistics. He replaces Jimmy Wright, a former operations 
expert at Wal-Mart who plans to return to retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilke comes to Amazon.com from Allied Signal, where he was in  
charge of the company's pharmaceutical fine chemicals unit. He was 
directly responsible for 15 plants/distribution centers in the 
United States, Europe and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Amazon.com plans to add three million square feet of  
warehouse space. Its goal is to expand its distribution network so 
it can stock more goods and get them to customers faster. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilke's appointment comes right before the holiday shopping  
season. The company hopes he will be able to work out any kinks in 
its distribution before the Christmas crunch. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on track to deliver our commitments this year,'' said  
Joe Galli, president and chief operating officer at Amazon.com. 
``But we have said from the beginning that there are some startup 
risks ... and some situations we have to smooth out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilke formerly worked in the information technology group at  
Andersen Consulting. He is a graduate of Princeton University and 
did his graduate studies at Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright came out of retirement to join Amazon.con in July 1998.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
