<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Second Russian Bank Employee Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A second Bank of New York employee has been  
dismissed amid an investigation into whether the Russian mob and 
others laundered billions of dollars using the bank's accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	A source familiar with the matter said Thursday that Svetlana  
Kudryavtsev, an associate in the bank's Eastern European division, 
was fired for failing to cooperate with an internal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	A bank spokesman confirmed Ms. Kudryavtsev had been fired, but  
did not provide a reason. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, the bank fired Lucy Edwards, a London-based vice  
president, for gross misconduct, violation of the bank's internal 
policies, falsification of bank records and failure to cooperate 
with the bank's investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement authorities are looking into allegations that up  
to $10 billion was laundered through the bank's accounts by Russian 
organized crime and other figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank had earlier suspended Ms. Edwards along with another  
executive, Natasha Kagalovsky, who supervised the bank's business 
in Eastern Europe from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kagalovsky has denied any wrongdoing. So far, no criminal  
charges have been filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Troubled that its name has been associated with the scandal,  
bank chairman Thomas A. Renyi on Monday sent a memo to employees 
defending the institution's reputation and promising ``prompt 
action'' if any inappropriate action by bank staff was discovered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
