<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton for president in 2000?  
</P>
<P>
	Nah. But a filing with the Federal Election Commission is  
pumping life into the persistent rumor that she has her eye on a 
prize bigger than the U.S. Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative group Judicial Watch is trumpeting the fact  
that FEC records list Mrs. Clinton as a candidate for both the 
Senate and for president. 
</P>
<P>
	They show that in January a committee called People for American  
Leadership filed a statement of organization in support of a bid by 
Mrs. Clinton for president. But the committee, formed by Thomas B. 
McMullen Jr., of Washington, D.C., folded in June without reporting 
any activity, said FEC spokeswoman Sharon Snyder. 
</P>
<P>
	McMullen did not return a telephone call seeking comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The committee's filing also lists a Web site,  
www.hillary4president.org, that describes itself as grass-roots 
call to candidacy for Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The site also says the movement to draft Mrs. Clinton began in  
July 1998 at the 150th anniversary of the women's rights convention 
in Seneca Falls, N.Y., which the first lady addressed. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is considering a run for the seat being vacated by  
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for her exploratory campaign  
committee, brushed aside speculation that Mrs. Clinton was 
interested in her husband's job. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only office that Hillary Clinton is interested in is the  
United States Senate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Sen. Bill Bradley on Friday filed forms  
with the Federal Election Commission that will allow his 
presidential campaign to receive matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Candidates must file papers naming their campaign contributors  
and the amounts they donated so the FEC can determine which are 
eligible for matching federal funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley has requested more than $1.5 million from the FEC based  
on donations from 7,168 supporters from the beginning of the year 
through April 15. 
</P>
<P>
	If the FEC deems each donation matchable, Bradley's campaign  
will receive the amount requested. He already has qualified for 
federal matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley is the first Democratic candidate to submit donor  
information to the FEC. Several Republican candidates already have 
requested matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters Douglas Kiker and Shannon McCaffrey contributed to  
this report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
