<DOCNO> APW19990903.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 01:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect in Atlanta Killings Caught </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- A man arrested after being wounded in a  
shootout with police turned out to be the same man suspected in a 
triple shooting outside Atlanta that left two women dead, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Pierce, 21, is accused in the Aug. 26 shooting of his  
former girlfriend and her two friends who were in the Atlanta area 
attending college. The two friends died. The ex-girlfriend, shot in 
the mouth, survived and identified Pierce as the shooter. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce had attended high school with the women in Boston.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was known to our officers. Our officers have been on the  
lookout,'' said Brookline Police Chief Daniel O'Leary. ``We were 
concerned that he was coming up here. Sure enough, he came up 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police here met up with Pierce when they approached a parked car  
they believed was empty, checking it for a possible registration 
violation. When they got close, two men who had been lying down sat 
up, O'Leary. 
</P>
<P>
	The car sped off and police gave chase. After they surrounded  
the car, gunfire erupted and one man fled. The other fired numerous 
shots at police before being hit in the leg, O'Leary said. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until the suspect was in the hospital that Boston  
police determined it was Pierce, O'Leary said. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver of the car was arrested after he crashed a car he  
allegedly stole after fleeing, O'Leary said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men face charges in Massachusetts including attempted  
murder and gun possession. It was not immediately clear Thursday 
when extradition hearings might begin for Pierce, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure both of us will have our shots at him,'' said Bob  
Mathews, police captain in East Point, Ga., where the Aug. 26 
shootings occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just sorry it's not a more serious wound,'' he said. ``For  
the families and everyone else involved, we're glad he's in 
custody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce is accused of walking into an East Point apartment and  
shooting at the three 18-year-old Boston women, who were best 
friends and high school classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrice Lassiter was killed. Monique Brown, who was to be a  
freshman at Clark Atlanta University, died Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The sole survivor, Shunae Allen, had been Pierce's girlfriend.  
She identified the suspect, who had studied at Morris Brown College 
in Atlanta. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 16:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Alomar Doing it All for Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- His offensive numbers are eye-catching, and his  
defense at second base has been second to none. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Alomar has been everything the Cleveland Indians could  
have hoped for. In fact, they've never had a player like him. 
</P>
<P>
	By getting his 100th RBI in the Indians' 6-5 win over the  
Anaheim Angels on Thursday night, Alomar became the first player in 
club history to drive in 100 runs, score 100, hit 20 homers and 
steal 30 bases in the same year. 
</P>
<P>
	A contrived statistic to be sure, but nonetheless one that  
points out Alomar's all-around excellence in 1999, and why he could 
be the AL's MVP this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is real special,'' Alomar said of RBI No. 100, already  
six more than his previous career best in 12 big-league seasons. 
``I never thought I would get there. I feel good about that, but as 
far as I'm concerned, the year is not over until we get to the 
World Series and win it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has been 51 years since the Indians last won the Series, and  
despite a rash of injuries to key players all season, they're in 
position to make another run. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland, which began a four-game series at Baltimore on Friday  
night, will likely clinch a fifth straight AL Central crown in the 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	OK, the Indians were expected to win baseball's weakest  
division, especially after signing Alomar as a free agent last 
November. But the 10-time All-Star has been even better than 
advertised, finally filling the biggest hole -- the club used 18 
different second baseman since 1996 -- in Cleveland's lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was Robbie's 100th RBI?,'' Richie Sexson said  
incredulously after Thursday's game. ``For a second baseman, that's 
pretty unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unbelievable. That word has been used frequently this season to  
describe Alomar, who seems to make a sparkling defensive play every 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	During the series against the Angels, he made two plays that  
rank among his season's best. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday night he made a diving backhanded stop on the edge  
of the grass in short right-center, and from a sitting position 
threw out Jim Edmonds at first. The previous night, he went far to 
his left, again made a diving grab, and from his belly, shoveled 
the ball backhanded in time to first. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always take great pride in my defense,'' said Alomar. ``You  
can win a lot of games hitting, but you can win more with 
defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Offensively, Alomar has flourished batting third in the Indians'  
lineup behind Kenny Lofton and Omar Vizquel, and in front of Manny 
Ramirez, the majors' RBI leader. 
</P>
<P>
	His 22nd homer Thursday night matched his career-high set in  
1996 with Baltimore, and gave him the Indians' club record for 
homers by a switch-hitter in a season, passing Carlos Baerga and 
Eddie Murray, who each hit 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, completely healed after assorted injury problems the  
past two years, is currently among the league leaders in average 
(.330), RBIs (100), steals (32), on-base percentage (.429) and 
walks (84). He leads the league in runs (117), and would have to be 
among the top five candidates for MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would mean a lot,'' he said. ``But that's not something I'm  
shooting for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar joined the Indians so he could be reunited with his  
brother, Sandy, the Indians' catcher who has spent most of the 
season on the disabled list following knee surgery and is getting 
closer to a return. 
</P>
<P>
	``To win a World Series would top it all, 100 RBIs, MVP, all of  
it,'' he said. ``That's what I'm shooting for.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 16:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
