<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 21:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Braves' Galarraga Back With the Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Big Cat is back, and so is his familiar big  
smile. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta Braves first baseman Andres Galarraga, sidelined since  
spring training after undergoing cancer treatment, won't be playing 
this season, but his cancer is gone and he'll be on the bench for 
the remainder of the year rooting his teammates on. 
</P>
<P>
	His first game back was a success. The Braves beat Arizona 7-3  
to extend their NL East lead over the New York Mets to 4 1/2 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was exciting to put on the uniform and be with those guys  
on the bench,'' Galarraga said. ``I feel like a little kid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing his familiar No. 14 uniform, Galarraga hung out with his  
teammates during batting practice and returned to the field shortly 
before the game against the Arizona Diamondbacks, accompanying 
coach Pat Corrales as he brought out the lineup card. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd gave Galarraga a standing ovation and one fan held up  
a sign that said, ``The Braves Big Cat Is Back. Welcome Back 
Andres.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I almost started crying,'' he said. ``I could feel my eyes  
getting wet. I want to thank the fans for all the support they have 
given me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the game, fellow Venezuelan Eddie Perez playfully wrestled  
with Galarraga near first after they shook hands with the players 
coming off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to touch my base, and he didn't want me to,''  
Galarraga said, breaking into a grin once again. ``I touched it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Braves have remained a first-place team without  
Galarraga -- they won Friday for the 13th time in 14 games -- they 
welcomed his presence in the clubhouse and the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't replace that smile. You can't replace that attitude.  
You can't replace that personality,'' Chipper Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Galarraga has returned to the Atlanta dugout, the  
Braves still have his No. 14 written on their caps as they have all 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be fun for him to be around the guys for  
a while,'' Walt Weiss added. ``It's great to see him. He looks 
good. His spirits are high. They always are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until Friday, Galarraga had remained home in West Palm Beach,  
Fla., while undergoing treatment. His black-and-gray hair, which 
fell out during chemotherapy, has grown back. 
</P>
<P>
	``All throughout the treatment, we've been watching his tumor  
and it actually has disappeared, so we're very, very happy and 
excited,'' said Galarraga's physician, Dr. Luis Barreras, who was 
at the first baseman's side during the news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors discovered a cancerous tumor pressing against  
Galarraga's spine on Feb. 18. He underwent chemotherapy for four 
months (six treatments in all, one every three weeks) followed by 
radiation treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	``The chemo was the toughest part,'' said Galarraga, adding ``it  
really made me sick for 2-3 days after the treatment, but I can't 
complain. I've been positive all the time and I can play baseball 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga, who admitted he has added about 25 pounds to his  
6-foot-3, 235-pound frame, said he will be in uniform and travel 
with the Braves the rest of the season. He must strengthen his back 
before he can return to the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to be here to be with the team, at least in the  
dugout,'' he said, adding that he will provide support ``all the 
way to the World Series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barreras said Galarraga can begin workouts in November and is  
expected to be ready to play when spring training opens in 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he'll be able to play next year, but for right now  
he'll just be a big support for his team. I think his smile will be 
enough,'' Barreras said. 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga, who turned 38 in June, was an All-Star last year when  
he had a .305 average and led the Braves with 44 homers and 121 
RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling young. I feel healthy and I'm not thinking of age.  
A lot of players play past 40. Why not me?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga, who signed a $24.75 million, three-year contract with  
the Braves before the 1998 season, also has played with Montreal, 
St. Louis and Colorado. He has a .290 career average with 332 
homers and 1,172 RBIs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
