<DOCNO> APW19990903.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 12:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lemieux Wins Control of Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux won bankruptcy court approval  
today to take control of the Pittsburgh Penguins, making him the 
first retired player to become the owner of a major sports team for 
which he played. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz approved the deal within  
minutes of Lemieux's 9 a.m. court appearance, ending a 10-month 
odyssey of bankruptcy for the club Lemieux led to two Stanley Cups. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like we've done something and succeeded. Now the  
puck's on Mr. Lemieux's stick and we've all seen what he's been 
able to do with that,'' Markovitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge sealed the deal by approving an agreement between  
Lemieux's ownership group and SMG, the Philadelphia-based company 
that leases the Civic Arena and rents the space to the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one thing to bring the team out of bankruptcy. We have to  
make it viable now. Hopefully, we can make this a great success 
story,'' Lemieux said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delays in finalizing the agreement, in which SMG agreed to  
invest $5 million in the team, postponed Lemieux's closing on the 
team several times over the past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully the Penguins will thrive and survive in  
Pittsburgh,'' SMG attorney Daniel Shapira said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the NHL's board of governors approved Lemieux's  
takeover of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Lemieux came into the picture, there was still some doubt  
whether the Penguins would remain in Pittsburgh, or even in the 
NHL. The team went into bankruptcy last season and was only able to 
meet its payroll with the help of a bank loan. 
</P>
<P>
	With approval of Lemieux's takeover, the Penguins made it just  
under the wire. They are scheduled to open training camp Saturday 
and will play their first exhibition game Sept. 11 against the New 
York Islanders. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said he and his group of investors, numbering more than  
a dozen, have put together $52 million so far and hope to raise 
more money. He said the market value of the Penguins is currently 
$85 million, or the price of an expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux has the largest stake in the team, most of it coming  
from the $25 million in deferred salary the Penguins owed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux will keep the hockey operation in the hands of general  
manager Craig Patrick while he concentrates on the business side 
with the help of others. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a team effort, just like it was in the 90s  
when we were winning Cups,'' Lemieux said. The Lemieux-led Penguins 
won championships in 1991 and 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux has said he will cut ticket prices immediately upon  
assuming control of the team, but he did not detail how he would do 
that. He said the prices should allow a family to attend a game 
without paying $200 or $300. Any reduction should help the team 
meet its goal of selling 12,000 season tickets for the 1999-2000 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	About 8,000 season tickets have been sold so far, even with the  
team's future uncertain for much of the summer. Last year, the team 
sold only 8,300 season tickets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 12:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
