<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 15:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ordonez, Lopez Say Fight Behind Them </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Whatever caused the fight between Rey Ordonez  
and Luis Lopez is behind them, they said one day after Lopez 
punched Ordonez, leaving the New York Mets' starting shortstop with 
six stitches over his left eye. 
</P>
<P>
	The players addressed reporters along with general manager Steve  
Phillips on Friday, but not before Phillips told them not to talk 
about details of the fight that took place on the team bus early 
Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is over,'' Ordonez said. ``It's a new day. Let's  
play baseball. That's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened was that we exchanged words and had an  
argument,'' Lopez said. ``It's over with. Rey and I talked with 
Steve and Bobby (Valentine, manager) and we're ready to play 
ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ordonez was ready to play Friday night against the Colorado  
Rockies, despite the swelling and the stitches. He has no 
blurriness or double vision and was cleared by doctors to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter how he looks, as long as he can see well  
enough to field grounders and hit the ball,'' Valentine said. 
``This is a baseball game, not a beauty contest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight came on the bus ride back from Newark International  
Airport early Thursday morning after the Mets completed a 3-3 road 
trip at Arizona and Houston. While neither player will miss any 
time, Valentine was unhappy with the judgment they showed with the 
team in the pennant race. 
</P>
<P>
	With four weeks to play, the Mets entered the day 3 1/2 games  
behind Atlanta in the NL East and four games ahead of Cincinnati in 
the wild-card race. Every game is critical as the Mets seek their 
first postseason berth in 11 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to them a bit about responsibility,'' Valentine said.  
``We can't do anything about what already happened. I hope in the 
future each of them can learn from this situation and become more 
responsible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the players nor Phillips would say what the fight was  
about, but Phillips did deny reports that Ordonez started the fight 
because Lopez was hazing rookie Jorge Toca. 
</P>
<P>
	``This wasn't about hazing,'' Phillips said. ``This had to do  
with a situation between these two guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips would not say what discipline the team imposed on  
either player, though it is believed both were fined. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
