<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Olympic Athlete Charged in Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- Leo Adolphus Garnes, who represented his  
native Barbados in the 1992 Olympics, was charged with capital 
murder in the shooting deaths of his ex-girlfriend and her sister. 
</P>
<P>
	Garnes, 31, a standout for the Alabama A&AMP;M cross-country team in  
1993, was being held Friday in the Madison County Jail without 
bond. 
</P>
<P>
	He is accused of shooting Nichol Richele Grant, 23, and her  
sister, Carla NaTasha Grant, 20, in an apparent domestic argument. 
Nichol Grant, the mother of Garnes' 5-month-old daughter, Eboni, 
died at the scene Tuesday. Carla Grant died Wednesday at a 
Huntsville hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Huntsville police Sgt. Rex Reynolds said Friday the women  
apparently went to Garnes' Huntsville apartment, where the shooting 
occurred, because of a dispute over personal property. 
</P>
<P>
	An officer arriving at the apartment after the shootings saw  
Garnes leaving the apartment and asked him to stop, police Sgt. 
Juan Joyner said. Garnes confessed to police at the scene, Reynolds 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds said there had been a dispute over the custody of the  
5-month-old child, but the argument Tuesday was apparently over 
something else. The child wasn't present at the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had religious convictions, and so did she,'' said the Rev.  
James Doggette of Madison Mission Seventh Day Adventist Church. 
``You would always see both of them in church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doggette said Garnes told him he had run 26 miles Sunday to work  
off energy and ponder his problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was trying to work his way through some struggles.  
Unfortunately, there was an explosion,'' Doggette said. 
</P>
<P>
	Garnes, who ran the 5,000 meters for Barbados in the 1992  
Olympics at Barcelona, Spain, was selected outstanding men's track 
runner in the Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Conference in 1993. 
He hasn't been enrolled at A&AMP;M since 1994, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The capital murder charge carries a possible death sentence, if  
convicted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
