<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Times Raises Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times is raising the newsstand  
price of its weekday newspaper in the metropolitan area from 60 
cents to 75 cents. The change takes effect on Sept. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The $2.50 cost of the Sunday newspaper, home delivery prices and  
the $1 newsstand price for the daily Northeast and national 
editions will not change. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first increase in suggested newsstand prices since  
September 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since we last raised the price we have increased the value of  
our product for our readers, added color, added new sections,'' 
Times spokeswoman Lisa Carparelli said Wednesday. ``We will 
continue to reinvest in our product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times Co., with holdings including The Boston Globe  
and 21 regional newspapers, three magazines, eight TV stations, two 
radio stations and nearly 50 Web sites, had revenues of $2.9 
billion in 1998. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
