<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 23:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Roger Ebert &AMP; The Movies' Debuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- It's like Rodgers without Hammerstein. Cagney  
without Lacey. Thelma without Louise. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently, there is no other name that goes with Ebert other  
than Siskel -- at least for now. 
</P>
<P>
	Movie critic Roger Ebert has opted not to have a headlining  
co-host as he begins his first full season without Gene Siskel, who 
died last February while recovering from brain surgery at the age 
of 53. 
</P>
<P>
	Their widely circulated show, formerly known as ``Siskel &AMP;  
Ebert,'' is now simply called ``Roger Ebert &AMP; The Movies.'' It 
debuts this weekend with ``Good Morning America'' critic Joel 
Siegel as the first of at least three regular co-hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I doubt we will ever find a replacement for Gene,'' says Mary  
Kellogg, an executive producer at Buena Vista Television, 
syndicator of the show. ``It was a rare moment in television where 
two individuals work. I don't think it's replaceable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When ``Siskel and Ebert'' went into syndication in 1982, the tag  
team arguably became the most recognizable and influential movie 
critics in the nation. Their trademark ``thumbs-up'' and 
``thumbs-down'' reviews became a benchmark for the movie industry, 
and viewers were drawn to their argumentative banter. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Siegel, other co-hosts on the revamped show will include  
CNN's Jeff Greenfield, who has been friends with Ebert since 
college, and Joyce Kulhawik of WBZ-TV in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegel first appeared on the Chicago-based show last season when  
Ebert and his producers were trying to figure out how to keep the 
show running while coping with Siskel's death. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first time I did the show, which was in May, I was really  
struck at how much Roger missed Gene. It was just very obvious,'' 
Siegel says. ``He'd been in this situation and he'd turn to his 
right, and it was obvious that he expected to see Gene -- and there 
I was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ebert, who was traveling Friday, could not be reached for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, Kellogg says the show will feature an updated set  
with ``more contemporary colors,'' a new theme song and different 
on-screen graphics. 
</P>
<P>
	The program format will, however, remain the same with Ebert and  
his co-host du jour continuing to comment on clips from movies, 
from blockbusters to low-budget art films. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, the co-hosts also will be allowed to join Ebert in  
giving a thumbs-up or thumbs-down rating -- something they stopped 
doing after Siskel's death. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did it out of respect for Gene, as it was still his  
season,'' Kellogg says. ``Now we're moving on to the next phase.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Siegel says he's finding it difficult to sum up a movie with one  
gesture, especially when he has mixed feelings about a film. He 
says he's also adjusting to other aspects of the show, including 
having to keep his ratings secret until the actual taping. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to confess, I felt like a guest,'' Siegel says of the  
Chicago taping of this weekend's show. 
</P>
<P>
	He laughs, then adds, ``And one of the things that strikes me  
about Roger is that when you disagree with him, he takes it very 
personally. ... He gets this hurt little boy look on his face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Programming experts say those may be just the sort of reactions  
TV viewers are looking for, a sort of friendly tension that Siskel 
and Ebert -- who grew to like one another -- made their trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	Either way, at least one TV industry insider says she thinks  
Ebert has enough clout to keep the show a success. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ebert is still respected and well-known,'' Shelby Mason,  
associate director of programming at New York-based Petry 
Television, a company that serves as a liaison between TV stations 
and syndicators. ``And if there isn't any competition (from other 
shows), I'm sure people who are curious would definitely view it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
