<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Israel Says Peace Deal Imminent  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said today  
that Israeli and Palestinian negotiators were ``very close' to 
reaching a deal for a revised West Bank land-for-security 
agreement. The revised agreement had been held up by a dispute over 
Palestinian prisoners to be released by Israel, but that problem 
had been resolved, Israeli officials said. Egypt's Middle East News 
Agency quoted Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat as saying that a 
deal had been reached and would be signed tomorrow night at the Red 
Sea port of Sharm el-Sheikh. 

</P>
<P>
	Charges Dropped in Diana Probe  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A French judge has dismissed all charges against  
nine photographers and a press motorcyclist implicated in the car 
crash that killed Princess Diana, ending the two-year investigation 
into the accident, judicial sources said today. Judge Herve Stephan 
said the accident was the result of an intoxicated driver, who also 
was taking drugs incompatible with alcohol, the sources said. 
Stephan also concluded that the decision by Dodi Fayed, Diana's 
boyfriend, to order an off-duty security official, who was drunk, 
to drive the Mercedes, also contributed to the crash. 

</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Drops to 4.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate dipped back  
down to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent in August as gains in 
computer, data processing and health care jobs helped offset 
continued job losses at factories. The Labor Department reported 
today that the decrease in August's unemployment rate followed a 
4.3 percent rate in July. Despite the decline in the unemployment 
rate, employers added a smaller-than-expected 124,000 jobs to their 
payrolls in August, following a gain of 338,000 jobs in July. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Killed in Fla. Plane Crash  
</P>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- An ambulance plane flying from  
Michigan to Boca Raton crashed into a strip mall early today while 
trying to make an emergency landing, killing at least four of the 
seven people aboard. It wasn't immediately known if any were 
patients. The plane, a twin-engine Beechcraft King Air BE-90, hit 
the roof of a mall building at about 3:30 a.m., according to a 
Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman. All four of the dead 
were aboard the plane, a National Transportation Safety Board 
official said. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Discusses Banking Scandal  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin, who has remained silent  
on an alleged money laundering scandal linked to Russia, summoned a 
top security officer to the Kremlin today for private talks on the 
controversy. In the most serious case, U.S. investigators are 
trying to determine whether Russian criminal groups laundered up to 
$10 billion through the Bank of New York. No one has been charged 
with a crime, and the Russian government has not been accused of 
any wrongdoing. The country's Federal Security Service is 
investigating the extent of Russian involvement. 

</P>
<P>
	More FBI-Waco Evidence Is Found  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Roundly criticized for not disclosing evidence  
related to its 1993 assault on the Branch Davidian cult, the FBI 
released a videotape on which an FBI commander is heard authorizing 
the use of incendiary tear gas hours before a deadly fire ended the 
Davidians' 51-day standoff with federal agents. The FBI made the 
tape public yesterday as Attorney General Janet Reno asked an 
outsider to head an independent inquiry into the FBI's long-denied 
use of flammable weapons during the April 19, 1993, assault near 
Waco, Texas. 

</P>
<P>
	NatWest Seeks L&AMP;G Acquisition  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British banking giant National Westminster Bank  
PLC is in talks to buy life insurance and pensions company Legal &AMP; 
General Group PLC, NatWest said today. The bank, the third largest 
in Britain, is in advanced talks with the company for a cash and 
stock deal that would create a powerful force in the British 
financial services sector and one of the country's largest fund 
management groups. NatWest will pay $17 billion for Legal &AMP; 
General, The Financial Times reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo's key stock index closed slightly lower today  
as the Nikkei fell 1.26 points to close at 17,629.99. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuba Contradicts Pan Am Drug Tests  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- President Fidel Castro said his country's own  
investigation shows that two Cuban gold medalists who tested 
positive for drugs at last month's Pan American games were the 
victims of a plot. Castro said that multiple urine tests of 
weightlifters William Vargas and Rolando Delgado conducted by Cuba 
and sent to three different laboratories in Europe all tested 
negative for the anabolic steroid Nandrolone. However, urine tests 
analyzed by a Canadian lab during the games in Winnipeg, Manitoba, 
showed Vargas and Delgado testing positive for the drug. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  



</P>
