<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Board Won't Go Public This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Stock Exchange will wait until at  
least next year before making any decision on when and how the 
world's largest stock market might shift to public ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	The Big Board is currently privately owned by its members, or  
seat holders. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Grasso, the chairman of the NYSE, said earlier this  
summer that he had hoped the exchange could complete an initial 
public offering, or IPO, this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	But after a meeting of the board of directors of the exchange  
Thursday, Grasso announced the NYSE first had to come up with a 
strategic business plan that would satisfy a number of ``very 
significant public policy questions.'' He said that study wouldn't 
be completed until sometime next year and that a decision then 
would be made on whether to proceed with an IPO. 
</P>
<P>
	Work on the strategic plan is to begin immediately.  
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE and the Nasdaq Stock Market both are considering IPOs  
to fend off competition from rival electronic trading exchanges, 
known as ECNs for electronic communications networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the NYSE and Nasdaq believe going public will give them the  
flexibility to compete with ECNs, which can provide faster and 
cheaper trades. 
</P>
<P>
	Both markets also have said the stock created in an IPO could be  
used to buy or team up with an ECN. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview Thursday evening on cable financial channel  
CNBC, Grasso said the NYSE could set up or team up with an ECN even 
before an IPO. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any doubt that to the extent that we're  
going to launch an ECN ... that that will come sooner than an IPO 
will come,'' Grasso said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since many of the ECNs are either publicly traded or are units  
of publicly traded companies, they already have stock that can be 
used for expansion or upgrading technology, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the issues that will be studied is how the exchange would  
be policed as a public company. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE now is self-regulated, and imposes fines and other  
penalties on members who cheat investors and break other rules. The 
NYSE also is answerable to the Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC officials have raised concerns that the NYSE's regulatory  
obligations would be compromised if the exchange was to shift to a 
publicly traded company that is accountable to shareholders seeking 
profits from their investments. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the $64,000 question, from the SEC's perspective,''  
said David Bayless, former head of the SEC's San Francisco office. 
</P>
<P>
	The question poses a dilemma for the exchange and potential NYSE  
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayless, echoing officials at the SEC, said the best answer may  
be for the NYSE to split off its regulatory operations into a 
separate organization, affiliated with but not part of the stock 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Grasso told reporters after the board meeting that another  
possible solution would be to merge regulatory operations with the 
independent enforcement of the National Association of Securities 
Dealers, the organization that also oversees Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the SEC, said he looks forward to  
working closely with the NYSE on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We share a common interest in ensuring that any future  
self-regulatory structure is consistent with the protection of 
investors and the maintenance of fair and orderly markets,'' Levitt 
said in a statement released in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Also under study is the membership structure of the exchange in  
the event of an IPO and how its 1,366 seat holders would be 
compensated in a transfer to public ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	One idea floated has members receiving stock in exchange for  
their seats. But that plan could be scuttled by members who don't 
want to pay the capital gains taxes that would be assessed on that 
type of stock transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	Any plan needs to be approved by two-thirds of the members.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, it's all going to boil down to what's in it for  
the members, whether the members feel it's a good deal 
financially,'' said John Burke, a 20-year seat holder with John 
Burke Securities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
