<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United Shuttle Turbulence Hurts 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- None of the passengers on board a United  
Shuttle flight was prepared for the pocket of turbulence that sent 
it plunging dramatically from its 24,000-feet cruising altitude. 
</P>
<P>
	The seat belt light was out about halfway between Los Angeles  
and San Francisco, and some of the 107 passengers aboard the 
Thursday afternoon flight were roaming through the Boeing 737. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the plane dipped, sending many of them flying through the  
cabin, injuring 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I looked out the window,'' said passenger Maureen  
Cheesman, ``my first thought was, `It's going down.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Cheesman was traveling with her daughter's high school soccer  
team from Quincy, Mass. Five of the 57-member group were hurt, 
including 8-year-old Benjamin Francisco, who suffered a gash on his 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	Team coach Paul Bregoli said he saw some of the children  
``bounce up from their seats and hit their heads on the overhead 
compartments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Passenger Ronald Kalio said ``everybody went straight to the  
ceiling. There was two stewardesses that spent the rest of the trip 
in the aisles. They were knocked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the injuries involved sprains, cuts and back pain.  
Thirteen passengers and two flight attendants were treated at area 
hospitals and released, United spokesman Joe Hopkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane continued to San Francisco International Airport and  
landed safely less than an hour later, a Federal Aviation 
Administration spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopkins said United is ``90 percent sure'' the plane encountered  
wake turbulence, a common disturbance caused by air stirred up by 
another plane. 
</P>
<P>
	A larger MD-11 passenger jet was in front of the United jet, but  
was ahead by at least 10 miles, the minimum legally required 
separation, said Ron Wilson, a San Francisco airport spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson said the United plane may have hit clear-air turbulence,  
a rarer, more severe phenomenon which cannot be detected in 
advance. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA and the National Transportation Safety Board were  
investigating. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
