Nasdaq Composite Index        2842.58  + 108.34
Gold(final) -    $253.90    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.
Silver(final) -   $5.150  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.

</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Drops to 4.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unemployment edged down to 4.2 percent last  
month, returning to a 29-year low, as a pre-Labor Day government 
report today spelled good news for job seekers without re-igniting 
inflation jitters on Wall Street. Businesses added a 
smaller-than-expected 124,000 jobs to payrolls in August, after a 
gain of 338,000 jobs in July, and reported moderate wage growth, 
the Labor Department said. Economists and investors viewed the 
developments as signs that job growth is slowing to a more 
sustainable pace, and wages are growing slowly enough to keep from 
touching off inflation. 

</P>
<P>
	European Stocks Close at 4-Day High  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed at a four-day high today,  
buoyed by a strong showing on Wall Street as inflation fears 
cooled. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies had one 
of its biggest percentage gains this year, rising 7.13 points, or 
2.3 percent, to close at 312.32. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, 
which tracks 297 companies in countries that joined the single 
currency, closed up 7.78 points at 327.22. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 
50 Index rose 90.74 points to 3,809.11, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index 
closed up 92.73 points at 3,744.20. In domestic markets, London's 
FTSE 100 blue-chip index closed up 2.2 percent at 6,332.10; 
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX jumped 2.8 percent to 5,336.22; the Paris 
CAC-40 index rose 2.7 percent to 4,672.37; Milan's MIBtel index 
rose 2.2 percent to 34,001.00; and Amsterdam's AEX index rose 2.4 
percent to 578.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Predicts Lower Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Coca-Cola Co. said today third-quarter  
earnings will fall short of expectations. Atlanta-based Coca-Cola 
predicted earnings per share will be 34 cents to 35 cents this 
quarter, compared with analysts' predictions of 36 cents. On top of 
that, the company said it will reduce earnings by an additional 2 
cents to 3 cents a share because of the recall stemming from a 
health scare linked to Coke in Belgium and France. Coke blamed slow 
growth in beverage sales on the continuing economic turmoil abroad. 
Coca Cola stock was down 2 1/8, or 3.57 percent, at 57 3/8 today. 

</P>
<P>
	Workers Become More Demanding  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- This Labor Day, thousands of workers will mark  
the holiday either on strike or thinking about walking a picket 
line. Labor experts say despite agreements like the contract 
reached between Boeing and its machinists earlier this week, unions 
are growing more aggressive and more willing to walk out. Nine 
straight years of economic growth, a string of high-profile 
strikes, and a chance to win back concessions from past contracts 
have put pressure on negotiators to bring back good deals. Bill 
Johnson, president of Aerospace Machinists Industrial District 
Lodge 751 in Seattle, said Wednesday after his union approved the 
Boeing contract. ``You can take on a major corporation and be 
successful.'' 

</P>
<P>
	WHO Decries Flawed Drug Donations  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Up to two-thirds of the drugs donated during  
humanitarian emergencies are unsuitable, badly labeled or near the 
end of their shelf life, the U.N. health agency Friday as it issued 
tightened guidelines on drug donations. Medical staff in countries 
in crisis have had to waste their time sorting out masses of drugs 
that they cannot use and that are costly to dispose of, the World 
Health Organization said. The updated WHO guidelines urge donors to 
ensure that their gifts respect the wishes of the receiving 
country, avoid double standards in quality and are based on good 
communication with the recipients. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Says IMF May Delay Payment  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund's next loan  
installment to Russia may be delayed, the country's finance 
minister said today as he insisted that no previous IMF money was 
misspent. Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said the IMF board in 
Washington, which had planned to meet later this month, may not 
convene until October to discuss releasing the second installment 
of a $4.5 billion loan to help Russia pay its debts. Russian 
officials have said that a visiting IMF delegation was satisfied 
with the government's adherence to loan conditions. The IMF team 
flew out on Friday, but did not comment on its findings. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Looks Into Banking Scandal  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin, who has remained silent  
on an alleged money laundering scandal linked to Russia, summoned a 
top security officer to the Kremlin today for private talks on the 
controversy. In another corruption case, Russia's suspended chief 
prosecutor, Yuri Skuratov, confirmed today that Yeltsin and his 
daughters were linked to an investigation into an alleged bribery 
scandal. In the most serious corruption case, U.S. investigators 
are trying to determine whether Russian criminal groups laundered 
up to $10 billion through the Bank of New York. No one has been 
charged with a crime, and the Russian government has not been 
accused of any wrongdoing. 

</P>
<P>
	Malaysia PM Skips Pacific Rim Talks  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad  
will not attend next week's annual summit of Pacific Rim leaders in 
New Zealand, fueling speculation Friday about imminent general 
elections in Malaysia. Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar said 
Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi would stand in for 
Mahathir at the Sept. 12-13 summit of the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation forum. ``It should not be interpreted as a snub,'' Syed 
Hamid told reporters. The move, however, whipped up widespread 
speculation that Mahathir, Asia's longest-serving leader, is 
preparing to dissolve Parliament and call a quick poll. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
