<DOCNO> APW19990903.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 17:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Collins Resigns As Angels' Manager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- A tearful Terry Collins resigned as the  
Anaheim Angels' manager on Friday, less than three months after the 
last-place team gave him a two-year contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Maddon, the Angels' bench coach, will take over as interim  
manager for the rest of this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Anaheim began Friday with a nine-game losing streak and a 51-82  
record, the worst in the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins and general manager Bill Bavasi said the manager was not  
forced out. The two had a long talk Thursday night, and both 
decided it would be best if he quit now. 
</P>
<P>
	Bavasi said he made his recommendation to Collins ``a little bit  
for the club and mostly for Terry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he's not bitter, but I'm bitter. This club had every  
reason to respond and didn't. This is just bad chemistry in the 
clubhouse,'' Bavasi said. ``The team didn't quit on Terry; I can't 
imagine anybody quitting on Terry. ... They quit on themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels were still in contention at the All-Star break, but  
lost 37 of their next 47 to plummet into last place in the AL West. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is, the team's got to perform,'' Collins said.  
``When you don't perform, the manager's accountable. I had a 
feeling today that this is the time. I tried everything I knew, 
from patting them on the back to try to motivate them to kicking 
them in the butt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, 50, hadn't spoken to any of the players about the  
decision, although he said he planned to talk later with some of 
them individually. 
</P>
<P>
	His decision apparently had lot more to do with the players'  
squabbling among themselves than it did with the team's record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday in Cleveland, I had to address a couple of issues  
again and was unable to talk about the game, and that's when it hit 
me,'' Collins said. ``I won't miss the bickering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Bavasi asked some players for their opinion of the manager  
before Collins' contract was renewed, players seemed to splinter 
into pro- and anti-Collins factions. A few unidentified players 
complained about Collins' managing style, but he was given the 
extension anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Second baseman Randy Velarde, who publicly took issue with  
Collins, was traded to Oakland along with starting pitcher Omar 
Olivares for three minor leaguers on July 29. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest clubhouse flareup came when reliever Troy Percival  
complained that not all of his teammates were on the field during a 
brawl with in Cleveland on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident began began after Percival allowed a three-run  
homer to Richie Sexson, capping a 10-run, eighth-inning rally, and 
then hit David Justice with a pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Mo Vaughn was in the clubhouse watching on TV and went to the  
dugout, but said he arrived too late to go on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Percival noted that some players hadn't participated in the  
fight, an apparent reference to Vaughn. The following day, Vaughn 
complained that no Angels' pitcher has retaliated this year after 
he was hit, and criticized Percival for hitting Justice, saying, 
``Take a beating like a man and get the next out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bavasi said the makeup of the team doesn't seem to be working,  
and that he accepted responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than we're going to be looking for a manager the rest of  
this season, we're going to be looking at the players,'' he said. 
``I don't know how they're going to react to this, and I'd be less 
than honest if I said I cared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anaheim could be headed for the poorest season in the Angels'  
39-season history -- worse than the 1980 team's 65-95 mark. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like they're the Harlem Globetrotters out there, and  
we're the Washington Generals,'' Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina 
said after Thursday night's 6-5 loss at Cleveland, which turned out 
to be Collins' final game. 
</P>
<P>
	After managing the Houston Astros to second-place finishes in  
the NL Central from 1994-96, Collins went to Anaheim and had a 
220-237 record with the Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in clubhouses where guys don't like each other,''  
Collins said. ``But when I was in Houston, they still went out and 
played hard every game. The manager has one hammer these days, the 
lineup card, and that's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team had high expectations after signing Vaughn to an $80  
million, six-year contract last November, and began the season with 
baseball's 13th-highest payroll at $51.5 million. But the season 
was filled with injuries and discontent. 
</P>
<P>
	DiSarcina was one of several key players sidelined for an  
extended period, along with Vaughn, outfielders Jim Edmonds and Tim 
Salmon, and pitchers Ken Hill, Tim Belcher, Jason Dickson, Mike 
James, Pep Harris and Jack McDowell. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, criticized in the past for being too intense, signed  
the extension on June 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't believe there's a better place to work,'' he  
said then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 17:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Industry Wins Fla. Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The tobacco industry won a major victory Friday  
when a state appeals court ruled that damage claims in a landmark 
smoking case must be considered one smoker at a time. That removes 
the threat of a single multibillion-dollar verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling came in a class-action lawsuit that was brought on  
behalf of as many as 500,000 sick Florida smokers. In July, a jury 
decided in the smokers' favor, ruling that the industry produced a 
deadly product. The next step is to decide how much the smokers 
will get in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The question before the appeals court was whether the damage  
claims would be considered as a group, or individually. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has essentially devastated the most threatening aspect of  
the claim to the tobacco industry,'' said Martin Feldman, tobacco 
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. ``This is enormous news on this 
case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Daynard, a Northeastern University law professor who  
heads an anti-tobacco clearinghouse, conceded the ruling erased 
prospects for a crippling damage award. 
</P>
<P>
	A big verdict would have forced tobacco companies to post a  
large bond to appeal the case and could have forced a bankruptcy 
filing this year, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll just be ordinary multimillion punitive verdicts,''  
Daynard said. ``But this thing is still probably the most potent 
litigation on the horizon against the tobacco companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers on both sides were barred by a gag order from talking  
about the case, 
</P>
<P>
	The case was the first class-action lawsuit by smokers ever to  
go to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the second round is set to begin. The jury will  
return to determine whether two sick smokers should be compensated. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants are the nation's five biggest cigarette makers --  
Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, 
Lorillard Tobacco and the Liggett Group -- and two industry 
associations, the Council for Tobacco Research-U.S.A and the 
Tobacco Institute Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	With Friday's decision from the 3rd District Court of Appeal,  
``there is no potential for damages to be decided on a group basis 
and, as a result, this case now doesn't look very different from 
the vast majority of cases brought against the industry,'' Feldman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The individual claims will produce smaller dollar awards, and  
the industry will have an opportunity to wipe out the whole case by 
appealing once one damage award is set, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Results of recent tobacco cases have been mixed. In March, a  
jury in Portland, Ore., awarded $81 million to the family of a 
smoker who died of lung cancer. The month before, a woman with 
inoperable lung cancer won $51 million in San Francisco. Both 
awards were reduced by judges. 
</P>
<P>
	But the industry won another Oregon case as well as lawsuits on  
behalf of unions in Ohio, three dead smokers in Tennessee and one 
in Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. juries have awarded damages in smoking liability cases only  
five times -- twice in Florida and once in New Jersey, Oregon and 
California. Both Florida verdicts and the New Jersey verdict were 
overturned on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The $206 billion national settlement reached with the tobacco  
industry in November bars states from suing to recoup the costs of 
treating sick smokers, but it does not prohibit lawsuits by 
individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Philip Morris surged on news of the ruling, trading in  
late afternoon up $2.37 1/2, or 6 percent, at $39.25 on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the NYSE, R.J. Reynolds rose 75 cents a share to  
$28.37 1/2, Lorillard parent Loews Corp. shares were up $2.81 1/4 at 
$80.37 1/2 and Liggett parent Brooke Group Ltd. was up 18 3/4 cents a 
share to $19.31 1/4. On the American Stock Exchange, Brown &AMP; 
Williamson parent British American Tobacco Co. was up 12 1/2 cents. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 09:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates World Series Trophy Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Someone made off with the gold World Series  
trophy won in 1979 by the Pittsburgh Pirates, but it turned up 
today behind a church. 
</P>
<P>
	A 12-year-old boy was doing cleanup work at the church found it  
in a black plastic bag outside the back door, said Detective Donald 
Pasquarelli. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Mark Ninehouser said two pennants were missing from the  
trophy -- the Boston Red Sox and the Oakland Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said they still don't know who took the trophy or  
how it disappeared from the lobby of the Allegheny Club at Three 
Rivers Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe somebody's conscience was bothering them and they  
decided to turn it in,'' Pasquarelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exception of events like the annual Pirates Fest in  
March and the grand opening of Lazarus department store last year, 
the trophy has rarely left the stadium since it was donated by the 
Galbreath family, former owners of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	But sometime between 5:15 and 6 p.m. Wednesday during a private  
corporate party at the club, the trophy disappeared from an 
unlocked glass display case. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities and a memorabilia expert estimate the value of the  
trophy at $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think it was a guest,'' club president Kevin Vaughn  
said. ``What we think is that someone somehow got into the club and 
just walked out with it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 17:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Today In History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Today is Saturday, Sept. 4, the 247th day of 1999. There are 118  
days left in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Highlight in History:  
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 4, 1781, Los Angeles was founded by Spanish settlers.  
</P>
<P>
	On this date:  
</P>
<P>
	In 1888, George Eastman received a patent for his roll-film  
camera and registered his trademark, Kodak. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1894, some 12,000 tailors in New York City went on strike in  
protest of sweatshops. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1917, the American expeditionary force in France suffered its  
first fatalities in World War I. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1948, Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands abdicated, citing  
health reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1951, in the first live, coast-to-coast television broadcast,  
President Truman addressed the nation from the Japanese peace 
treaty conference in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1957, Arkansas Gov. Orval Faubus called out the National  
Guard to prevent nine black students from entering Central High 
School in Little Rock. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1957, Ford Motor Co. began selling its ill-fated Edsel  
automobile. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, the Food and Drug Administration issued a report  
calling birth control pills safe, despite a slight risk of fatal 
blood-clotting disorders linked to the pills. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1971, an Alaska Airlines jet crashed near Juneau, killing 111  
people. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1972, U.S. swimmer Mark Spitz won a record seventh Olympic  
gold medal, in the 400-meter relay at the Munich Summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years ago: The Air Force launched its last Titan 3 rocket,  
which reportedly carried a reconnaissance satellite. Since 1964, 
the Titan 3 had sent more than 200 satellites into space. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: On the eve of a U.N.-sponsored conference on  
population in Cairo, Egypt, Vice President Al Gore told NBC the 
United States was seeking a blueprint for world population growth 
that rejected abortion as a family planning tool and an 
international right. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: During a visit to Ireland, President Clinton said  
the words ``I'm sorry'' for the first time about his affair with 
Monica Lewinsky, describing his behavior as indefensible. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Birthdays: ABC Radio commentator Paul Harvey is 81.  
Actor-comedian Howard Morris is 80. Cooking expert Craig Claiborne 
is 79. Actress Mitzi Gaynor is 68. Singer Merald ``Bubba'' Knight 
(Gladys Knight &AMP; The Pips) is 57. Actress Jennifer Salt is 55. 
Golfer Tom Watson is 50. Rhythm-and-blues musician Ronald LaPread 
(The Commodores) is 49. Actress Judith Ivey is 48. Rock musician 
Martin Chambers (The Pretenders) is 47. Actor-comedian Damon Wayans 
is 39. Rock musician Kim Thayil (formerly of Soundgarden) is 39. 
Actress Ione Skye is 28. Hip-hop singer JeLana LaFleur (Quad City 
DJ's) is 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Thought for Today: ``One should respect public opinion insofar  
as is necessary to avoid starvation and to keep out of prison, but 
anything that goes beyond this is voluntary submission to an 
unnecessary tyranny, and is likely to interfere with happiness in 
all kinds of ways.'' -- Bertrand Russell, English 
mathematician-philosopher (1872-1970). 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
