<DOCNO> APW19990903.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Foyt Returning to Winston Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DARLINGTON, S.C. (AP) -- An old face will make a new start next  
year in NASCAR when A.J. Foyt returns to Winston Cup racing as a 
car owner. 
</P>
<P>
	And Foyt, a four-time Indianapolis 500 champion and winner of  
the 1972 Daytona 500, will run the entire Winston Cup schedule for 
the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 64-year-old Foyt, conditioned to winning championships  
with his Indy Racing League cars, is not abandoning the IRL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just be doing a lot of commuting,'' Foyt said Friday at  
Darlington Raceway. ``It might be a little tough to do the 
Indianapolis 500 and the Coca-Cola 600 in the same day, but I'll 
get there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt, despite infrequent appearances he worked into his Indy-car  
career for more than two decades, is no stranger to NASCAR. And his 
operation out of a 30,0000-square-foot shop in Charlotte, N.C., 
will be run by longtime team manager and crew chief Waddell Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not getting into this just to run,'' said Foyt, who also  
announced a sponsorship deal with Conseco Inc., the financial 
services group that has backed his Indy-car effort. ``We want to go 
out there and finish in the top 10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt realizes the difficulty of that with a single-car operation  
in a sport where all 23 races this year have been won by drivers 
from multicar teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's tough, and it was even when I raced here,'' said  
Foyt, who had seven victories in 128 NASCAR career starts. ``But if 
you hire the right people, you can make some things happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much remains to be done before Foyt will be ready to field his  
first entry in the first race of the next century -- the 
season-opening Daytona 500. Most of the details will be left to 
Wilson, who built the engines and has called the shots for several 
Daytona 500 winners. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the unfinished business is selecting a driver and make of  
car. All Foyt knows at this time is that the car will be his 
familiar No. 14, the number Kenny Brack drove to both the IRL title 
last year and the Indianapolis 500 championship in May. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kenny likes those IROC cars,'' Foyt said of the all-star  
series in which Brack has driven stock cars. ``But I don't think 
he's ready for these Winston Cup cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt might consider owner-driver Ricky Rudd, and discussed  
buying his operation. Rudd, a 20-time career winner who lost his 
lucrative sponsorship, is still seeking backing to keep his own 
operation afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	But he wouldn't rule out driving for Foyt.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know A.J. is a fierce competitor, and I am, too,'' Rudd  
said. ``A.J. and I are alike in that if we were playing tiddlywinks 
we'd probably be kicking each other under the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt is the second open-wheel car owner to announce he's  
entering NASCAR next season. Cal Wells III, who owns cars in CART, 
is forming Winston Cup and Busch Series teams in 2000. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
