<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 13:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aggies Defense Opens With Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) -- It's not a good time for No. 6 Texas A&AMP;M  
to be without linebacker Dat Nguyen. 
</P>
<P>
	Nguyen, the Lombardi Award winner and departed leader of the  
Wrecking Crew defense, now plays for the Dallas Cowboys. The Aggies 
will have to find a defense for Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim 
Rattay when the two teams meet in Independence Stadium on Saturday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Rattay led the nation last season with 4,943 passing yards and  
46 touchdown passes, and the Aggies are gearing up all the 
defensive backs they can muster for their season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be a situation where we have to get five or six  
defensive backs ready to play,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said. ``If 
you get someone dinged up it complicates everything. We may have 
some guys rushed into the game that maybe wouldn't have played 
otherwise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies lost linebackers Nguyen and Warrick Holdman and  
safety Rich Coady from last year's defense that didn't allow a 
touchdown pass from Rattay in a 28-7 victory at Kyle Field. The 
Aggies are the only team to deny Rattay a touchdown pass in 24 
starts at Louisiana Tech. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do try to put pressure on the defensive backs, make them  
play three or four extra guys,'' Rattay said. ``We do different 
things to make our offense successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rattay completed 28 of 40 passes for 240 yards in last week's  
41-7 loss to No. 1 Florida State. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a secondary game,'' A&AMP;M safety Brandon  
Jennings said. ``He's got three or four go-to guys instead of one 
like last year. If our secondary shows up and plays its game, we'll 
be okay. But you've got to be perfect. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take all of us. You can't beat him with just  
four defensive backs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs like to have at least three receivers on the field  
as targets for Rattay, whose quick delivery and beefy offensive 
line keep sacks to a minimum. Florida State got to Rattay only 
once. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their scheme is timed to get the pass off in 1.9 seconds,''  
Slocum said. ``It's almost impossible to get a sack. Maybe if no 
one touched you but even if a guy just steps in front of you the 
ball is gone before you get there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Aggies are 15-point favorites, they're aware of the  
intensity they'll be facing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll go into Shreveport and all their fans will be having a  
good time before we get there,'' A&AMP;M punter Shane Lechler said. 
``They'll be talking about you and all your family. They'll play 
hard as long as they have a chance. If we take care of business 
we'll be OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs play one game annually in Independence Stadium.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite the big loss to Florida State, first-year coach Jack  
Bicknell is glad to have played the first game already. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was great for me too,'' Bicknell said. ``It's so hard the  
first time you do anything. You don't know what to expect. I was 
very nervous at the hotel. Once we got on the field, I settle 
down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies victory last year was later forfeited when it was  
learned that fullback Tiki Hardeman was scholastically ineligible. 
Hardeman sat out the rest of the season and has regained his 
starting spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Randy McCown returns for his senior year at quarterback and  
he'll have veteran receivers Chris Cole and Chris Taylor to try to 
give the Aggies more passing punch. Hardeman will share time with 
huge sophomore Ja'Mar Toombs, who stepped into Hardeman's spot a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Tailback Dante Hall, who rushed for 1,024 yards last season,  
also is back. 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies (11-3 last season) played their final game of last  
season in Louisiana in a 24-14 loss to Ohio State in the Sugar 
Bowl. Their goal is to return to New Orleans in January since the 
Sugar Bowl will be for the national championship. Louisiana Tech 
finished 6-6 last season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
