<DOCNO> APW19990903.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Mideast Deal Said Approved  
</P>
<P>
	GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinians leaders  
will sign an agreement tomorrow to restart a long-delayed West Bank 
pullback by Israel, clearing the way for an overall peace accord 
within a year, a Palestinian Cabinet minister said. Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright, shuttling between the Israelis and 
Palestinians, presided over the diplomatic triumph as the two sides 
overcame last-minute disagreements, mostly over the release of 
Palestinian prisoners. Word of the breakthrough came from 
Palestinian Planning Minister Nabil Shaath, who spoke to reporters 
as Albright met with Yasser Arafat at his headquarters here 
tonight. 

</P>
<P>
	Pro-Indonesia Gangs Roam East Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Marauding gangs of pro-Indonesian  
militias set towns ablaze today and kept up the killing spree that 
has terrorized East Timor since a historic vote earlier this week 
on independence from Indonesia. Thousands of residents fled for 
their lives and frightened U.N. workers were forced to abandon 
their posts as the militias swept through towns in much of the 
territory. With results of the vote to be announced tomorrow and 
independence widely expected to prevail, many fear the violence may 
only get worse. The U.N. mission says it has been ``defenseless'' 
in the face of the deteriorating security situation. 

</P>
<P>
	Reno Denies Rift With FBI Chief  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno denied that the  
escalating Waco controversy has strained her relations with FBI 
Director Louis Freeh. Even so, she said today that she is looking 
outside the FBI and Justice Department to find ``the perfect 
person'' to head an inquiry into the government's 1993 standoff 
with the Branch Davidians. A week after Reno acknowledged that her 
credibility was damaged by the belated FBI admission that 
incendiary tear gas canisters were used in the waning hours of the 
Texas siege, and with new tensions simmering over the FBI's release 
this week of previously undisclosed evidence, she insisted her 
relationship with Freeh remains good. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Opposition Leader Raps West  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- One of Serbia's main opposition  
leaders said his rivals in an anti-government group are trying to 
incite civil war in Serbia on the explicit order of the West, local 
media reported today. The accusations were bound to further deepen 
the rift between already bitterly divided anti-government forces 
here. Vuk Draskovic, head of the Serbian Renewal Movement, said 
other opposition leaders were ``working with clear instructions 
from the West to spark a civil war,'' the state-run Tanjug news 
agency reported today. 

</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Drops to 4.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unemployment edged down to 4.2 percent last  
month, returning to a 29-year low, as a pre-Labor Day government 
report today spelled good news for job seekers without re-igniting 
inflation jitters on Wall Street. Despite the drop in the 
unemployment rate, businesses added a smaller-than-expected 124,000 
jobs to payrolls in August, after a gain of 338,000 jobs in July, 
and reported moderate wage growth, the Labor Department said. 

</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Industry Wins Fla. Appeal  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The tobacco industry won a major victory today when  
a state appeals court ruled that damage claims in a landmark 
smoking case must be considered one smoker at a time. That removes 
the threat of a single multibillion-dollar verdict. The ruling came 
in a class-action lawsuit that was brought on behalf of as many as 
500,000 sick Florida smokers. In July, a jury decided in the 
smokers' favor, ruling that the industry produced a deadly product. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 235.24  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks raced higher today after the government's  
employment report calmed fears about rising inflation and prompted 
a broad rally that included the biggest point gain in the history 
of the Nasdaq composite index. At the close of trading on Wall 
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 235.24 at 
11,078.45. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led 
decliners 2,290-677. The Nasdaq rose 108.34 to 2,842.58, according 
to preliminary calculations, surpassing the previous high for a 
one-day point gain, 103.16, set on June 16. 

</P>
<P>
	Rusedski Advances at U.S. Open  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Britain's Greg Rusedski, who reached the U.S.  
Open final two years ago, moved into the third round today by 
pounding out a 6-4, 6-3, 6-1 victory over Germany's David Prinosil. 
In women's singles, Germany's Anke Huber upset eighth-seeded Jana 
Novotna 6-3, 6-2; Mary Joe Fernandez of Miami ousted No. 13 
Dominique Van Roost of Belgium 7-5, 6-0; and No. 10 Arantxa 
Sanchez-Vicario defeated Switzerland's Patty Schnyder 6-2, 6-2. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 20:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Alomar Doing it All for Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- His offensive numbers are eye-catching, and his  
defense at second base has been second to none. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Alomar has been everything the Cleveland Indians could  
have hoped for. In fact, they've never had a player like him. 
</P>
<P>
	By getting his 100th RBI in the Indians' 6-5 win over the  
Anaheim Angels on Thursday night, Alomar became the first player in 
club history to drive in 100 runs, score 100, hit 20 homers and 
steal 30 bases in the same year. 
</P>
<P>
	A contrived statistic to be sure, but nonetheless one that  
points out Alomar's all-around excellence in 1999, and why he could 
be the AL's MVP this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is real special,'' Alomar said of RBI No. 100, already  
six more than his previous career best in 12 big-league seasons. 
``I never thought I would get there. I feel good about that, but as 
far as I'm concerned, the year is not over until we get to the 
World Series and win it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Alomar hit a three-run homer -- his career-high 23rd --  
and drove in five runs to lead the Indians past the Orioles 7-6. 
The homer rallied Cleveland from a 6-4 deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been 51 years since the Indians last won the Series, and  
despite a rash of injuries to key players all season, they're in 
position to make another run. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland, which began a four-game series at Baltimore on Friday  
night, will likely clinch a fifth straight AL Central crown in the 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	OK, the Indians were expected to win baseball's weakest  
division, especially after signing Alomar as a free agent last 
November. But the 10-time All-Star has been even better than 
advertised, finally filling the biggest hole -- the club used 18 
different second baseman since 1996 -- in Cleveland's lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was Robbie's 100th RBI?,'' Richie Sexson said  
incredulously after Thursday's game. ``For a second baseman, that's 
pretty unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unbelievable. That word has been used frequently this season to  
describe Alomar, who seems to make a sparkling defensive play every 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	During the series against the Angels, he made two plays that  
rank among his season's best. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday night he made a diving backhanded stop on the edge  
of the grass in short right-center, and from a sitting position 
threw out Jim Edmonds at first. The previous night, he went far to 
his left, again made a diving grab, and from his belly, shoveled 
the ball backhanded in time to first. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always take great pride in my defense,'' said Alomar. ``You  
can win a lot of games hitting, but you can win more with 
defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Offensively, Alomar has flourished batting third in the Indians'  
lineup behind Kenny Lofton and Omar Vizquel, and in front of Manny 
Ramirez, the majors' RBI leader. 
</P>
<P>
	His 22nd homer Thursday night matched his career-high set in  
1996 with Baltimore, and gave him the Indians' club record for 
homers by a switch-hitter in a season, passing Carlos Baerga and 
Eddie Murray, who each hit 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar, completely healed after assorted injury problems the  
past two years, is among the league leaders in average (.331), RBIs 
(105), steals (32), on-base percentage (.429) and walks (84). He 
leads the league in runs (119), and would have to be among the top 
five candidates for MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would mean a lot,'' he said. ``But that's not something I'm  
shooting for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar joined the Indians so he could be reunited with his  
brother, Sandy, the Indians' catcher who has spent most of the 
season on the disabled list following knee surgery and is getting 
closer to a return. 
</P>
<P>
	``To win a World Series would top it all, 100 RBIs, MVP, all of  
it,'' he said. ``That's what I'm shooting for.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 20:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
