<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nebraska Healthy and Ready To Roll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Bobby Newcombe and DeAngelo Evans are  
healthy. The defense is sound and coach Frank Solich is over any 
first-year jitters. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska, it would seem, is ready to roll.  
</P>
<P>
	The fifth-ranked Cornhuskers open the season Saturday at Iowa,  
which will be playing its first game with Kirk Ferentz as coach. 
It's a tough way for a new coach to start, especially when facing 
an opponent intent on making amends after losing four games last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	A season with just four losses would be a huge success at Iowa,  
which went 3-8 last fall in coach Hayden Fry's final year. At 
Nebraska, it was devastating because it came one year after the 
Cornhuskers went 13-0 and shared the national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to prove something to ourselves,'' wide receiver Matt  
Davison said. ``The four losses just didn't sit well with us. We 
want to come out this year and re-establish ourselves as a 
powerhouse, that Nebraska is a team to be reckoned with every 
week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cornhuskers will attempt to do that against a team that's a  
bit of a mystery to Solich, starting his second season as Tom 
Osborne's successor. 
</P>
<P>
	Fry coached Iowa for 20 years and opponents knew what to expect,  
to the point that critics chirped the Hawkeyes had become too 
predictable. While Ferentz worked under Fry in the 1980s, he has 
made several other stops and spent the last six seasons as an NFL 
assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Ferentz's assistants are new at Iowa, including the  
offensive and defensive coordinators. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have good athletes, a lot of speed,'' Davison said.  
``We're going to have to do a lot of play action and things like 
that to make things work on offense. We need to be prepared for 
about anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ferentz, on the other hand, knows what to expect from Nebraska.  
The Cornhuskers will hand the ball to their I-backs, they'll run 
some option with Newcombe, sprinkle in a few passes and depend on 
their offensive line to knock people down. The problem is stopping 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	That challenge alone should be enough to motivate his team,  
Ferentz said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this doesn't get our guys' motor going, I don't know what's  
going to,'' he said. ``There are a lot of positives about this 
thing. Hopefully, our guys will play hard and have a little fun 
with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska appears to have the tools to handle Iowa, which had the  
worst offense in the Big Ten last year and doesn't have much depth 
on defense. For starters, Newcombe and Evans are at full strength 
after injury-plagued seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Newcombe recovered from the torn knee ligament that kept him out  
of seven games last season, and he beat out Eric Crouch in a much 
publicized battle for the starting job. Crouch also runs the option 
well and will play in both halves Saturday, Solich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferentz said it wouldn't have made any difference who the  
Cornhuskers started. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were hoping neither one of them would be starters,  
actually, but that didn't work out,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans, slowed by groin, tailbone and toe injuries, has played in  
only three games since rushing for 776 yards in 1996, the 
third-best figure by a Nebraska freshman. He'll share time with Dan 
Alexander, who was impressive in preseason after running for 369 
yards in limited duty last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Sophomore Kyle McCann won a three-way duel to start at  
quarterback for Iowa. McCann started five games last season and 
completed 54 percent of his passes for 1,179 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferentz said McCann will be allowed to play through his  
mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plan is to let Kyle go and play,'' Ferentz said.  
``Obviously, we reserve the right to make a change at any time, but 
I think at the quarterback position, you don't want a guy out there 
peeking over his shoulder all the time. I don't think that's a 
healthy thing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
