<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Child Trapeze Swings Are Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government recalled about 60,000 trapeze  
swings Thursday after six children suffered serious cuts from 
exposed bolts. 
</P>
<P>
	The injuries occurred when children dropped down from an  
overhead ladder or fell or climbed onto the bolts, the Consumer 
Product Safety Commission said. The cuts on the children's arms 
required stitches. 
</P>
<P>
	The swings were sold as part of Backyard Products gym set,  
containing various other equipment, and has a wooden bar and rings. 
The bar is attached to the swing chains by a ``U-bolt'' bracket 
with bolts that are now considered too long. 
</P>
<P>
	Trapeze sets attached by a rope-type assembly are not included  
in the recall, the commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	Department, toy, discount, lumber and hardware stores nationwide  
sold the backyard gyms from December 1998 through July 1999 for 
$250 to $450. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers should stop using the trapeze swing immediately and  
call 888-446-0750 to order a free repair kit, the commission said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux's Penguins Takeover Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux owns six scoring titles, two  
Stanley Cup rings and several NHL records. Now, he also owns the 
Pittsburgh Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 2 1/2 years after playing his final game, Lemieux became  
the first retired player to own a major sports team for which he 
played. 
</P>
<P>
	It took U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz a few minutes  
Friday to complete a $95 million closing that gave the team to 
Lemieux, who turned around the once-troubled franchise and battled 
back from Hodgkin's disease. The deal ensured the Penguins will 
stay in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now the puck's on Mr. Lemieux's stick, and we've all seen what  
he's been able to do with that,'' Markovitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than an hour later, Lemieux appeared in a business suit and  
was introduced to the media as the new owner. He began his new 
career by lowering ticket prices on 3,500 seats at the Civic Arena 
and announcing the creation of a section of seats where families 
can buy tickets at reduced prices. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Craig Patrick will run the hockey side of the  
organization; Lemieux promised he will stay on the business side of 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless somebody wants to know what the Hall of Fame center has  
to say. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he wants me to, I'll be glad to give him my opinion,''  
Lemieux said, smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	There was little to smile about in the days leading up to final  
approval of the deal. Negotiations over a deal at the Civic Arena 
were breaking down with SMG, the Philadelphia-based group that 
leases the facility and rents space to the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was finalized in a conference call Wednesday among  
Lemieux's group, SMG, the governor's office and U.S. Sen. Rick 
Santorum. SMG will invest $5 million in the team and Lemieux will 
pay $1.5 million in debts to the arena management company. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG will lease space to the team until 2004, after which time  
SMG's role would be reduced -- if the team is still playing at the 
38-year-old facility. Lemieux said he wants a new facility, but 
said it was not an immediate priority. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one thing to bring the team out of bankruptcy,'' Lemieux  
said. ``We have to make it viable now. Hopefully, we can make this 
a great success story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SMG attorney Daniel Shapira said the two parties, who have had a  
rocky relationship, would be forced to get along now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, the Penguins will thrive and survive in  
Pittsburgh,'' Shapira said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last October, former co-owner Roger Marino took the franchise  
into bankruptcy court for protection from creditors. Lemieux, who 
had sued Marino for some $30 million in salary by the Penguins, 
became the head of a committee of creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	A few months later, he was putting together a bid for the team.  
</P>
<P>
	On June 24, Markovitz -- whose only options were to approve the  
Lemieux plan or sign off on an alternative proposal that could have 
moved the franchise -- gave Lemieux the go-ahead. Lemieux said at 
the time he felt ``like a rookie again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux has more than a dozen investors in his group, with about  
$52 million raised so far. He has the largest stake of all the 
owners, most of it coming in the deferred salary he was owed from 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a businessman just yet, but everyone can learn,''  
Lemieux said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins begin training camp Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a new era,'' said Patrick, adding he was worried about  
the prospect of starting training camp without the deal being 
finalized. ``I was afraid if this wasn't done, where the funds were 
coming from.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to be back,'' Lemieux said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 09:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates World Series Trophy Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Someone made off with the gold World Series  
trophy won in 1979 by the Pittsburgh Pirates, but it turned up 
today behind a church. 
</P>
<P>
	A 12-year-old boy was doing cleanup work at the church found it  
in a black plastic bag outside the back door, said Detective Donald 
Pasquarelli. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Mark Ninehouser said two pennants were missing from the  
trophy -- the Boston Red Sox and the Oakland Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said they still don't know who took the trophy or  
how it disappeared from the lobby of the Allegheny Club at Three 
Rivers Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe somebody's conscience was bothering them and they  
decided to turn it in,'' Pasquarelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exception of events like the annual Pirates Fest in  
March and the grand opening of Lazarus department store last year, 
the trophy has rarely left the stadium since it was donated by the 
Galbreath family, former owners of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	But sometime between 5:15 and 6 p.m. Wednesday during a private  
corporate party at the club, the trophy disappeared from an 
unlocked glass display case. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities and a memorabilia expert estimate the value of the  
trophy at $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think it was a guest,'' club president Kevin Vaughn  
said. ``What we think is that someone somehow got into the club and 
just walked out with it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 00:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Day of New Umps Goes Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Baseball games went on, even without the 22  
umpires who lost their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours after the departures of the veterans became official  
at 6 a.m. Thursday, an opponent of the union leadership said the 
other umps might be locked out until next summer unless Richie 
Phillips is toppled. 
</P>
<P>
	And there was a chance one more umpire would join the 22. NL  
umpire Steve Rippley called the league office and said he was 
thinking of resigning, according to several management officials 
who spoke on the condition they not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The 16-year veteran didn't quit Thursday, NL senior vice  
president Katy Feeney said, but it was unclear if he had made any 
final decision. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no problems involving the 25 new umpires during  
Thursday's eight games, and none of the veteran umps who kept their 
jobs walked out in sympathy with the terminated 22, whose best 
chance to get back on the field is winning in arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	Marty Foster, who became a permanent AL ump earlier in the day,  
ejected Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild during an argument in 
the sixth inning of Thursday night's game at Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was fine,'' Rothschild said. ``He gave me a chance to walk  
away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Cuzzi, one of 13 new NL umps, was among three newcomers in  
his four-man crew for the Phillies-Giants game in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult,'' he said. ``I have the plate today. I'm going  
out to work the best that I can. I don't know what to expect from 
the other guys. We have a young guy coming up from Triple-A. He's 
never worked a game in the big leagues before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That umpire, Jim Wolf, was called up from the minors as a  
fill-in for union president Jerry Crawford, who was with Phillips 
on Tuesday and Wednesday at federal court in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	The first game for Wolf, who isn't among the 25 permanent new  
umps, involved the Phillies, for whom his brother, Randy, pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have butterflies big-time,'' Jim Wolf said. ``I've got a  
swarm in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal agreed to Wednesday night in Philadelphia,  
the 22 stopped work, but will be paid for the rest of the year. 
Whether they resigned, as owners say, or were fired, as the union 
says, will be decided by an arbitrator at a date not yet 
determined. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia branch of the American Arbitration Association  
gave each side a list of 15 arbitrators Thursday. If umpires and 
owners can't agree on one, they will take turns crossing out names 
until only one remains. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's lawyers are expected to try to convince the  
arbitrator not to decide the case, arguing that even if umps were 
terminated, their labor contract leaves those decisions up to 
league presidents, with no appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the 22 umps, managers weren't sure what to expect in the  
season's remaining 4 1/2 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The quality may not be what we're used to,'' New York Yankees  
manager Joe Torre said. ``Ideally, you would like to understand 
what the young umpires are going through. But if something happens 
in the eighth inning of a close game, you throw that all out the 
window.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AL ump Joe Brinkman, a leader of the group trying to replace  
Phillips, predicted owners would lock out umpires on Jan. 1, just 
as they did in 1995 when the previous labor deal expired. 
</P>
<P>
	``If nothing changes, I don't see us going back to work next  
season until June or July,'' Brinkman said. ``If Richie is gone, 
then that will change considerably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It appears opponents will attempt to petition the National Labor  
Relations Board to form a new union, according to several baseball 
lawyers who spoke on the condition they not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty percent or more of eligible union members are needed to  
petition the NLRB to conduct an organization election. Depending on 
whether the 22 count, there are either 71 or 93 umpires, meaning 22 
or 28 umpires are needed on a petition. Ultimately, the NLRB 
determines who is eligible to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``My negotiator is still Richie Phillips and will be Richie  
Phillips, and it won't change,'' said Ed Montague, an NL ump who 
kept his job. 
</P>
<P>
	The umpires' departures resulted from the union's failed  
strategy of mass resignations, designed to force an early start to 
negotiations for a contract to replace the labor deal that expires 
Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of negotiating, baseball accepted the 22 resignations  
and hired 25 replacements from the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a brand-new crew put together, and the first time we've  
worked together as a crew,'' AL ump Dan Morrison said after his 
game in Baltimore on Thursday night. ``It's like starting all 
over.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
