<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 3, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Palestinian: Mideast Deal Is OK'd  
</P>
<P>
	GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians have  
overcome their last disagreements and forged a new West Bank 
land-for-security accord, a Palestinian cabinet minister said 
today. The agreement will be signed tomorrow, Palestinian Planning 
Minister Nabil Shaath told reporters as Palestinian leader Yasser 
Arafat and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright wrapped up 
their talks. The deal would restart a long-delayed West Bank 
pullback by Israel and release of Palestinian prisoners and could 
clear the way for an overall peace accord within a year. 

</P>
<P>
	8 Die in Small Plane Crash in Fla.  
</P>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Eight people aboard a twin-engine  
plane died today when the craft clipped a building and burst into 
flames while trying to make an emergency landing in the dark. No 
one on the ground was injured. The pilot of the Beechcraft King Air 
BE-90 bound from Michigan to Boca Raton, called the control tower 
for permission to land at Palm Beach International Airport around 
3:30 a.m. Moments later, there were two calls of ``mayday,'' and 
then the fiery crash about a half-mile from the runway, on airport 
property. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Charged in MIT Laughing Gas Death  
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- A student and a recent graduate were  
charged today in connection with the death of a Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology student who inhaled laughing gas. The pair 
face charges stemming from the distribution of illegal drugs from 
the dorm room where Richard A. Guy was found dead Tuesday, MIT 
Police Chief Anne Glavin said. The complaint lists charges that 
include possession of nitrous oxide, hallucinogenic mushrooms, 
amphetamines and marijuana, all with intent to distribute. The pair 
also face charges of conspiracy, possession of a hypodermic needle 
and cruelty to animals, cats. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Predicts Lower Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Blaming struggling foreign economies that have  
impeded sales overseas, The Coca-Cola Co. said today that 
third-quarter earnings will fall short of expectations. The company 
predicted earnings per share will be 34 cents to 35 cents this 
quarter, compared with analysts' predictions of 36 cents. It also 
said it will reduce earnings by an additional 2 cents to 3 cents a 
share because of the recall stemming from a health scare linked to 
Coke in Belgium and France. The news didn't go over well with 
investors, causing Coke's stock price to drop nearly 5 percent in 
afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Soars 223, Nasdaq Surges 93  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks surged higher today after the  
government's employment report showed the U.S. economy added jobs 
at a slower-than-expected pace and that wage growth moderated in 
August, helping to ease fears about rising inflation. Just before 4 
p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 204.85 at 
11,048.62. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 34.27 at 
1,353.38, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 95.68 at 2,829.92. 

</P>
<P>
	Diana Investigation Said Complete  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A two-year investigation into the car crash that  
killed Princess Diana apparently has ended as a French judge 
dismissed charges against nine photographers and a press 
motorcyclist, judicial sources said today. Judge Herve Stephan said 
the accident was the result of an intoxicated driver, Henri Paul, 
who also was taking drugs incompatible with alcohol, the sources 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	New Mexico Moves Inmates to Va.  
</P>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- New Mexico transferred 109 inmates to a  
super-maximum-security prison in Virginia today after a guard was 
stabbed to death in an uprising at a privately run prison. The new 
Wallens Ridge Correctional Facility, a state prison in Big Stone 
Gap, Va., was chosen because it is designed to hold the most 
dangerous of inmates. The inmates were transferred from the 
Guadalupe County Correctional Facility, where prisoners took over 
common living areas for three hours Tuesday before authorities 
regained control. 

</P>
<P>
	Rusedski Moves Ahead at Open  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Britain's Greg Rusedski, who reached the U.S.  
Open final two years ago, moved into the third round today by 
pounding out a 6-4, 6-3, 6-1 victory over Germany's David Prinosil. 
In women's singles, Germany's Anke Huber upset eighth-seeded Jana 
Novotna 6-3, 6-2; Mary Joe Fernandez of Miami ousted No. 13 
Dominique Van Roost of Belgium 7-5, 6-0; and No. 10 Arantxa 
Sanchez-Vicario defeated Switzerland's Patty Schnyder 6-2, 6-2. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  







  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
