<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 00:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Contridicts Pan Am Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- President Fidel Castro took the offensive today on  
recent scandals involving Cuban athletes, saying his country's own 
investigation shows that gold medalists who tested positive for 
drugs at last month's Pan American games were the victims of a 
plot. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was all a colossal lie, an infamous and shameful lie, a  
criminal plundering of merits won through denial, tenacity, 
consecration and sacrifice,'' the Cuban leader said during a 
much-anticipated three-hour appearance on live national television 
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Castro called for the unusual television program, which included  
the presence of 14 foreign journalists and five Cuban journalists. 
No questions will be allowed until the completion of the second 
half of the program, scheduled to resume tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday night, Castro, a leading sports official and a top  
sports doctor said that multiple urine tests of weightlifters 
William Vargas and Rolando Delgado conducted by Cuba and sent to 
three different laboratories in Europe all tested negative for the 
anabolic steroid Nandrolone. The tests were done four to five days 
after the two returned to the island from the games, the Cuban 
president said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, urine tests analyzed by a Canadian lab during the games  
in Winnipeg showed Vargas and Delgado testing positive for the 
drug. Steroids are injected into the body to increase strength and 
bulk and can remain in a person's system for months. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the 20 samples analyzed by three laboratories there was not  
a single reported presence of Nandrolone or its traces, not a 
single athlete in our weightlifting team was using drugs,'' Castro 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Castro also defended high jump world champion Javier Sotomayor,  
who was stripped of his gold medal at the Pan Am games after 
testing positive for cocaine. The test, Castro said, was the result 
of a ``dirty political war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Castro questioned how the urine tests for Sotomayor and other  
Cubans were conducted at the games. The Cubans were required to 
drink water or other ``refreshing drinks'' before their tests and 
were given their tests in a room apart from athletes from other 
countries, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban officials have suggested that someone slipped the cocaine  
into Sotomayor's food or drink before the test, which was given 
shortly after won his fourth straight Pan Am gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be ``absurd'' to believe that Sotomayor consumed  
cocaine before that feat, because the large quantity found in his 
system would surely have impeded his performance, the Cuban 
president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban officials have become increasingly frustrated by what they  
believe is an orchestrated campaign by their enemies to discredit 
the communist country and its long respected sports program. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Pan Am games, they complained about Canadian news  
media that joked about and encouraged its athletes to defect. 
</P>
<P>
	The speech followed a dispute last week in Houston at an  
International Amateur Boxing Association Championship event. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges initially awarded welterweight Timour Gaidalov of Russia  
a gold medal over Juan Hernandez of Cuba, setting off an angry 
protest by Cubans. Four of the five judges were later suspended by 
the AIBA's executive committee and the decision was reversed in 
favor of Hernandez. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 10:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Canada Opens Francophone Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONCTON, New Brunswick (AP) -- Canada welcomed leaders from  
French-influenced countries to a three-day summit today, urging 
them to make human rights and democratic values their main goals 
heading into the 21st century. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic development can only exist when there is peace, and  
basic freedoms are the foundations of peaceful societies, Canadian 
Prime Minister Jean Chretien told an opening ceremony for La 
Francophonie, an organization of French-speaking or 
French-influenced countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Human rights has become a significant issue at La Francophonie's  
three-day summit in this eastern Canadian city, primarily because 
many of the francophone nations attending -- Congo, Burundi and 
Burkina Faso, for example -- are reported by rights organizations to 
be among the worst violators of basic freedoms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let us all work to ensure that the legacy we leave to future  
generations is a Francophonie made up of countries where democratic 
values are embraced,'' Chretien told the 52 delegates, many of them 
heads of state. 
</P>
<P>
	The francophone organization is intended to promote and maintain  
French language and culture, primarily among many of France's 
former colonies in Africa. At the 1997 Hanoi summit, though, 
delegates decided to broaden their mission to also include more 
political and economic issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Rights activists are urging it to broaden its role further,  
putting human rights on the official agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	The topic's absence from this year's agenda prompted groups like  
Amnesty International to stage their own parallel summit on the eve 
of the opening, decrying the presence of rights violators in Canada 
and the failure of La Francophonie to do anything about the issue 
that affects so many members. 
</P>
<P>
	The parallel summit put forward a list of demands asking that  
such issues as poverty, torture, political executions, sexual 
mutilation of women and the use of children as workers and warriors 
be meaningfully discussed. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the welcoming ceremony at the University of Moncton, a  
few dozen protesters carried signs demanding Burundi's president, 
Pierre Buyoya, who staged a coup during the last francophone summit 
in Canada in 1987, be tried by an international criminal tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Canada is a country of justice,'' said Ferdinand Ngendabanka,  
chairman of a Burundian community group in Ottawa. ``They make 
justice in Kosovo, Bosnia, they should do it for countries in 
Africa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	French President Jacques Chirac said the francophone  
organization shouldn't take any steps to sanction members, but 
should be able to exclude those who seriously violate rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be well imagined that the people that don't respect  
certain rules won't be accepted in the club by people who respect 
the rules,'' he said in an interview Thursday night with 
Radio-Canada, the French-language network of the Canadian 
Broadcasting Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	France has proposed that the Francophone organization take on a  
monitoring role to make sure its former colonies are respecting 
international norms of human rights. Also, the organization is 
planning to set up a series of international conferences over the 
coming year on human rights in collaboration with the Commonwealth 
of English-speaking countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990903.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 10:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
