<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-03 14:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Drops to 4.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unemployment edged down to 4.2 percent last  
month, returning to a 29-year low, as a pre-Labor Day government 
report Friday spelled good news for job seekers without re-igniting 
inflation jitters on Wall Street. Financial markets soared on the 
news and ended the week on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the drop in the unemployment rate, businesses added a  
smaller-than-expected 124,000 jobs to payrolls in August, after a 
gain of 338,000 jobs in July, and reported moderate wage growth, 
the Labor Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists and investors viewed the developments as signs that  
job growth is slowing to a more sustainable pace, and wages are 
growing slowly enough to keep from touching off inflation. And 
that, economists said, could persuade the Federal Reserve to sit 
tight and not raise interest rates again at its Oct. 5 meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets, which have been nervous about prospects of a  
third rate increase, were buoyed by August's unemployment report. 
The Dow Jones industrial average at 11,078.45, up 235.24. The 
Nasdaq composite index rose 108.34 to close at 2,842.58, according 
to preliminary calculations, surpassing the previous high for a 
one-day point gain, 103.16, set on June 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The inflation-sensitive market for government bonds also  
rallied, pushing yields on 30-year Treasuries down to 6.01 percent 
from 6.13 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report ``casts doubt on the need for another rate  
increase,'' said David Wyss, an economist with Standard and Poor's 
DRI. ``The economy is slowing down by itself, and inflation isn't a 
problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While low unemployment and strong wage growth appear to be good  
developments for workers, economists worry that it can be a recipe 
for sparking inflation. Their fear: Employers scrambling to find 
workers must woo them with higher wages and benefits, costs likely 
to drive up consumer prices if not constrained by other forces. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, economists were heartened that average hourly  
earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures, grew a tiny 0.2 
percent to $13.30 in August, a 3.5 percent increase compared with a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the third consecutive monthly rise, slightly slower  
than July's revised 0.3 percent increase. The government's previous 
estimate was that average hourly earnings rose 0.5 percent in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``With wage inflation running at a 3.5 percent year-over-year  
pace, the argument for another Fed rate hike just doesn't make 
sense,'' said Richard Yamarone, an economist with Argus Research 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists said August's unemployment report substantially  
reduces the odds of an Oct. 5 rate increase by the Fed. They didn't 
close the door to a rate increase in November, which would that 
depend on what additional economic data has to say about the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the Federal Reserve raised interest rates for a  
second time this year and hinted that additional rate increases may 
not be necessary unless the economy shows signs of overheating or 
if inflation breaks out. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4.2 percent jobless rate in August, which followed a 4.3  
percent rate in July, matched May's level. Before that, 
unemployment last touched 4.2 percent in February 1970. The 
economic expansion, the longest in peacetime history, has given the 
country a low overall unemployment rate. 
</P>
<P>
	``On Labor Day 1999 we have much to celebrate,'' said Labor  
Secretary Alexis Herman. ``American workers have opportunities 
unlike any they have had before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 124,000 jobs created in August occurred as gains in  
computer, data processing, health care and other jobs helped offset 
continued job losses at factories. Many economists expected around 
210,000 jobs to be created last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of service sector jobs increased by 132,000, led by  
gains in computer services which grew by 15,000 jobs. Doctors' 
offices, hospitals and other health-care facilities added 19,000 
new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall retail employment held about steady. Bars and  
restaurants dropped 38,000 jobs, but jobs added at car dealers and 
furniture stores helped offset that decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers, still feeling the lingering affects of the global  
financial crisis, cut 63,000 jobs in August. That more than wiped 
out an increase of 51,000 jobs in July. But Herman said she's 
optimistic about manufacturing's future because she said the rate 
of job loss is slowing. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction jobs, meanwhile, declined by 29,000, largely  
offsetting gains in the previous two months. Economists said job 
losses in construction as well as in other businesses could reflect 
that employers are having trouble finding qualified people in the 
tight labor market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
