<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Court Asked To Review Twins Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The threat of a move to North Carolina  
has been dead more than a year, but the Minnesota Twins might still 
be the target of an investigation into whether baseball conspired 
to get public money for a new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Mike Hatch wants the U.S. Supreme Court to  
review a state Supreme Court decision that blocked such an 
investigation in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch's predecessor, Hubert H. Humphrey III, launched the  
inquiry in 1997, when Twins owner Carl Pohlad was negotiating with 
a buyer who wanted to move the team to North Carolina. A sale 
agreement was to be signed only if the Legislature refused to help 
pay for a new ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is important to pursue the possibility that the independent  
owners of baseball may be threatening to boycott communities which 
do not increase public subsidies for ballparks,'' Hatch said in a 
statement Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Organized baseball, unlike any other sport or industry, claims  
to have a complete and blanket exemption from antitrust laws,'' 
Hatch said. ``The state of Minnesota believes it has the right to 
look at professional baseball to see if they have violated 
antitrust laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twins president Jerry Bell said the organization was surprised  
by Hatch's request because the state Supreme Court decision was 
unanimous. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said neither the Twins nor major league baseball could  
be forced to comply with the investigation. Humphrey had asked for 
papers going back to 1959 to determine whether baseball officials 
illegally conspired by threatening to move franchises. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins and the commissioner's office argued their conduct was  
exempt from state and federal antitrust laws because the U.S. 
Supreme Court held in 1922 that professional baseball was not 
interstate commerce and was exempt. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court followed that decision in its April  
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We conclude that the sale and relocation of a baseball  
franchise ... is an integral part of the business of professional 
baseball and falls within the exemption,'' Justice Paul H. Anderson 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson wrote that the exemption ``may be an aberration''  
carved out by the U.S. Supreme Court, but the nation's highest 
court should retain the exclusive privilege of overruling its own 
decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Supreme Court reviews only a fraction of the cases that  
come through its office. 
</P>
<P>
	Humphrey's request was for all documents related to revenue  
sharing, potential relocation and sale of major league baseball 
teams, and the construction and methods for obtaining new ballparks 
in Minnesota and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's an historic time for the court to take this  
case,'' said Jim Jacobson, assistant attorney general who manages 
the antitrust division. ``A number of factors are all coming 
together.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
